<1ST_LINE>r w PM-DeafSchool-President Bjt   03-12 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Deaf School-President, Bjt,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zinser Says Student Uprising Was Unforeseen</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos WX7, WX8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The woman who resigned as head of Gallaudet
University after angry student protests says officials didn't
foresee that having a deaf president would become ``a national
civil rights matter.''
   Elisabeth Ann Zinser, who can hear and does not know sign
language, said a week of outcry over her appointment at the school
for the deaf made her see that deaf people as a group must ``take
their place in society and this had become the time.''
   ``I have responded to this extraordinary social movement of deaf
people, not to the demands of the students and protesters,'' she
said.
   ``As the search progressed and as we got to the point of
actually making the offer to me, the situation was becoming more
intense, but they still did not perceive that it would end up
becoming a national civil rights matter,'' she said.
   She said she resigned when she realized how deeply the deaf
community felt about the Gallaudet presidency as a symbol.
   ``I eventually began to really believe what was being said here
on the part of that community,'' she said.
   The 124-year-old school is the only liberal arts university for
the deaf in the world, but has never had a deaf president.
   About 2,500 students and supporters rallied at the Capitol after
Zinser resigned, claiming victory, but insisting that they would
not stop until their demand for a deaf president is met.
   The students say they want the president chosen from the two
deaf finalists from Sunday.
   The students want Jane Bassett Spilman, chairwoman of the board
to resign, a deaf majority on the board, and guarantees that there
would be no reprisals against any of the demonstrators.
   Virtually all 2,200 graduate and undergraduate students at
Gallaudet participated in the week-long protests.
   ``We're still winning. We're still winning,'' said student
leader Jerry Covell. He said he was pleased that Zinser had
resigned, but he urged the students to continue their battle.
   Gary Olsen, executive director of the National Association of
the Deaf, told the students their protests had helped the cause of
deaf people nationwide.
   Truman Stelle, a Gallaudet faculty member, said, ``It is long
past time that Gallaudet had a deaf president, as testimony that
deaf people are capable of leading themselves.''
   Stelle said the ouster of Spilman was important because ``she
clearly sees herself as owner of the Gallaudet plantation,
answerable to no one.''
   At a news conference earlier Friday, Spilman criticized the
``external interests of people who perhaps are not as interested or
involved in the day-to-day operations of Gallaudet and not as well
informed as the board and the administration.'' She did not
elaborate.
   Zinser, who was vice chancellor of the University of North
Carolina at Greensboro, had never formally submitted her
resignation there, and University of North Carolina system
President C.D. Spangler said she would be welcome back.
   The House Education and Labor Committee's subcommittee on select
education, which has jurisdiction over funding for Gallaudet, has
scheduled hearings for Tuesday to review the makeup of the board
and the controversy over the presidential selection. Three-quarters
of the school's $76 million operating budget comes from the federal
government.
   And John Banzhaff, George Washington University law professor
and founder of the National Center for Law and the Deaf, has filed
a complaint with the District of Columbia Office of Human Rights
charging the board with unlawful discrimination for never hiring a
deaf president.
</TEXT>
