<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Salvador-March 1stLd-Writethru a0867 03-12 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-March, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0867,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Car Bombs Explode in Capital</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with car bombs in capital. Picks
up 3rd graf pvs, ``There were ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two car bombs exploded in the
fashionable ``pink zone'' strip of restaurants and night clubs
Friday, injuring one boy and scattering dinner customers, witnesses
said.
   The explosions occurred about 9:30 p.m., several hours after
about 400 union activists marched through the capital to demand
that the Salvadoran government free a detained labor leader.
   The car bombs damaged five private cars and shattered windows in
three businesses, the witnesses said.
   The boy had minor head and arm injuries but did not appear to be
seriously hurt.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility for the explosions.
   Leftist guerrillas assumed responsibility for a machine-gun
attack in the same district June 19, 1985, in which 13 people,
including four off-duty U.S. Embassy Marine guards and two American
businessmen, were killed.
   In the march earlier Friday, one demonstrator was wounded by a
gunshot in the leg when other demonstrators identified an
undercover security agent in their ranks and confronted him. The
man pulled a pistol, shot a demonstrator and ran off.
   There were no confrontations with police or soldiers along the
five-mile march route. Uniformed security forces were not in sight.
   The demonstrators, many of whom carried nail-studded wooden
clubs and iron bars, asked passengers to get off about 10 buses
along the march route, then deflated the bus tires so the vehicles
blocked side streets.
   A pickup truck was set afire near the U.S. Embassy, where the
marchers stopped for 30 minutes to denounce U.S. support for the
Salvadoran government.
   Protesters painted the walls around the embassy with
anti-American slogans, and set a stack of tires afire.
   The demonstrators demanded the release of Humberto Centeno, the
leader of the telecommunications workers union, who was arrested
Thursday night.
   The union members alleged Centeno was badly beaten by the troops
who arrested him, and that he was hospitalized.
   The government acknowledged Centeno's arrest but claimed he
tried to attack a member of the security forces. It made no mention
of his condition.
   Centeno was arrested after about 50 union members occupied the
Labor Ministry for nine hours Thursday, demanding higher pay and
reinstatement of fired workers.
   Several metal boxes containing telephone line connections were
pried open during Friday's march, doused with gasoline, and set
ablaze, leaving dozens of city blocks without phone service.
</TEXT>
