<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Fashion     03-12 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Fashion,0672</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Designers: Princess Plus Cheeky and Classic Fashions Spell Success</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Take trend-setting Princess Diana, mix in a
fashion collection that's cheeky and classic, long and short, and
British designers hope to have the perfect ingredients for a
smashing autumn season.
   Conscious of the lingering effects of the October stock market
crash and Britain's soaring pound, London's top designers have
abandoned the silly and unsaleable for a massive dose of realism _
what Alastair Blair calls ``just adult grown-up clothes.''
   There is still plenty of individuality and a little zaniness _
Vivian Westwood's mini-crinoline skirt topped with a peplum and
under-bust waistcoat _ but overall the fall collections launched
Friday were eminently wearable.
   The four-day London show attracting more than 6,000 buyers has
become a regular stop on the international fashion circuit,
sandwiched between the Milan and Paris shows. The clothing and
textile industry is Britain's third-largest export earner, with
clothing exports alone totaling $2.4 billion.
   Princess Diana, one of the industry's biggest boosters, hopes to
give Britain's designers an edge over foreign rivals with a
reception Monday night at her home in Kensington Palace for 200
buyers, designers and fashion journalists.
   Edina Ronay, a favorite designer of the princess and her
sister-in-law, the Duchess of York, said: ``It's one-up on any
other country that doesn't have a royal family that the whole world
knows about.''
   Blair, another royal favorite, said of the princess: ``I think
she's 98 percent responsible for the revival of interest in British
fashion and I think what she's doing is terrific.''
   Like the Italians, Britain's designers couldn't decide whether
hems should be long or short so they offered both with plenty of
trousers, mainly wide, as well as some slimmer jodhpurs, breeches
and Dickensian stovepipes.
   Several British designers also picked up on the Italian
fascination with ``ecological furs.'' Arabella Pollen, who did a
circus theme, had fake leopard and zebra mini-suits and Antony
Price did brocade suits and frock coats trimmed in fake mink.
   Ronay's designs went Edwardian. Wendy Dagworthy also explored
``retro themes of Edwardian and late Forties'' and Betty Jackson
did hourglass Edwardian jackets in a collection she called ``a
complete mix-up ... which I love.''
   The new realism of British fashion, the designers said, means
choice, quality and price-consciousness.
   ``I think it's luxury dressing ... it's beautiful fabrics, it's
opulent,'' said David Sassoon of Belville Sassoon.
   ``And then there's a contradiction, well almost, with lots of
trousers _ they're suddenly important again and they don't pose a
length problem. Women who don't know whether to go long or short
will opt for pants,'' he said.
   Betty Jackson's collection was nearly all pants, wide and slim.
Rifat Ozbek designed a clinging wool jersey jumpsuit with a tiny
draped mini-skirt over it. Bruce Oldfield said shapes were more
important than lengths _ and he's doing bell skirts.
   Benny Ong, who showed silks with short bell skirts as well as
long tubular dresses, said: ``I think women want to look younger
but without looking silly. Give them a choice, but maintain their
integrity.''
   Blair echoed that view, showing long and short skirts. ``I think
women who do spend money on clothes are fed up that they have to
look like 18-year-olds. You have to give people a choice.'' he said.
   With flounces and full skirts outmoded, Blair said he was able
to use less fabric and cut the cost of his daywear by 25 percent
and his evening gowns by 17 percent _ a plus in the current
financial climate.
   Gina Fratini, whose black velvet cocktail dresses with ruffles
and dashes of hot pink, electric blue and turquoise were an instant
seller, said the stock market crash had made the designers ``come
out fighting.''
   ``I think the stock market crash, if anything, has brought the
fun clothes back because we want to cheer ourselves up,'' she said.
</TEXT>
