<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 0212EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     03-12 0825</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Department Funds Will Help Promote Salmon Exports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Agriculture Department export program is
helping Alaska promote salmon in Western Europe and Japan, two
lucrative U.S. farm markets where competition is rising.
   The department's Targeted Export Assistance program, popularly
called TEA, has allocated $1.95 million this fiscal year for the
Alaska Seafood Marketing Institute, a quasi-independent commission
of the state's Department of Commerce and Economic Development.
   According to a USDA list of trade organizations sharing in the
program, the only other comparable group is the Catfish Farmers of
America, which was allocated $50,000.
   Department officials said each TEA plan is negotiated with the
sponsoring group. Some put up money to match or exceed the federal
contribution, while others contribute less than TEA provides.
   Total funding of TEA, which was authorized by the Food Security
Act of 1985, was pegged at a minimum of $110 million annually.
About 40 different commodities, including Alaskan seafood, share in
the program.
   As directed by Congress, the purpose of TEA is to finance
promotional activities for U.S. agricultural products that have
been put to a disadvantage by subsidies and unfair trade policies
of competitor nations.
   The institute is ready to pit Alaska salmon against pen-raised
salmon from Norway being promoted in France and Japan, according to
Roberta Graham of Evans-Kraft Bean, an Anchorage public relations
firm representing the institute.
   Alaska processors also are attending trade fairs and food shows
in Tokyo and Paris to promote salmon, Ms. Graham said this week
(Thursday) during a visit to Washington.
   ``You have the Corn Belt and the Wheat Belt,'' she said. ``I
choose to call Alaska the Fish Belt.''
   The importance of fishing to the Alaskan economy cannot be
understated, she said. It's second only to the oil, generating $900
million for the state's economy last year.
   In the first year of the TEA program, the Alaskans got $1.5
million from USDA. The 1988 allocation, according to March 1
figures by the department's Foreign Agricultural Service, is $1.95
million, making a two-year total of $3.45 million.
   But no matter how important fishing is to Alaska, the state's
TEA allocation is a small part of the program's overall budget for
the fiscal year that began on Oct. 1. Some other commodities
qualified for much higher shares.
   The largest single TEA allocation this year is $10.5 million to
promote citrus from Arizona and California. The American Soybean
Association followed with $9.8 million. The U.S. Feed Grains
Council got $2.4 million, and U.S. Wheat Associates, $1.2 million.
   California, the nation's leading producer of agricultural
products in terms of value, qualifies for the largest share of TEA
money. The 1988 allocations, for example, include six different
California state commissions and boards affecting: avocados,
$450,000; cling peaches, $5.7 million; kiwifruit, $500,000; prunes,
$5.5 million; raisins, $9.8 million; and table grapes, $750,000.
   As the main producer of almonds, California also benefits from
$6.5 million of TEA money allocated for that crop this year. The
Walnut Marketing Board gets $6.5 million to promote walnuts
overseas, another California crop.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The keynote speaker for the Agriculture
Department's conference on quality of farm products will be U.S.
Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter.
   The meeting will be held in St. Louis, Mo., June 29 through July
1, said Assistant Secretary Kenneth A. Gilles.
   Gilles said Friday that the conference ``will focus on
maintaining a quality advantage for American agriculture in the
highly competitive domestic and international marketplace.''
   Subject matter will include cereals, oilseeds, fruits and nuts,
vegetables, red meat, poultry, industrial crops, dairy, tobacco,
cotton, wool, horticulture and forage crops.
   ``The major audience for this conference is farm organizations,
farm market development organizations, agribusiness, wholesalers,
retailers, trade associations, agriculturally related industries,
and the agricultural higher-education community,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department is adding the
Simbrah Association to its list of registered cattle breeds so
owners can qualify for higher federal payments when animals are
slaughtered under the department's brucellosis eradication program.
   Brucellosis is a highly contagious disease, said James W.
Glosser, acting administrator of the department's Animal and Plant
Health Inspection Service.
   ``Our experience has shown that indemnities encourage owners to
remove infected animals from their herds to prevent the spread of
the disease.''
   Brucellosis can be passed on to humans _ where it is known as
undulant fever _ through raw milk from infected cows.
   Simbrah cattle are a cross between Simmental and Brahman, the
department said. Approximately 2,200 U.S. producers own registered
Simbrah cattle.
   To receive federal indemnities for registered cattle, the owner
must present a certificate of registration as proof that the animal
belonged to one of the 61 USDA-listed breed associations.
   The indemnity rate for all dairy cattle, and registered beef
cattle and bison is $250 per animal, while the payment for
non-registered beef and bison is $50 per animal.
   Officials said the new rule goes into effect on April 11.
</TEXT>
