<DOCNO> AP880312-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 0230EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CapitalGains     03-12 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Capital Gains,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBO Says Lowering Capital Gains Rate Wouldn't Produce Revenue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional analysts are challenging
President Reagan's contention that a capital-gains tax cut would
reduce the federal budget deficit.
   Although boosting the tax rate probably would produce less
revenue, the Congressional Budget Office concluded that most
evidence indicates that a lower rate would also result in a revenue
loss. The study estimated that loss at $3.9 billion to $7.8 billion
a year if the top rate on long-term capital gains were lowered from
33 percent to 15 percent.
   Some advocates estimate the government would collect as much as
$15 billion a year more under a 15 percent cut because the lower
rate would encourage people to sell long-held assets.
   CBO researchers cautioned against putting too much faith in any
prediction of how taxpayers might react to changes. There are so
many uncertainties, the study said, ``that one cannot reject the
possibility that a 15 percent rate might increase revenues.'' But
the CBO said that is unlikely.
   As part of the massive revision of federal income taxes in 1986,
Congress eliminated the long-time preferential treatment accorded
capital gains, which are profits from the sale of stocks, real
estate and other assets owned more than six months. That action
raised the top rate on capital gains from 20 percent to 33 percent.
   In a written message to Congress on Jan. 25, Reagan said: ``The
most important piece of unfinished (tax) business is to reduce the
capital-gains tax rate to the level that will generate the savings
and investment necessary for future economic growth. Past
experience demonstrates that lowering the capital-gains tax rate
will mean increased realizations of capital gains upon which taxes
are paid.
   ``Reducing the capital-gains tax rate to an agreed-upon optimum
should be a cornerstone of tax reform for the 1990s,'' Reagan wrote.
   The president did not say how deeply the rate should be cut, but
the level mentioned most often by congressional advocates is 15
percent.
   There is considerable support in Congress for reducing the
maximum capital-gains rate. Advocates say this not only would raise
revenue _ by encouraging the sale of long-held assets _ but also
would encourage new investment.
   Opponents, noting that eliminating the capital-gains benefit was
a major factor in getting the 1986 tax law enacted, contend
restoring it would threaten that entire package.
   Most benefits of a capital-gains reduction would go to the
wealthiest Americans. The Internal Revenue Service estimates that
taxpayers with incomes of $100,000 or more account for 55 percent
of all capital gains but only 9 percent of other income.
   In a report to Chairman William Gray, D-Pa., of the House Budget
Committee, the CBO concluded that any increase in capital-gains
realizations _ the sale of assets _ was not likely to generate
enough revenue to offset a cut in the tax rate.
   In addition, the study said, restoring preferential treatment to
capital gains might reduce other forms of taxable income, such as
interest and dividends, because investments that created capital
gains would be made more attractive than other types.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880312-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 0232EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FBIAgent-Presser     03-12 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FBI Agent-Presser,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Upholds Suppression of Former FBI Agent's Statements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teamsters President Jackie Presser's attorney
says he's pleased with a ruling that prosecutors improperly
obtained statements from an FBI agent charged with lying about his
role in handling Presser as an informant.
   ``We look forward to a similar result in the Jackie Presser
case,'' attorney John Climaco said in an interview in Cleveland
Friday after an appeals court in Washington suppressed statements
that former Cleveland FBI agent Robert S. Friedrick allegedly made
to government prosecutors in early 1986.
   Friedrick was indicted in May 1986 on five counts of making
false statements that forced the government to delay for nearly a
year its planned prosecution of Presser.
   Presser, who has headed the 1.6 million-member Teamsters union
since 1983, was also indicted in May 1986. A grand jury in
Cleveland charged him with two counts of labor racketeering, one
count of embezzlement and two counts of filing false reports with
the government. His trial is set for July.
   Friedrick orginally said Presser had been authorized by his FBI
handlers to hire ``ghost employees'' at a Cleveland Teamsters union
local who did no work.
   The Justice Department wanted to prosecute Presser for the
alleged ghost hirings, but abandoned the investigation after
Friedrick's assertions.
   However, Friedrick admitted during the ensuing FBI-Justice
Department inquiry that his statements about authorizing the
illegal acts were false, according to tapes and transcripts
provided by the Justice Department. His alleged admissions revived
the Teamsters probe, which resulted in the indictment of Presser.
   Friedrick's attorney, William Beyer, said Friday's appeals court
decision eliminates the only evidence prosecutors have against his
client.
   ``I don't know of any other evidence that they have to support
their claim,'' Beyer said in a telephone interview from Cleveland.
   But Friedrick, who was fired from the FBI last August, succeeded
in having his alleged admissions suppressed as evidence by U.S.
District Judge George Revercomb on grounds that the Justice
Department interrogators had not advised him of his constitutional
right to remain silent.
   Clendon Lee, spokesman for the U.S. attorney's office in
Washington, declined comment.
   It was unclear what effect the decision would have on the
government's case against Presser.
   Stephen Jigger, head of the FBI strike force in Cleveland and
prosecutor in the Presser case, declined comment, saying he had not
yet received a copy of the court decision.
   During a June 26, 1985, interview at FBI headquarters in
Washington, Friedrick signed an FBI form that said he was required
to answer questions, but that the government could not use his
statements against him in a criminal prosecution as long as they
were true.
   During interviews the following January, Friedrick made
statements contradicting his previous assertion that Presser had
been authorized to put ghost employees on the local's payroll. The
next day he failed a lie detector test.
   The appellate court upheld Revercomb's finding that Friedrick
was not warned during the interview that statements he made could
be used against him.
   The prosecutors ``made a conscious decision prior to the
interview not to furnish Friedrick with or even mention (the FBI
form); indeed they hoped that Friedrick would make incriminating
statements that they could use against him in a subsequent
prosecution,'' the court said in an opinion by Judge Kenneth Starr.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
