<HEAD>Names In The News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY14</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sore jaw from a bout in the dentist's
chair has put Gov. Mario Cuomo out of action for a couple of days
and will probably cause him to skip a Gridiron-style dinner, his
press secretary says.
   The governor's dental work Friday was nothing serious but was
enough for him to be told to ``lay low'' through today, said Gary
Fryer.
   As a result, Cuomo will probably skip an appearance tonight at
the annual Inner Circle dinner, a satirical look at New York City
politics and government staged by reporters, Fryer said.
   Fryer said he wasn't certain of the exact nature of the dental
work, but said Cuomo might have to return for more.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: Version moved sports wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MESA, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baseball player Steve Kiefer says he's lucky
to be alive after getting smacked with a beer bottle that cut his
neck.
   Kiefer, an infielder with the Milwaukee Brewers, suffered cuts
that required nearly 200 stitches after the incident Thursday night
at a night spot here.
   ``The doctor told me it was one-sixteenth of an inch from the
carotid artery,'' said Kiefer, 27. ``If it would have cut that, it
would have killed me. I feel lucky to be alive.''
   Delfino Neira, 28, of Bakersfield, Calif., was charged Friday
with aggravated assault. Police said there was an argument over a
woman's belt before Neira left the bar, and he returned later and
hit Kiefer with the bottle.
   Kiefer said he found a belt on the floor of the nightclub and
gave it to a woman who said it was hers.
   Shortly after that, Kiefer said, Neira ``came by and nudged me.
I didn't accost him. I just said `Excuse me.' '' Neira apparently
left the bar but returned about 45 minutes later.
   ``I don't recall any argument,'' Kiefer said. ``The police said
he was a friend of the girl who the belt belonged to. But I don't
see what that had to do with it, because I gave it back to her.''
   Kiefer was expected to return to team workouts Sunday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Kennedy clan has grown by one, with the
birth of a daughter to one of Sen. Edward M. Kennedy's nieces,
Victoria Lawford Pender.
   The 8-pound, 9-ounce baby, Alexandra Lawford Pender, is the 14th
great-grandchild of matriarch Rose Kennedy. She was born Friday at
Georgetown University Hospital, the senator's office said.
   Mrs. Pender, 29, is a daughter of Pat Kennedy Lawford and the
late actor Peter Lawford. Her husband, Robert, is a Washington
attorney.
   Both mother and child are doing well, officials said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lotfi Mansouri has quit as general director of
the Canadian Opera Company with a parting shot to the local
establishment, saying he would accept a similar post with the San
Francisco Opera.
   The Iranian-born Mansouri, who has had the Toronto post for 12
years, said he leaves the city with ``great sadness,'' but added,
``I am sick and tired of trying to justify the art form (here).''
   At a news conference Friday, he again expressed regret that the
Canadian company is not better supported by government funds and
that there still is no definite word on a proposed new opera-ballet
house in Toronto.
   He will take up his new post in January 1989, succeeding general
director Terence McEwen, who is retiring for health reasons. Both
men are 58.
   The San Francisco Opera, second in size on the continent to New
York's Metropolitan Opera, has a budget of $25 million, twice that
of the Canadian Opera Company.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rosa L. Parks, the 75-year-old heroine of the
civil rights movement, left Johns Hopkins Hospital with a new
pacemaker.
   Ms. Parks, a Detroit resident, received a pacemaker Tuesday and
was discharged Friday, said hospital spokesman Phil Kibak.
   Nearly 33 years ago, Ms. Parks refused to give up her seat to a
white man on a segregated bus in Montgomery, Ala. She was arrested,
and the black community retaliated by boycotting the buses.
   A national celebration in her honor is scheduled here in June.
