<1ST_LINE>u a AM-BrushFires 1stLd-Writethru a0739 03-12 0488</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brush Fires, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0739,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grass Fires Out of Control in West Texas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATE throughout with area of land burned by fire, official
saying fire might last four days, other quotes, color, smoke seen
in Fort-Worth-Dallas, Val Verde county fire, edits to tighten. No
pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters begged for help from
neighboring counties Friday in battling grass fires that seared a
60-mile swath across West Texas ranch land.
   ``The fire is out of control on all fronts,'' the Shackelford
County sheriff's office reported. ``We're pulling all our forces
back in to protect homes.''
   The fire killed an undetermined number of cattle, set hunting
camps ablaze, and destroyed at least one mobile home. Some of the
500 firefighters suffered minor burns and were overcome by smoke,
but no serious injuries were reported.
   The fire was reported within two or three miles of Albany, a
town of about 2,500 people, but evacuations were not immediately
ordered. Firefighters earlier burned ground near the town to divert
the main fire.
   ``It's just an inferno in the pastures. And with winds of 35
mph, a horse couldn't outrun it,'' said Albany resident Liston F.
Todd, who was helping build firebreaks to detour the blaze.
   The fire, which began Thursday, covered an area 60 miles long
and 25 miles wide over three counties, with at least a 20-mile wide
portion of the blaze out of control, officials said.
   Joe Fox, the Texas Forest Service official overseeing the
firefighting, said it could take four more days to finally put out
the fire. Smoke and haze reached the Fort Worth-Dallas area, more
than 120 miles east of the blaze.
   A U.S. Forest Service aircraft tanker was scheduled to fly over
the area Saturday morning, dumping up to 2,000 gallons of
fire-extinguishing chemicals.
   Shifting winds made it difficult to determine where the fire
would spread, and in some cases firefighters were nearly surrounded
by the swift flames.
   At least one firefighting bulldozer was caught and destroyed by
the fire. A TV news team was momentarily threatened by a line of
fire that suddenly changed course.
   Twenty volunteer fire departments sent men and equipment to the
area on Friday, a day after Gov. Bill Clements ordered 100 National
Guardsmen to help.
   They joined nearly two dozen Forest Service firefighters and the
crews of 15 fire deparments. Police radios crackled with pleas for
more equipment and manpower to battle the blazes.
   Texas Forest Service spokesman Sam Logan said there had been
speculation that trash fires may have sparked the blazes when
humidity dipped to 7 percent Thursday. ``We consider anything below
30 percent is really dangerous.''
   Meanwhile, a blaze broke out in Val Verde County about 200 miles
away, blackening 125,000 acres of ranchland about 60 miles north of
the Mexican border.
   No injuries were reported. A shift in the wind was expected to
help the fire burn itself out, officials.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
