<HEAD>Jackson Looking For Another `Gold Medal' In South Carolina</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top prospects uncertain. Caucuses don't begin until 4:30 p.m.
EST</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID REED</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson was hoping to win a clear
majority of delegates today in South Carolina's Democratic
presidential caucuses, while Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr.
insisted he was a strong contender.
   ``If you believe it we're going to win this nomination,''
Jackson told members of the South Carolina Education Association
Friday.
   Jackson said half the states have held primaries or caucuses and
he has finished first or second in all but a few of them. ``In
South Carolina ... I want to win another gold medal.''
   The caucus meetings at 1,788 precincts were scheduled to begin
in the late afternoon.
   Jackson came into South Carolina second to Massachusetts Gov.
Michael Dukakis in delegates overall, and Jackson predicted that
after today's caucuses and the primary Tuesday in his second home,
Illinois, he would be the delegate leader.
   Illinois Sen. Paul Simon has virtually ignored South Carolina
recently and his state campaign coordinator, Dan King, said Friday
that the campaign was asking Simon supporters to remain uncommitted
in the caucuses today but to work to become delegates to the county
conventions later in the month.
   Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt campaigned two days in the state
this week and also is looking for a share of the 44 delegates at
stake.
   Gore, who toured the state's major cities Friday, said he
expected to do ``extremely well'' today and said he was the
candidate with the momentum. He told a crowd of a few hundred
supporters at the Statehouse that his strong showing on Super
Tuesday surprised everyone.
   ``I believe that momentum is going to continue right through the
convention in Atlanta and right through November,'' he said. ``I'm
excited about the possibility of victory.''
   John Dukakis said Friday he believed his father would get some
support because of his front-runner status and his vision for
economic growth.
   ``We would like to pick up some delegates,'' he said. ``But
we're realistic and know it's going to be difficult. We understand
that we're up against two strong favorite sons and that they are
going to do well.''
</TEXT>
