<DOCNO> AP880312-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 0259EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-RevenueSharing     03-12 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Revenue Sharing,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Upholds Administration On Revenue Sharing Account</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Associations representing city and county
governments are ``virtually certain'' to appeal a court ruling that
is permitting the Reagan administration to withhold $180 million in
revenue sharing funds, an attorney says.
   A three-judge panel of the U.S. Court of Appeals for the
District of Columbia Circuit on Friday reversed a lower court
ruling and said the administration did not have to distribute the
money to local governments.
   ``I think it's virtually certain we'll ask the court to
reconsider its decision,'' said David C. Vladek, a lawyer for the
National Association of Counties, the National League of Cities,
the U.S. Conference of Mayors and 10 city and county governments.
   ``My sense is the court did not fully comprehend the nature of
our legal arguments,'' he said.
   The dispute involves President Reagan's Feb. 1, 1986, order
under the Gramm-Rudman law that set aside 4.3 percent of budget
items, including $180 million from that year's $4.2 billion
appropriation to the revenue sharing trust fund.
   The local governments argued that the law provided that 1986
budget money that had been sequestered should remain in government
trust funds and be paid out in 1987. They argued that even though
Congress had abolished revenue sharing after 1986, it intended that
any money remaining in the trust fund be distributed.
   Revenue sharing, begun under the Nixon administration, provided
nearly all local governments with unrestricted federal grants.
   U.S. District Judge Joyce Hens Green on July 28 ruled in favor
of the local governments and said Treasury Secretary James A. Baker
III had illegally transferred the revenue sharing money from the
trust fund to the general fund.
   However, Judge John R. Gibson, who wrote the appeals panel's
decision reversing Green, said Congress' intent with the
Gramm-Rudman law was clearly to reduce the federal budget deficit.
   ``Merely freezing (the monies in 1986) and resuscitating them
(in 1987) would not result in any meaningful deficit reduction and
could be characterized by critics to be a sham,'' said Gibson, who
was joined by Judges Patricia M. Wald and David Santelle.
   ``The result in this case may be harsh, but we believe it is
consistent with congressional intent,'' wrote Gibson, who was
designated to the case from the U.S. Court of Appeals for the
Eighth Circuit in St. Louis.
   Among the plaintiffs are New York City; Kansas City, Mo.;
Milwaukee County, Wis.; and Cuyahoga County, Ohio, which includes
Cleveland.
   The U.S. Conference of Mayors, at the time of the original
district court decision last summer, had estimated that New York
would receive $10 million; Chicago, $2.6 million; Los Angeles, $2.2
million; and Detroit $1.3 million of the money.
   Other estimates were $606,000 for New Orleans; $554,000 for
Indianapolis; $677,000 for Washington D.C.; $440,000 for Denver and
$104,000 for Des Moines, Iowa. Estimates for other cities were not
provided.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880312-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 0300EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p BC-HartText 2Takes   03-12 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Hart Text, 2 Takes,600-1200</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of Gary Hart's statement
withdrawing Friday from the race for the Democratic presidential
nomination.
   Thank you very much.
   Thank you all very much.
   I want to, first of all, introduce my wife, Lee, our son, John.
   I want also to acknowledge the presence of some very good
friends and great party leaders here today: The governor of the
state of Colorado, Roy Romer. Our good personal friends and more
than worthy successor to me in the United States Senate, Tim and
Wren Wirth. And the chairman of the Colorado state Democratic
Party, and also a very good friend of ours, Buie Seawell.
   We want to thank each and every one of you for being here.
   Few people have had the good fortune that I've had; good fortune
measured in terms of my family and a far-flung network of friends
and supporters around the country, and in the opportunities that I
have been given to serve my country.
   Fewer Americans, still, have had the opportunity to run for
president of the United States, and I've had that chance twice.
   The people are the strength of this country.
   I said I wanted them to decide about my candidacy.
   I got a fair hearing.
   And the people have decided.
   And now I clearly should not go forward.
   My candidacy represented a more complicated and difficult choice
than in 1984.
   A choice beyond the scope of traditional politics, and I fully
understood that.
   I also had a more far-reaching and complex economic, defense,
and foreign policy agenda.
   That was difficult to reduce to slogans and sound bites.
   Nonetheless, I did get a chance, particularly in the debates, to
get my message of fundamental change and reform on the record, and
to draw distinctions between my ideas and those of the other
Democratic candidates.
   For that, I want to thank all those, especially the young people
who came to my speeches.
   And I want to thank members of the press and media who were
fair, balanced and professional.
   Lee and I want to congratulate Mike and Kitty Dukakis, Jesse and
Jackie Jackson, and Al and Tipper Gore, for their very impressive
achievements last Tuesday and before.
   They've all worked extremely hard, and they deserve every bit of
the credit they have received.
   I also want to thank Paul Simon, along with the others, for his
gentlemanliness towards me in the debates, and wish him well in his
home state primary.
   While disagreeing with him strongly on trade and international
economics, I've been extremely impressed with Dick Gephardt's
thoughtfulness and his equanimity under harsh attack.
   Despite his lack of political success, all of us gained great
respect for Bruce Babbitt, as truth-teller and prophet on our
national budget and fiscal policy.
   Win or lose, each of these candidates has grown in stature and
deserves to be considered as genuine national leaders.
   But win or lose, we also face an unhappy reality.
   The Democratic Party has won only one national election since
1964.
   The struggle in our party is not between the left and the right,
it's between the past and the future.
   And those who cling to the past too often mask their lack of
vision and direction with caution and vagueness and platitudes.
   We can only win if we are prepared to govern.
   And we can only be prepared to govern if we challenge the future
with bold, specific new policies to make our economy productive
once again, and to conduct a serious foreign policy in an
increasingly complex world.
   The remaining candidates should forgo the bitter personal
attacks so favored by political insiders, and, instead, show their
concern for the national interest by seriously debating the issues
that are threatening our country.
   Instead of canceling or running from debates, now that there are
fewer candidates, there should be more debates.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880312-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 0301EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p BC-HartText 1stAdd   03-12 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Hart Text, 1st Add,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>DENVER: more debates.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A presidential campaign really is a debate over differences
among the candidates.
   And that's what it ought to be.
   The remaining candidates should put out budget proposals to
reduce Reagan deficits and show how they would pay for their
programs.
   This would demonstrate competence and show honesty on the tax
issue.
   I encourage these candidates to learn the principles and
philosophy of military reform, because that represents the best
defense policy for our country.
   And they should spell out a foreign policy framework that's
specific on issues such as Third World debt and the use of military
force to avoid the continuing pitfalls of ad hoc response of crisis
after crisis.
   We should challenge our young people to help eliminate
illiteracy and poverty and pollution, to give something back to
their country through a voluntary national service.
   So now is the time that the candidates should welcome serious
debates, not about personalities, but about policies for this
country's future.
   The reason I got back in the race was to help stimulate that
debate about the future, to challenge caution and narrow-interest
politics of the past, and to lead the cause of reform.
   And I intend to continue that leadership for reform, because it
is the best hope for our country.
   It's a cause that lives on beyond any campaign.
   I hope those who share that cause will help me continue the
Center for a New Democracy, which we began in 1984.
   Through the center, through speeches, through writing and
symposiums around the country, we can provide a voice for those who
know our policies must be fundamentally restructured to keep the
torch of democracy and idealism and hope alive.
   Most of all, I want to say that no one has ever been more
blessed with family and friends than I have.
   My friends and supporters around the country have given the word
``loyalty'' new meaning.
   They've toiled tirelessly in an uphill fight, understanding the
odds throughout, and having as their only reward the knowledge that
they had done their very best to move our country forward.
   To all of you everywhere, particularly the young people, my very
warmest thanks and deepest gratitude, and I promise that I'll find
some way in years to come to repay your commitment and loyalty to
the cause which we shared.
   Public words, of course, are insufficient to express my feelings
towards Lee and Andrea and John, each of whom has demonstrated in
his or her own way inexhaustible courage and fortitude and
conviction in that same cause.
   They're owed more than I can ever possibly repay.
   And to those of you in and out of politics who may face
setbacks, failures, or defeats, who are told to give up,
accommodate, or compromise, I hope you'll simply say, as I do,
``Hell, no.''
   Preserve your integrity, study time and patience, and never give
up.
   As I have before, I leave with you these words:
   ``No great cause is ever lost or ever won. The battle must
always be renewed and the creed restated, for some things are
universal, catholic, and undying. They do not age or pass out of
fashion, for they symbolize eternal things. They are the guardians
of the freedom of the human spirit, the proof of what our mortal
frailty can achieve.''
   Thank you all.
   God bless you.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End Hart Text _ 2 Takes</HEAD>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880312-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 0302EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w BC-McFarlane-Chronology     03-12 0709</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-McFarlane-Chronology,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Iran-Contra Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a brief chronology of the life of
former National Security Adviser Robert C. McFarlane, particularly
events related to his involvement in the Iran-Contra affair:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1937</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   July 12 _ Born in Washington, D.C., the son of William Doddrige
McFarlane, a New Deal Democratic congressman. Grows up in Graham,
Texas.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1959</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Receives a B.S. degree in electrical engineering from the U.S.
Naval Academy in Annapolis, Md. Commissioned as a second lieutenant
in the U.S. Marine Corps. Four days after graduation, marries his
wife, Jonda.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1967-1971</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Serves with the Marines in the Far East, including a combat tour
in Vietnam.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1971</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Works as White House fellow in the Nixon administration.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1973</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Named military assistant to Henry A. Kissinger, who was then
national security adviser to President Nixon.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1975</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Becomes special assistant for national security affairs to
President Ford.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1979</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Frustrated with the policies of the Carter administration, he
resigns commission as lieutenant colonel in the Marine Corps. He
serves as assistant to Sen. John Tower, R-Texas, on the Senate
Armed Services Committee.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1981</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   January _ Named a counselor in the State Department, under then
Secretary of State Alexander Haig.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1982</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   January _ Becomes chief deputy to William P. Clark, who was
President Reagan's national security adviser, and ran the
day-to-day operations of the National Security Council.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1983</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   July _ Named special envoy to the Middle East, succeeding Philip
Habib, at a time when Israel was occupying a large part of Lebanon.
   October _ Chosen by President Reagan to succeed Clark as
national security adviser. Soft-spoken and shunning publicity, he
gains a reputation for working 80-hour weeks.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1984</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   May _ McFarlane meets with Bandar bin Sultan of Saudi Arabia to
discuss the needs of the Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1985</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   July _ Israeli official suggests to McFarlane that a transfer of
arms to Iran could lead to the release of U.S. hostages in Lebanon.
McFarlane takes the message to Reagan.
   Aug. 30 _ First plane load of U.S.-made weapons sent from Israel
to Tehran. McFarlane and White House Chief of Staff Donald Regan
later disagree over whether the president approved the shipment.
McFarlane says yes, Regan says no.
   Dec. 4 _ McFarlane resigns as national security adviser and is
succeeded by Rear Adm. John Poindexter. Sources say McFarlane's
rivalry with Regan led to the resignation.
   He joins the Center for Strategic and International Studies, a
Washington policy study center, but later continues working for the
National Security Council as a consultant.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1986</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   May 25 _ McFarlane and National Security Council aide Oliver
North fly to Tehran with a shipment of military equipment,
expecting hostages to be freed. They take a cake shaped like a key
and a Bible signed by President Reagan. The negotiations fail and
they fly home.
   Dec. 1-3 _ He testifies to the Senate Intelligence Committee in
the initial congressional inquiry into the Iran-Contra affair.
   Dec. 8 _ McFarlane falsely tells the House Foreign Affairs
Committee that he did not know about solicitation of donations to
the Contras from an unidentified foreign country, later revealed to
be Saudi Arabia.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1987</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Feb. 9 _ McFarlane is hospitalized after taking an overdose of
Valium in a suicide attempt. He is hospitalized for two weeks. He
says later in an interview, ``What really drove me to despair was a
sense of having failed the country.''
   May 11 _ McFarlane begins four days of testimony before the
congressional Iran-Contra committees. He tells committee members,
``Shoot your best shot.''
   In the testimony, McFarlane says the president instructed his
staff in 1984 to find ways around the congressional ban on military
aid to the Contras. He denies that he, North and Poindexter
concocted a cover-up story in November 1986.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>1988</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   March 11 _ McFarlane pleads guilty to misdemeanor charges that
he misled Congress in December 1986. He avoids the more serious
charge of perjury and pledges to cooperate with the independent
counsel investigating the Iran-Contra affair.
   The charges involve assurances that McFarlane made in three 1985
letters that the administration was not secretly aiding the Contras
and a fourth statement in testimony before the House Foreign
Affairs Committee on Dec. 8, 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
