<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Politics-Quotes     03-12 0381</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Politics-Quotes,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quotes From Presidential Candidates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some of the latest comments by
candidates for the presidency:
   
   BOB DOLE, seeking to save a candidacy he says is ``hanging by
our fingernails'' and maintaining many voters are still undecided:
``It's like last-minute Christmas shoppers. Some people don't even
know what they're going to buy until the last 24 hours and then
they buy whatever is left. We don't want that to happen.''
   
   GEORGE BUSH, declining a one-on-one confrontation with Dole,
recalling that he tried that with Ronald Reagan in 1980 and
probably lost the GOP nomination that year because of it: ``I may
be older, but I'm a lot smarter now, too.''
   
   MICHAEL DUKAKIS, dining in Chicago's ``Greektown'' section and
commenting on whether he is trying to build an ethnic coalition:
``We want to put together a coalition of people all over this
country, whether they're first-generation or second-generation
Americans.''
   
   ALBERT GORE, continuing to attack Dukakis: ``His complete lack
of experience in foreign policy is, I think, a major issue at a
time when the next president must be prepared to seize the
opportunities for a new relationship with the Soviets.''
   
   PAT ROBERTSON, saying he will campaign all the way to the
Republican National Convention: ``I'm in it until New Orleans.''
   
   GARY HART, abandoning his presidential bid: ``The people are the
strength of this country. I said I wanted them to decide about my
candidacy. I got a fair hearing. And the people have decided. And
now I clearly should not go forward.''
   
   RICHARD GEPHARDT, complaining about negative television ads in
the South: ``I feel like Dukakis and Gore have mugged me in an
alley. They are borrowing my rhetoric, but they don't have any
substance behind it.''
   
   JESSE JACKSON, urging blacks and whites in South Carolina to
unite around him: ``It's not so much black versus white as it is
barracudas eating us small fish. They don't eat fish by color. They
eat fish by size.''
   
   PAUL SIMON, asking educators to help him win Tuesday's Illinois
primary: ``We want to send a message to the nation from Illinois.
Part of that message is that for people who need quality education,
this administration has been out to lunch.''
</TEXT>
