<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 0332EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Iditarod     03-12 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iditarod,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Racers Hit Yukon; 70-Year-Old Still In Lead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RUBY, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mushers in the 1,150-mile Iditarod Trail
Sled Dog Race traded rolling hills for the flat expanse of the
frozen Yukon River as they tried to catch 70-year-old Joe
Redington, who's led since Tuesday.
   Redington arrived at Ruby, a Yukon village 653 miles from the
race's start in Anchorage and the first checkpoint on the river, at
12:30 p.m. Friday and left six hours later.
   His closest rival, Martin Buser of Big Lake, pulled in at 5:05
p.m. In third was Herbie Nayokpuk of Shishmaref, who arrived in
Ruby at 6:20 p.m.
   Four-time Iditarod champion Rick Swenson of Two Rivers was
running fourth. He checked out of Cripple, 120 miles back, at 7:25
p.m. Thursday. Joe Garnie of Teller followed Swenson out at 8:45
p.m., and defending champion Susan Butcher of Manley left at 9:50
p.m.
   Jerry Austin of St. Michael, running in eighth place, said he
and several mushers near him are still strong contenders in a race
that won't reach the finish line in Nome until later next week.
   ``Don't write off anybody that's three or six hours off the pace
right now,'' he said in Cripple. ``We're just inching our way up.
We're steadily gaining on them.''
   Butcher noted that Redington and Nayokpuk took their mandatory
24-hour layovers early in the race, an advantage because the
leaders later got bogged down in new snow. But that advantage may
be wearing thin, she said.
   ``It was a break for them in the beginning, but now they've been
going with no real long rest for a while. I think our dogs are
fresher,'' she said.
   But Nayokpuk, who couldn't keep up with Redington between
Cripple and Ruby, said Butcher and Swenson may have trouble
catching Redington.
   ``I tried to travel with Joe Redington from Cripple, but he
disappeared in a hurry,'' a tired Nayokpuk said as he sat on the
porch of a house in Ruby and changed his boots. ``I never saw him
again. He has the dogs. If he gets those dogs running to Nome, he's
going to be a hard one to beat.''
   Redington is known as the Father of the Iditarod for helping
found the race 16 years ago.
   The race started March 5 in Anchorage. After Ruby, mushers race
146 miles downriver to the village of Kaltag, then cross to the
Bering Sea coast for a final dash to Nome.
   The winner will collect $30,000 of a $150,000 purse; the next 19
finishers will split the rest. Two of the 52 teams that started the
race have dropped out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880312-0025 </DOCNO>
