<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Canada-PilotsStrike     03-12 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Canada-Pilots Strike,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Ontario Pilots Strike Over Wages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON, Ontatio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 200 Air Ontario pilots walked
off the job today over a wage dispute, shutting down the regional
commuter services that handles 60,000 passengers monthly.
   Company spokesman Paul McKnicht said Friday that the pilots
agreed to continue flying Air Ontario air ambulances during the
strike.
   ``The bulk of our flight operations will be curtailed but
management personnel will be operating a few essential services in
remote communities of northern Ontario,'' McKnight said.
   Those communities, north of Timmins, depend on the airline to
fly in commodities such as food and fuel, he said.
   Negotiations between Air Ontario and the Canadian Air Line
Pilots Association broke off Thursday over pay. The pilots walked
off the job at 12:01 a.m. today.
   Union spokesman Roger Burgess-Webb said union officials have
told the airline they would be willing to resume talks but no
further discussions have been scheduled.
   Neither side would predict how long the strike would last, but
McKnight said it would be ``very very expensive.''
   The airline acts as a feeder for Air Canada flights from London,
where it is based, and 47 other communities around Ontario.
   Air Ontario Inc was created last May when Air Ontario Ltd.
merged with Austin Airways of Timmins. Air Canada owns 75 percent
of Air Ontario.
   Air Ontario has flights to Winnipeg and Montreal in Canada, and
to Hartford, Conn., and Cleveland, Ohio.
</TEXT>
