<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LaRoucheTrial     03-12 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-LaRouche Trial,0633</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LaRouche Trial On Hold As Battle For FBI, CIA, Other Records
Mounts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three intelligence operatives who say the FBI and
CIA asked them to infiltrate Lyndon LaRouche's political operation
repeatedly tried to involve him in illegal activities, a LaRouche
attorney told a judge.
   Defense lawyer Michael Reilly on Friday urged U.S. District
Judge Robert E. Keeton to halt testimony in LaRouche's fraud and
conspiracy trial until prosecutors finish searching government
records for references to the operatives and evidence of
infiltration of LaRouche groups.
   Keeton canceled testimony for Monday, and said he would decide
then if a longer delay was necessary in the trial of LaRouche, six
aides and five LaRouche organizations.
   The defendants are charged with conspiring to obstruct a federal
grand jury investigation into alleged credit card and loan fraud
during LaRouche's 1984 presidential campaign.
   Keeton has ordered Assistant U.S. Attorney John Markham to
search the files of the FBI, CIA, National Security Council and
Vice President George Bush.
   Reilly said he would present evidence of entrapment in private
if Keeton desired, but refused to be specific in open court. Keeton
did not request the information.
   The three operatives referred to by Reilly are retired Army Sgt.
Maj. Fred Lewis, Ron Tucker and Gary Howard. In an FBI document
declassified last week, Lewis, Tucker and Howard said they were
asked by the FBI and CIA to infiltrate LaRouche organizations.
   Markham filed a memo in which he charged the three men were
lying.
   ``A search of the FBI files relating to them shows that they
were never requested to penetrate the organization and that they
never did so,'' Markham said in the memo.
   Reilly disputed that, saying Markham's memo made no reference to
infiltration on behalf of the CIA. He also noted a memo between two
pivotal players in the Iran-Contra scandal in which Lewis is
referred to by last name, but only as proof Lewis was well known by
government officials.
   In a memo sent to then-NSC aide Oliver North by retired Air
Force Maj. Gen. Richard Secord, one of North's principal operatives
in the network helping Nicaraguan Contra rebels, Secord said ``our
man'' told him Lewis had gathered ``info against LaRouche.''
   Lewis is the executive vice president of Rhyolite Management
Systems, a Texas company LaRouche lawyers contend was one of
several companies run by former military officers that the CIA used
to carry out covert activities.
   Howard and Tucker claim to be longtime government informants and
were the founders of another Texas company, now defunct, that
reportedly carried out covert activities.
   Markham originally told defense lawyers that ``our man''
referred to Oliver ``Buck'' Revell, a top FBI official involved in
counterintelligence. Markham later said he was mistaken and that
the reference was to John Cupp, a Secord associate who worked in
the resupply effort.
   Secord and Cupp, in interviews this week, also have said the
reference was to Cupp. Both denied any role in or knowledge of a
government effort to spy on LaRouche.
   Reilly on Friday filed a motion demanding the information
Markham relied on when he initially said Secord was referring to
Revell.
   ``If `our man here' is in fact Oliver Revell, it would create a
motive for high-level forces in the FBI and National Security
Council to conceal that in order to protect Mr. Revell,'' the
motion said.
   LaRouche attorneys said the information might help them prove
their contention that North asked the FBI and CIA to infiltrate
LaRouche groups because they were interfering with North's private
Contra resupply effort.
   An FBI spokesman said the agency would not comment on matters at
issue in a trial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
