<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GSA Reluctantly Extends Deadline For Bids On Phone System</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The General Services Administration says it is
``reluctantly'' extending the deadline for bids on a new
multibillion-dollar government telephone system to give US Sprint
Communications Co. more time to draft its proposal.
   The GSA said Friday it had extended the deadline by a month to
April 29 ``to insure the fullest possible competition'' for the
contract, one of the biggest ever let by the government.
   Besides Sprint, only two other teams of companies are bidding on
the project, the work for which will be split 60-40 between two
vendors.
   The other bidders are a team led by American Telephone &
Telegraph Co. and another headed by Martin Marietta Corp. with MCI
Communications Corp.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ford Cars Being Recalled To Fix Pollution-Control Equipment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency says Ford
Motor Co. is recalling 214,900 cars from the 1982 and 1983 model
years because some of the vehicles have been exceeding federal
emission standards.
   The company is notifying owners of 185,000 cars from 1983
equipped with the 1.6-liter four-cylinder engine to bring them in
for adjustment of the exhaust air-injection systems. These cars
were sold as the Ford Escort, Escort EXP and Escort Wagon and the
Mercury Lynx, Lynx LN-7 and Lynx Wagon.
   The agency said Friday that Ford also will recall 29,900 cars
from the 1982 model year to fix an exhaust gas recirculation system
which can cause excessive emissions of nitrogen oxides.
   The cars affected all have 2.3-liter four-cylinder engines and
automatic transmissions. They were sold as the Ford Mustang,
Granada and Fairmont and the Mercury Capri and Zephyr. Cars
originally sold in California are not affected.
   Dealers will check the carburetor spacer plates, which allows
some exhaust to enter the intake manifold, and clean them of
deposits if necessary.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>New Fitness Program Designed To Prepare Marines For Combat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Marine Corps has devised a new training
policy that mandates tougher physical conditioning programs to make
sure those who already have made it through basic training are
ready for combat.
   A new training policy order, signed last week and now being
prepared for distribution to the field, will require all commands
to refocus their physical conditioning program so that it goes
beyond just staying in shape to pass the standard physical fitness
test.
   The directive says commanders must ensure their Marines face ``a
minimum program of three hours per week'' of exercises that can be
divided between anaerobic conditioning, progressive resistance
training and aerobic conditioning.
   It says that Marine conditioning programs historically have
focused on physical fitness and adds: ``The focus, therefore, of
our programs must change. Each commander must emphasize unit and
combat fitness training, (instead of) physical fitness testing, and
reflect this distinction in training plans and schedules.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Field Tests For Genetically Engineered Bacterium Approved</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposal to conduct field tests in Wisconsin
for a genetically engineered bacterium designed to improve the
ability of alfalfa to use nitrogen in the air as a fertilizer has
won federal approval.
   The tests, approved Friday by the Environmental Protection
Agency, will be conducted in Pepin County, Wis., a county lying on
the Mississippi River about 20 miles southwest of Eau Claire.
   The bacterium, Rhizobium meliloti, grows naturally on alfalfa
roots, and mutant forms have been used to enhance plant growth in
the past.
   Using the techniques of recombinant DNA, BioTechnica Inc. of
Cambridge, Mass. has reinserted the genes responsible for nitrogen
use _ nitrogen fixation _ back into the organism, giving it two
copies of the genes.
   Lab and greenhouse tests indicate this will enhance alfalfa
yield, according to an EPA announcement when the company applied
for permission to test 13 months ago.
</TEXT>
