<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PoliticalBriefs     03-12 0835</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Gets Top Spot On New York Primary Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson won the coveted top spot for
New York's April 19 Democratic presidential primary ballot as the
result of a lottery draw at the state Board of Elections.
   Board spokesman Steven LaFever said Friday that the order of
appearance on the ballot, after Jackson, is expected to be
Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr., Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis,
Illinois Sen. Paul Simon, an uncommitted slate, political extremist
Lyndon LaRouche and Missouri Rep. Richard Gephardt.
   LaRouche supporters have filed a challenge to Simon's nominating
petitions and the board is expected to rule on that challenge
Monday. After that, the ballot lineup is to be finalized.
   While the Democratic candidates run state wide by name and thus
have only one draw for ballot placement, Republican candidates rely
on delegate slates filed in each of the state's 34 congressional
districts. That means there's a separate ballot spot draw in each
congressional district for the GOP delegate slates.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jackson Should Play `Inspirational' Role, Robb Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson probably won't be on the
Democratic ticket in 1988, but he should have some sort of
``inspirational role'' in a Democratic administration, says former
Virginia Gov. Charles S. Robb.
   Robb said Jackson would be best ``in some part of the greater
domestic policy portion where he is simply without peer _ in
motivating young people, in encouraging young people not to get
involved with drugs, in encouraging people to pursue education,''
Robb told the Cleveland City Club on Friday.
   ``I think it's probably clear that if he is to have a role in
the next administration, it ought to be a role that is principally
an inspirational role and not a managerial role,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Picks Up Endorsements In New Jersey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush's quest for the
GOP presidential nomination picked up steam in New Jersey as three
top Republicans in the state endorsed him.
   Assembly Speaker Chuck Hardwick and U.S. Rep. James Courter
announced their support of Bush in a press conference Friday. Hours
later, U.S. Rep. Matthew Rinaldo endorsed the vice president.
   At a news conference in Trenton, Hardwick urged Gov. Thomas H.
Kean to change his noncommittal stance while Republican leaders
asked the party to unite around Bush.
   ``Not only is it time for all Republicans to unite behind George
Bush's candidacy, but that I hope Gov. Kean, as the leader of our
party ... will endorse the vice president in the near future,''
said Hardwick.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Berry Named Press Secretary For Democratic Convention Committee</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ruth H. Berry has been named press secretary
for the 1988 Democratic National Convention Committee.
   Donald L. Fowler, the committee's chief executive officer, and
Paul Kirk, Democratic national chairman, announced the appointment
Friday.
   Berry previously served as national trip director for the Sen.
Joseph Biden's presidential campaign. She did advance work for both
the 1976 Carter-Mondale presidential campaign and the White House
press office under President Carter.
   She was a producer for Cable News Network's election unit in
1983 and worked as an associate producer for special events for ABC
News in 1982.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Jackson's Michigan Chairman Predicts Victory Without TV Ads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EAST LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thanks to a ``great volunteer army,''
Jesse Jackson can capture Michigan delegates without spending a
small fortune on television ads, says the head of the candidate's
state campaign.
   Organizer Joel Ferguson said Friday he's confident Jackson will
be enough of a newsmaker that he can count on being on television
without having to buy commercial time.
   Jackson will spend the three days before Michigan's March 26
Democratic caucuses barnstorming the state, and has a full schedule
of appearances before that, beginning with a commencement address
today at Michigan State University.
   After the address, Jackson is scheduled to meet with supporters,
labor leaders and Gov. James Blanchard _ activities that will be
parallelled by rival Michael Dukakis, who plans today to tour a
Lansing machine tool plant before meeting with labor and the
Democratic governor.
   Blanchard met Thursday with Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri,
another Democratic contender.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cuomo Doesn't Want Bush Tied To Iran-Contra Just Yet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo thinks independent
counsel Lawrence Walsh could do Democrats a favor by delaying the
release of any information that might link Vice President George
Bush to the Iran-Contra affair.
   ``The worst thing that could happen now is to have some kind of
exposure of Irangate that knocks Bush out and makes room for (Bob)
Dole,'' Cuomo said Friday of Bush's recent success in Republican
Super Tuesday primaries.
   Cuomo has joked in the past that the best Republican ticket,
from a Democratic standpoint, would be ``Bush and Bush.'' The
governor has said Dole would be harder for the Democrats to beat.
   ``If there's going to be some revelation, let it come after it's
too late to change Bush,'' Cuomo said of Walsh's investigation.
</TEXT>
