<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 0456EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson     03-12 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Says Campaign In Second Phase</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHYLLIS MENSING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson, stumping for votes on home turf in
advance of Tuesday's Illinois Democratic primary, says his
presidential campaign is in its second phase _ a phase where people
can view him as a winner.
   Many of his supporters had hoped he would do well in other state
contests but didn't really believe it would happen, Jackson said
Friday night. But his campaign has been buoyed by strong finishes
from the South to the Midwest and north to Alaska.
   ``So now we move into the second phase _ when you hope it and
believe it. Now, let's achieve it,'' Jackson told a crowd of more
than 1,000 cheering supporters who jammed a hotel ballroom for a
$50-per-person fund raiser.
   Jackson said he's finished first or second in 22 of 28 state
political contests so far despite being outspent by his Democratic
opponents. He said his message is making believers of those who
thought he could not win because he is black.
   ``Don't judge the campaign by its budget,'' he told the crowd.
``Judge it by its mission and its message.''
   The message Friday night included familiar themes: a campaign
against drugs; emphasis on prenatal care and daycare for the young
instead of ``jail care and welfare'' as they grow older; and a push
for jobs.
   In Illinois, polls show Jackson's top opponents are Sen. Paul
Simon, another home state favorite, and Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis, the front-runner in delegates. Jackson has refused to
attack his party rivals.
   ``If I stop to hit them, I might break my stride,'' he said.
   And he said he has proven his ability to manage a tight budget.
   ``If my competitors had my budget, they could not survive. If I
had their budget, they could surrender,'' Jackson said.
</TEXT>
