<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 0433EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Wedtech Bjt   03-12 0702</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech, Bjt,0726</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Says Biaggi And Co-Defendants Plundered Wedtech</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY10</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Mario Biaggi could have helped Wedtech
Corp. for free, but chose to help plunder millions of dollars from
the Bronx defense contractor, a prosecutor told jurors in the
congressman's racketeering trial.
   ``The crime is not what the congressman did. The crime is that
he was paid for what he did, the extortion and bribes,'' Howard
Wilson, an assistant U.S. attorney, said Friday in U.S. District
Court.
   Wilson's opening statement to jurors hearing the case of Biaggi
and six co-defendants outlined how ``a little company in the
Bronx'' was turned into ``an enterprise that was to be plundered,
to be used by the people on trial here.''
   ``And in the end, because of the corruption, because of the
greed, because of the lies, the company went kaput,'' he said.
   Wedtech, formed in 1965 as a machine shop, capitalized on laws
allocating government contracts for minority-owned enterprises, and
by 1985 had grown into a defense contractor with 1,000 employees
and $117 million in revenue.
   The company suspended operations and laid off most of its
workers in December 1986, then filed for protection from creditors
under Chapter 11 of the bankruptcy act.
   The co-defendants are former Bronx Borough President Stanley
Simon, 57; Bernard G. Ehrlich, 59, of Bedford, Biaggi's former law
partner and a former major general in the New York National Guard;
Biaggi's son, Richard, 38, of Fort Lee, N.J.; Peter Neglia, 39, of
Armonk, the former regional administrator of the Small Business
Administration; former Wedtech chairman John Mariotta, 57, of
Scarsdale and Ronald Betso, 39, of Brooklyn, a former policeman and
friend of Neglia's.
   ``All treated this company like a gold mine,'' said Wilson.
   The defendants claimed that Mariotta, who is Hispanic, was the
majority owner of Wedtech, entitling the company to no-bid federal
contracts, Wilson said.But Mariotta owned less than half, said the
prosecutor.
   Rep. Biaggi, who at one point demanded 5 percent of Wedtech's
revenues, was given 5 percent of Wedtech stock, which was put in
his son's name, Wilson said. The elder Biaggi and Ehrlich made $4
million from the 225,000 Wedtech shares they received, he said.
   At another point, Biaggi, 70, asked for $50,000 for expediting a
lease before the city's Board of Estimate, the prosecutor said.
   Simon demanded and received more than $50,000 in cash, meals,
chips for gambling at Atlantic City, N.J., casinos, marble for his
home, a trip to Rome and charitable contributions in his name,
Wilson said.
   Simon also got a Wedtech job for his brother-in-law and took
half his raises over the years, Wilson said.
   Neglia was Wedtech's ``paid-for friend,'' Wilson said. Among
other things, Wilson claimed, Neglia warned the company about a
congressional probe.
   Neglia was paid with stock options, frequent meals,
contributions to the Republican Party in his name and the promise
of a job on leaving government, Wilson said. Less than a month
after leaving office in early 1986, he went to work for the law
firm of Ehrlich and the younger Biaggi.
   Mariotta embezzled about $1 million and sold Wedtech stock worth
$6 million to $8 million, Wilson said.
   Ehrlich was ``Mario Biaggi's partner in the plunder of Wedtech.
When he got it, he split it,'' charged Wilson, who said Richard
Biaggi ``became the front man.''
   Wilson said the two men's law firm earned $1 million in
retainers' fees from Wedtech.
   Betso took stock options in his name for his friend Neglia,
Wilson alleged, then lied about it to the Department of Labor.
   Wilson promised testimony to back up his claims from Wedtech
accountants, supervisors and workers; Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y.;
and four former Wedtech officials who pleaded guilty to crimes
involving the company.
   Defense attorneys begin presenting their arguments Monday.
   The House Ethics Committee announced last month it would
recommend Biaggi be expelled following his conviction last year in
another case on charges he accepted illegal paid vacations from an
old friend and political ally.
   Biaggi had asked the committee not to act until his appeal of
that conviction was settled. The panel decided to postpone bringing
the matter before the full House.
