<HEAD>Intelligence Operative Reportedly Asked LaRouche To Help Free
Sakharov</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-LaRouche Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A relative of Andrei Sakharov says he asked Lyndon
LaRouche's help in getting the dissident out of the Soviet Union
but denied a claim by LaRouche attorneys that he was acting at the
bidding of U.S. intelligence operatives.
   ``We came to him on our own initiative,'' Efram Yankelovich said
in a telephone interview Friday. ``Nobody asked us or directed us
or suggested it to us.''
   Yankelovich is married to the daughter of Yelena Bonner,
Sakharov's wife.
   LaRouche attorney Michael Reilly said Yankelovich and Alexei
Semyonov, Sakharov's stepson, approached a LaRouche aide in 1984
and said a third party promised to spirit Sakharov and Bonner out
of the Soviet Union if LaRouche paid $2 million.
   LaRouche refused to get involved and ended the discussions after
the Sakharov relatives identified the third party as a man the
LaRouche organization believed was trying to entrap them, Reilly
said.
   Attorneys for LaRouche, six aides and five organizations on
trial here on fraud and conspiracy charges were denied access
Friday to classified FBI documents referring to an attempt to get
Sakharov and Bonner out of the Soviet Union.
   The defense lawyers earlier this week were given declassified
excerpts from the material. The excerpts say FBI files indicate
that in 1984 two intelligence operatives approached two Sakharov
relatives and told them they could get Sakharov and Bonner out of
the Soviet Union for $2 million.
   The operatives, Gary Howard and Ron Tucker, are quoted in the
same FBI document as saying they and a third man, retired Army Sgt.
Maj. Fred Lewis, had been asked by the FBI and the CIA to
infiltrate LaRouche organizations.
   Yankelovich said he never heard of Tucker or Howard.
   The LaRouche lawyers want the entire FBI file to help pursue
leads they say show numerous attempts by government informants and
operatives to entrap LaRouche.
   But U.S. District Judge Robert E. Keeton said the file was
properly classified and that the material not already given the
defense lawyers was irrelevant.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney John Markham said the file was created
in the Boston FBI office during an investigation of possible fraud
against Sakharov's relatives and possible violations of the
Neutrality Act, which prohibits interference in foreign countries.
   Tucker and Howard, in a $1.4 million lawsuit against the
government, describe themselves as longtime operatives involved in
government sting operations.
   In the suit, Tucker and Howard said they gathered evidence
against an arms merchant planning to sell weapons to Iran but that
the government refused to prosecute the case because it would have
exposed the Iran-Contra scandal.
</TEXT>
