<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Pilot-Cocaine 1stLd-Writethru a0459 03-12 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pilot-Cocaine, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0459,0534</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toxicology Report Shows Cocaine In System Of Dead Commuter Airline
Pilot</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RECASTS lead.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOE WHEELAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Survivors of a commuter airliner crash that
claimed nine lives expressed outrage at a government report that
the pilot had traces of cocaine in his body.
   ``It makes me mad,'' said Nancy Hill of Cortez, who suffered a
broken leg and a dislocated shoulder in the Jan. 19 Continental
Express accident outside Durango. ``We should have protection from
this kind of thing.''
   Both the pilot and co-pilot died in the crash, and investigators
have not determined which one was flying at the time.
   The eight survivors were rescued after one, Peter Schauer,
trudged 1{ miles over a snowy mountainside to a house.
   ``Our lives will never be the same, and when there is this kind
of problem involved, you have to be even more angry,'' Schauer said
Friday.
   The toxicology report released Friday in Washington said pilot
Steven S. Silver had .022 micrograms per milliliter of
benzoylecgonine, the principal metabolite of cocaine, in his
bloodstream.
   He also had 1.8 micrograms per milliliter of metabolized cocaine
and .022 micrograms of cocaine in his urine, according to the
report by the National Transportation Safety Board's Bureau of
Technology.
   ``I would say that is a small amount'' of cocaine, said Dr.
Merrit M. Birky, an NTSB chemist who had an outside lab analyze the
samples. ``It would be inappropriate for me to comment on the
significance of this.''
   Birky said cocaine is quickly converted to benzoylecgonine in
the bloodstream and has a half-life of seven hours in the body. But
Birky said he was unable to say how much cocaine the pilot ingested
or when he ingested it.
   The NTSB did not characterize the finding as a cause of the
accident or indicate whether the pilot might have been impaired.
   Silver, 36, of Denver was an employee of Trans-Colorado Airlines
Inc. of Colorado Springs. Trans-Colorado leases planes and crews to
Rocky Mountain Airways, a Continental Airlines subsidiary that
operates in Colorado as Continental Express.
   The Swearingen Metro III twin-engine turboprop crashed in a
mountainous area in southwestern Colorado after it was given
clearance to land at Durango-La Plata County Airport.
   The report said the toxicology report on co-pilot Ralph Harvey,
42, of Denver will be released later.
   Bill White, a Denver attorney acting as Trans-Colorado's
spokesman Friday, said the company was ``obviously surprised. We're
concerned.''
   The Air Line Pilots Association said it was ``deeply disturbed''
by the report, but said it ``leaves unanswered more questions than
it resolves.''
   George James, president of Airline Economics Inc., a Washington
consulting firm to the airline industry, said he was unaware of any
other commercial airline accident in which drug use had been
involved.
   The Department of Transportation on Thursday proposed a drug
testing program for more than a half million airline employees.
   In a statement Friday, Transportation Secretary James Burnley
called the evidence of drug use by Silver ``a tragic reminder that
not even commercial aviation is exempt from the drug abuse problem
which plagues our society.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
