<HEAD>Shot Fired At Greyhound, Two Passengers Wounded</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Sujal in 3rd graf cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHATTANOOGA, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two passengers on a Greyhound bus
suffered gunshot wounds today when a bullet hit the vehicle as it
rolled down a downtown highway, police said.
   The bullet apparently struck the bus near the middle of the
vehicle around 1 a.m., hit the first victim's foot, then lodged in
the second victim's leg, said police Detective Charles Dudley.
   Passengers Sujal Badami, 24, of Clemson, S.C., and Eric Douglas,
21, of Denmark, S.C., were treated at Erlanger Medical Center and
released, said hospital spokeswoman Debbie Goad.
   Badami was wounded in the foot and Douglas in the leg.
   The shooting on Interstate 124 followed a similar case Thursday,
in which a truck driver was seriously wounded when two shots
pierced his tractor-trailer on the interstate, police said.
   Sam Lands, hit in the chest and wrist, was in satisfactory
condition today at Erlanger, Ms. Goad said.
   The bus was hit as it headed for Memphis, police said. The
driver said he pulled over and flagged down a passing truck driver,
who used his citizens band radio to call police.
   The bus driver said company policy prohibited him from giving
his name.
   A drunken driver struck the bus a glancing blow while it was
parked on the side of the interstate, police said. The driver,
whose name was not released, was arrested, and was to be charged
later today, police said.
   Police have no suspects in either shooting, and could not say
until ballistics tests were completed if they were related. It was
not clear whether the shot that struck the bus was fired by a
sniper or from a passing car.
