<HEAD>Blizzard Keeps Its Punch; Golfball-Sized Hail Hits Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A major blizzard continued blasting the northern Plains today,
packing winds of 30 to 50 mph that reduced visibility to near zero
and piled up snow in drifts up to 10 feet high.
   A band of showers and thunderstorms spawned by the same storm
system produced hail the size of golfballs in north-central Texas.
The rain extended across central Arkansas and central Illinois into
southwest Wisconsin and southeast Minnesota.
   Areas hit hard by the blizzard Friday included northeast
Colorado, western and north-central Nebraska, western South Dakota
and eastern Wyoming. Roads remain closed in many areas. Bitterly
cold wind chills of 10 to 25 below zero were common.
   Blizzard warnings remained in effect today over much of the
eastern Dakotas and western Minnesota.
   Winter storm warnings or winter storm watches were up in
sections of Minnesota, Wisconsin, Iowa and Michigan.
   On Friday, snow was reported as deep as 31 inches, with snow
drifts 5 feet deep in Chadron, Neb. Drifts measured 10 feet in
Cody, although only 6 to 7 inches fell. Snowshowers also lingered
over the central Rockies.
   Strong winds over the northern Plains included gusts to 69 mph
at Akron, Colo. Wind gusts over 50 mph were clocked at Rapid city,
S.D.; Scottsbluff, Neb.; Limon, Colo.; and Duluth, Minn.
   There were numerous reports of large hail across north-central
Texas Friday night. Hail the size of golfballs was reported in De
Soto and Terrell. In Arkansas, 1-inch hail fell at Burg.
   Today's forecast called for snow and strong winds from the
Dakotas and Nebraska across the upper Mississippi Valley into upper
Michigan; strong winds in Kansas and Oklahoma; snowshowers
lingering over the northern and central Rockies and thunderstorms
extending from Alabama, Mississippi and northwest Georgia across
the Tennessee Valley, the Ohio Valley and the middle Mississippi
Valley, with rain reaching into southern Wisconsin, lower Michigan
and the lower Great Lakes region.
   Highs were expected in the 20s and 30s from the northern and
central Rockies across the northern two-thirds of the Plains and
the upper Mississippi Valley into upper Michigan, upstate New York
and northern New England; and the 70s and 80s from southern Texas
across the central Gulf coast states and the southern Atlantic
coast states, with a few readings in the 70s across Southern
California and southwest Arizona. The rest of the nation will have
highs in the 40s, 50s or 60s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 1
degree at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 70 degrees at Miami, Key West,
Fla., and Brownsville, Texas.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 46 fair; Boston 31 fair; Buffalo 31 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 40 fair; Cincinnati 51 fair; Cleveland fair;
Detroit 37 fair; Miami 70 partly cloudy; New York 41 fair;
Philadelphia 37 fair; Pittsburgh 38 fair; Portland, Maine 16 fair;
Washington 45 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 12 snow; Chicago 52 cloudy; Dallas-Fort Worth
60 cloudy; Denver 25 partly cloudy; Des Moines 37 partly cloudy;
Indianapolis 53 cloudy; Kansas City 33 windy; Minneapolis-St. Paul
33 snow; Nashville 56 windy; New Orleans 62 fair; St. Louis 51
cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 30 fair; Anchorage 35 cloudy; Las Vegas 45
fair; Los Angeles 55 fair; Phoenix 49 fair; Salt Lake City 26 fair;
San Diego 56 fair; San Francisco 45 fair; Seattle 41 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 9 fair; Toronto 28 partly cloudy.
