<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Mock-Robbins,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jamie Mock-Robbins, Leader in Sanctuary Movement, Dies at 32</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jamie Mock-Robbins, an early leader in
the sanctuary movement to aid Central American refugees, died at
age 32.
   Mock-Robbins, co-pastor of University Baptist Church, died on
Thursday. He had been battling cancer since October, The Seattle
Times said.
   In 1982, under the direction of Mock-Robbins and the Rev.
Donovan Cook, University Baptist became the first church in the
Pacific Northwest to declare itself a sanctuary for refugees
fleeing persecution in Central America. About 50 refugees have been
sheltered at the church.
   Mock-Robbins also spent much of the past four years in Central
America working with schools and churches. He organized relief in
1986 for victims of the San Salvador earthquake, which left about
1,000 people dead and hundreds of thousands injured and homeless.
   ``I have never known anyone as loving and gentle and dedicated
to living the gospel, and he demonstrated it daily, especially in
work in Central America,'' said Cook.
   Mock-Robbins also attended and helped organize demonstrations
and vigils in Seattle to protest U.S. military intervention in
Central American countries.
   A native of Dearborn, Mich., Mock-Robbins was a graduate of
Albion College and Andover-Newton Theological Seminary in Boston.
   He is survived by his wife, Katherine Mock-Robbins; his parents
from Dearborn, Mich., and a sister.
   A memorial service was scheduled for Sunday at University
Baptist.
</TEXT>
