<1ST_LINE>u i PM-GulfRdp     03-12 0454</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf Rdp,0466</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Claims Raid On Iranian Oil Tanker In Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMIR F. GHATTAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq claimed today it raided an Iranian
oil tanker in the Persian Gulf, resuming a campaign to cut Tehran's
economic lifeline after the foes halted 12 days of missile attacks
on each other's cities.
   The raid came amid reports from U.S. military sources in
Washington that Iran has started building launch pads for Silkworm
anti-ship missiles on its Abu Musa island near the Strait of
Hormuz, the narrow entrance at the gulf's southern end.
   The official Iraqi News Agency quoted a military spokesman as
saying Iraqi warplanes on Friday night attacked a ``very large
maritime target'' _ usually meaning an Iranian oil tanker _ off the
Iranian coast, scoring ``an accurate and effective hit.''
   ``The air raid was within the framework of Iraq's firm and
legitimate right in tearing the arteries of oil supplies of the
Iranian regime to deprive it of employing its oil revenues for the
purposes of aggression,'' said the spokesman, who was not
identified.
   The agency, monitored in Nicosia, gave no other details, and the
attack could not be immediately confirmed by independent shipping
executives in the gulf. Iran usually does not report attacks on its
shipping.
   The ship raid occurred only hours after a truce went into effect
to stop the unprecedented long-range missile duel in the ``war of
the cities'' that had begun Feb. 29.
   Iraq fired eight rockets at Tehran and three at the holy city of
Qom, south of Tehran, Friday afternoon just 16 minutes before
Baghdad said it would stop shooting.
   More than 400 ships of different nationalities have been damaged
in the gulf since the Iran-Iraq war broke out in 1980. The ``tanker
war'' began in early 1984.
   Iraq on Friday had claimed another a ship attack but that also
could not be confirmed.
   Iraq's last confirmed attack on a ship was on Tuesday, when
warplanes blasted a Maltese-flag tanker shuttling Iranian crude.
   That attack was preceded by a lull since Feb. 12, the last time
Iraqi warplanes were confirmed to have hit a ship.
   Defense officials in Washington, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the Iranians are building launching pads in Abu
Musa. They added that U.S. intelligence had not yet detected
efforts by Iran to move any of its Chinese-built Silkworms to the
island, which serves as base for Revolutionary Guards.
   Iran has batteries of Silkworms, which have a range of about 50
miles, on its shore along the Strait of Hormuz.
   It also has fired missiles believed to be Silkworms into
Kuwait's main oil port from the Faw Peninsula, which it captured
from Iraq in 1986.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
