<1ST_LINE>u a PM-BrushFire     03-12 0467</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brush Fire,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire May Take Several Days To Put Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A wildfire raged through west Texas today
after burning 200,000 acres of prarie, killing livestock,
threatening homes and closing roads.
   No people were reported killed or seriously injured in the
blaze, which an army of hundreds fought Friday. Officials said
could take several days to extinguish the fire.
   ``It looked like we were in hell _ fire all around. Pretty
spooky,'' Jimmy T. Brooks, a 40-year-old cowboy, said here Friday
before going back to the battle.
   Winds diminished from 30 mph to about 10 mph, helping
firefighters bring parts of the blaze under control, said Terry
Harlow of Shackelford County's emergency management team.
   The fire destroyed a mobile home and several hunting sheds in
the sparsely populated region about 150 miles west of Dallas. The
blaze also damaged oil field equipment and ranch fences.
   The fire covered an area about 60 miles long and 25 miles wide
in portions of Callahan, Shackelford and Throckmorton counties,
officials said, and a 20-mile wide swath of the blaze burned out of
control. A few families were evacuated from ranches, officials said.
   Joe Fox, the Texas Forest Service official overseeing the
firefighting effort, predicted it could take another four days to
extinguish the blaze.
   Albany, a town of about 2,500 people and the county seat of
Shackelford, was under siege Friday. A change in wind direction
brought the fire to within 100 yards of the town, said Lawrence
Winkler, a spokesman for the Shackelford County emergency division.
But the wind died down.
   All four major highways through Albany were closed by heavy
smoke, officials said.
   Smoke and haze also cast a light fog-like pall over the
Dallas-Fort Worth area late Friday afternoon, and some Fort Worth
residents said they smelled the smoke.
   Gov. Bill Clements dispatched 100 National Guard soldiers. They
joined west Texas fire departments, Texas Forest Service
firefighters, state highway department employees, units from
Abilene's Dyess Air Force Base and the Fort Worth Fire Department.
Winkler said volunteer oilfield workers also pitched in.
   Some firefighters suffered minor burns and were temporarily
overcome by smoke, officials said.
   At the 88-year-old Nail Ranch, an estimated 35,000 acres were
scorched, an unknown number of cattle lost and 20-25 miles of fence
destroyed, said Ronnie Nail, one of the ranch heirs.
   Shifting winds made it difficult to determine where the fire
would spread, and in some cases firefighters were nearly surrounded
by the swiftly moving flames.
   One of the fires may have started when someone was burning tires
near here, while two others appeared to have formed along Farm Road
604 and may have been caused by passing motorists.
   There was speculation that trash fires may have sparked the
blazes Thursday, when humidity dipped to 7 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
