<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Spain-Noriega     03-12 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-Noriega,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spain Offers Noriega Political Asylum</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Panama, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spain told the United States it would give
political asylum to Panamanian strongman Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega if it helps end that Central American country's political
crisis, a newspaper reported today.
   Spain's leading daily, the independent El Pais, quoted Jose
Antonio Yanez, as saying, ``Spain, in a critical situation, would
be prepared to receive Noriega, if it can lead to a solution'' of
the Panamanian political situation.
   Yanez is a top policy adviser to Socialist Prime Minister Felipe
Gonzalez. Elena Chi, Consul at the Panamanian Embassy in Madrid,
told The Associated Press that Noriega had no plans to seek asylum
in Spain.
   Panamanian President Eric Arturo Del Valle was dismissed Feb.
26, a day after he tried to fire Noriega. As chief of the
15,000-strong Defense Forces, Noriega is considered the real power
behind the civilian government.
   Despite Delvalle's ouster by the Noriega-dominated National
Assembly, the United States still considers Delvalle Panama's
legitimate president.
   The United Staets has frozen official Panamanian government
funds deposited in U.S. banks, creating a financial crisis in
Panama, whose currency is the U.S. dollar.
   El Pais said Yanez, who ended a three-day visit to Washington
Friday, expressed Spain's position in a one-hour meeting Friday
with Elliot Abrams, U.S. undersecretary of State for interamerican
affairs.
   It said Spain's offer was made on condition that the U.S.
government not seek Noriega's extradition from Spain to face
indictments in Florida on charges of drug trafficking and money
laundering. Noriega has rejected the accusations.
   Other conditions set by Spain included that Noriega himself
request asylum in Spain and that Panama's political opposition
agree to the move, the newspaper said.
   Yanez, the paper said, also received a guarantee from the United
States that it would respect the Panama Canal Treaty of 1977
calling for the U.S. government to turn over control of the Panama
Canal at the end of 1999.
   The paper also reported the United States delivered a message to
Noriega in which it promised the military leader the Washington
would not oppose his residence in a third country.
   Gabriel Lewis, a former Panamanian ambassador to the United
States now leading the opposition to Noriega in Washington, told El
Pais he appreciated Spain's offer of asylum for Noriega ``because
his leaving would clear up the Panamanian crisis.''
   The newspaper also quoted Panamanian Defense Forces spokesman
Maj. Edgardo Lopez as saying: ``Once and for all: Noriega is going
to stay in Panama and, if necessary, die in Panama, but he will
never accept a shameful exit.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
