<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Austria-Waldheim 1stLd-Writethru a0431 03-12 0562</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Austria-Waldheim, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0431,0580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Begin Three-Day Anti-Waldheim Vigil</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with protest start. PICKS up 5th
graf pvs ``Waldheim attended...''; EDITS thereafter to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KENNETH JAUTZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protesters gathered outside the office of
President Kurt Waldheim today to demand that he resign because of
his World War II past as an officer in the German army.
   A small group of demonstrators maintained an overnight vigil on
the square in front of the president's office, and said they will
remain until late Sunday.
   The protesters fixed a 10-foot-long banner to a nearby fence
that read, ``Who Will Make Waldheim Resign.''
   ``We know that this will not force him to resign,'' said one
protester, who identified herself only as a 23-year-old student at
Vienna University.
   ``But hopefully it will help keep attention focused on him, and
remind people what a problem he has become for our country,'' she
added.
   The demonstrators were among 300 people protesting outside the
imperial Hofburg Palace on Friday, the 50th anniversary of
Austria's annexation by Nazi Germany.
   Organizers said they expected thousands of people for an
afternoon protest near the president's office in the center of the
capital.
   Waldheim attended several events marking the annexation, but the
controversy forced him to drop plans to deliver a major address.
   Austria's president normally is the keynote speaker for such
events, but Waldheim was the silent guest at several of the
ceremonies and did not play a major role.
   Waldheim concealed his role as a German army lieutenant in the
Balkans until it was disclosed in the media in March 1986, but he
has said he will not leave office until his term expires in 1992.
   Last year, the U.S. Justice Department placed the former U.N.
secretary-general on a list of undesirable persons, effectively
barring him from entering the country.
   A panel of historians concluded last month that Waldheim was in
close proximity to Nazi war crimes, including the deportation to
death camps of Jews and the murders of partisans, but did nothing
to prevent them.
   The report left open the question of Waldheim's guilt or
innocence in atrocities, fueling pressure that he resign.
   Waldheim always has denied any wrongdoing.
   Ceremonies Friday marking Anshluss drew few large crowds. Shops,
schools and businesses remained open, and many Viennese ignored a
nationwide moment of silence. Some public transport stood still and
the state-run radio fell silent during the observance.
   Austria's largest-circulation daily, the tabloid Neue Kronen
Zeitung, gave the anniversary events scant coverage.
   Chancellor Franz Vranitzky told a special Cabinet session Friday
that the Nazi invasion and annexation, or Anschluss, mattered to
Austrian politics today.
   ``The events of 50 years ago pose relevant, fundamental
questions about the essence of politics,'' Vranitzky said. ``If one
attempts to avoid them, they sooner or later return with greater
emphasis.''
   Vranitzky, in a later address to 900 students in Vienna's
historic Musikverein concert hall, urged young Austrians not to
``make blanket accusations against an older generation or to
reproach them'' for past mistakes.
   Speaking Friday at an evening service in Vienna's landmark St.
Stephen's Cathedral, Roman Catholic Archbishop Karl Berg of
Salzburg called on Austrians to recognize the mistakes of the past.
   Austrians must ``recognize guilt, feel regret and ask for
forgiveness,'' Berg told the several thousand people gathered in
the Gothic cathedral.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880312-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 0722EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-JailhouseLawyer     03-12 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jailhouse Lawyer,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmate Claims His Life Sentence Satisfied Because He Died Briefly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUBURN, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An inmate convicted of murdering two police
officers claims he has satisfied his sentence of 20 years to life
in prison because he ``died'' briefly during open-heart surgery.
   The heart and respiratory functions of Jerry Rosenberg, an
inmate at the Auburn Correctional Facility, stopped for about 90
seconds during surgery in Syracuse's University Hospital on Dec. 5,
1986, said attorney Richard Baumgarten.
   Rosenberg, a self-styled jailhouse lawyer, was denied parole
Wednesday for the fifth time since he became eligible for it in
1981. Rosenberg claims the parole board has no jurisdiction over
him because he had ``died,'' said Baumgarten, a spokesman for
Rosenberg.
   Baumgarten said he sent a letter to Gov. Mario M. Cuomo
requesting a pardon, and if it is denied, Rosenberg will pursue the
case in federal court.
   ``He cannot be forced to serve a second life sentence,'' he said.
   Baumgarten said Rosenberg has documentation to support his
claim, but wouldn't say what it is.
   Dan Hurley, the Syracuse hospital's communications director,
said the state considers a person dead only after he is declared
brain dead by two physicians, one of them a neurosurgeon or a
neurologist.
   Although he couldn't reveal Rosenberg's files without his
physician's approval, he said Rosenberg's case ``certainly wasn't
death as we know it.''
   Rosenberg was sentenced to death in February 1963 after he was
convicted of killing two policemen during a robbery in Brooklyn.
The death sentence was reduced in 1965 to 20 years to life.
   Rosenberg, who says he has earned three law degrees through
correspondence courses, said he is not licensed as an attorney, but
is recognized in state and federal courts as a legal representative
in more than 250 cases. He said he has been accepting thousands of
dollars in legal fees from inmates and others for 15 years.
   However, state Department of Correction officials last year
found him guilty of illegally receiving $8,800 in fees from inmates
and sentenced him to a four-year term in a special housing unit of
the prison. They said he needed a license to collect fees.
   Rosenberg may, however, represent inmates if he asks the
permission of the prison superintendent and provides his services
for free, according to state prison regulations.
   Rosenberg could not be reached for comment because he is in
solitary confinement.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
