<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man aboard a Pakistan International
Airlines jet fired two shots and wounded a security guard today
before being overpowered minutes before the aircraft landed near
the Afghan border, officials said.
   Karachi airport authorities said there were no other injuries
among the 143 passengers and 13 crew members aboard the A-300
Airbus. The jet, on a domestic flight from Karachi to Quetta,
landed safely.
   The incident occurred as the jet prepared to land at Quetta, a
city near the Afghanistan border in western Pakistan 375 miles
north of Karachi.
   The man entered the cockpit with a revolver and two security
guards tried to grab him, said the officials, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
   A scuffle ensued in the first class cabin during which the man
discharged his gun twice, wounding one of the guards, according to
officials.
   They said the second guard managed to subdue the gunman.
   Officials said the gunman has not been identified and his motive
was unclear.
   Pakistan's national news agency, APP, reported that the gunman
also was injured, but airport officials could not immediately
confirm this.
   They could not explain either how the man was able to smuggle a
firearm aboard the plane.
   Airport security usually is extremely strict in Pakistan.
Passengers pass through two metal detectors and have their carry-on
luggage inspected at least three times before boarding a flight.
</TEXT>
