<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-China     03-12 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-China,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shotgun Attack On Chinese Consulate Latest In Series</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A shotgun fired from a passing car blew out a
window of the Chinese Consulate in southwestern Japan, the latest
in a series of anti-Chinese incidents.
   Consul General Guo Chu and 15 other people were inside the
building when the shooting occurred Friday night, but no one was
hurt, officials said.
   Chief Cabinet Secretary Keizo Obuchi told a news conference
today the incident was ``extremely unfortunate'' and expressed hope
it would not hurt Sino-Japanese relations.
   Japan's Foreign Ministry called in Zhao Zhongxin, counselor at
the Chinese Embassy in Tokyo, and expressed regret over the
incident in the name of Foreign Minister Sosuke Uno.
   An unidentified person in a car fired a shotgun at the Chinese
Consulate in Fukuoka, 560 miles southwest of Tokyo, at about 10:50
p.m., police said.
   The blast broke a window and damaged the ceiling and walls on
the first floor of the three-story building, said Takanobu
Kashiwagi, a Fukuoka police spokesman.
   Two nearby policemen guarding the building heard the shot and
saw a car speed away, Kashiwagi said.
   Investigators found an abandoned car about a mile from the
consulate this morning. Kashiwagi said the car had been stolen in
Fukuoka two days earlier.
   Relations between China and Japan have deteriorated in recent
years, with China criticizing Japan over its increased military
spending and angry over a Japanese court decision awarding a
disputed student dormitory in Kyoto to Taiwan.
   China says ownership of the dormitory, purchased by Taiwan in
1952, should be transferred to China because of Japan's switch of
diplomatic relations from Taipei to Beijing in 1972.
   Some Japanese rightists have lashed out against the Chinese
criticism. Since last June, at least five monuments in different
parts of Japan dedicated to Sino-Japanese friendship have been
splattered with red paint. In September, a smoke bomb was hurled at
a wall at the Chinese Consulate in Osaka.
</TEXT>
