<1ST_LINE>r i PM-DancingLawsuit     03-12 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dancing Lawsuit,0245</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Courtroom Tale of Quickstep Dance Fiasco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elderly couple who crashed to the dance floor
during a vigorous quickstep ended up in the High Court in London,
where a judge said their testimony had put him off dancing for life.
   ``Ballroom dancing is not normally a dangerous pastime. I'm
terrified now _ I shall never go near a ballroom again,'' said the
judge, Sir Leslie Boreham, 70, as he threw the case out Thursday.
   Dance teacher Edith Spry, 72, had sought damages from
70-year-old Jack Plowright. She testified during a five-hour
hearing that she asked Plowright for a dance during a 1981 vacation
on the Spanish island of Majorca.
   Mrs. Spry said Plowright ``whirled me round like I had never
been whirled round before,'' leaving her breathless, bruised and
flat on her back on the dance floor.
   ``He was dancing at a terrific speed. I was quite frightened. .
.. But before I could say anything I was on the floor,'' Mrs. Spry
testified.
   Mrs. Spry sued Plowright for unspecified damages, claiming he
kicked her left leg and caused an ulcer when he fell on her. She
blamed his fast-paced dancing on incorrect footwear _ plastic
sandals.
   Plowright denied dancing boisterously and said he overbalanced
when his feet stopped during a turn. He said the floor was uneven.
   The judge decided that Plowright did not dance with reckless
abandon and dismissed the case.
</TEXT>
