<DOCNO> AP880312-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 0814EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-TrainSabotage     03-12 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Train Sabotage,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Train Inspector Gets Eight Years for Sabotaging Train</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A train inspector who tampered with the breaks of
a train because his relatives were refused seats has been sentenced
to eight years in prison, China's official Xinhua News Agency said
today.
   The report said a court in Lanzhou, northwest China, found Wang
Gang guilty of sabotage in dismantling six brake shoes on a
passenger train traveling from Urumqi to Zhenzhou on Jan. 18.
   It said Wang, an inspector at Yumen City in Gansu province,
became angered when he asked an attendant working on the train to
find two berths for his relatives and was told there were no
available seats.
   The faulty brakes were discovered after the train left the
station. They were replaced at the next station, the report said.
   China has been plagued this year by disasters on its overcrowded
railway system, with 34 people killed in a compartment fire, 19
killed in a head-on collision and 88 killed in a train derailment.
All three accidents occurred in January.
   The head-on collision, in northeast China's Heilongjiang
province, was blamed on sabotage, although there have been no
reported arrests.
   Railways Minister Ding Guangen resigned last week to take
responsibility for the accidents.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
