<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 0830EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GorillaTalk     03-12 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gorilla Talk,0410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gorilla May Find Romance at New Home</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GULF BREEZE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colossus, reputed to be the largest
lowland gorilla in captivity, is moving from frosty New Hampshire
to a spacious new home in Florida, where he'll get to enjoy the
sunshine and perhaps a little romance.
   The 600-pound gorilla is to fly in a chartered DC-3 Sunday from
Benson's Animal Park in Hudson, N.H., to nearby Pensacola. He'll
then be trucked to The Zoo, about 10 miles east of Gulf Breeze,
said Pat Quinn, president and director of the park.
   Colossus was captured as an infant 20 years ago in Africa and
has not seen another gorilla since then, but Quinn said he hopes to
introduce him to females of his species and breed him.
   ``We hope to socialize him so he will breed naturally with
females,'' Quinn said.
   The socialization process is to start by letting Colossus see,
smell and touch a male chimpanzee. Then he would be introduced to
another bachelor male gorilla or a infertile female, Quinn said.
   An initial attempt at breeding may be through artificial
insemination, and one potential recipient is Koko, the signing,
cat-loving gorilla owned by the Gorilla Foundation in Woodside,
Calif.
   Semen will be obtained from Colossus before he is moved and then
frozen.
   ``We are hoping to obtain some of that for use with Koko because
she is very anxious to become a mother,'' said Penny Patterson,
director of the Gorilla Foundation.
   Ms. Patterson said 16-year-old Koko's keepers know she wants to
have a baby because she has told them so through sign language.
That skill and her doting care of a pet kitten landed Koko on the
cover of National Geographic magazine.
   All Ball, so named by Koko because it was a tailless manx, was
hit by a truck and killed after the National Geographic story, but
Koko was given a replacement kitten named Smokey, now an adult cat
still living with her.
   Koko and a male gorilla, Michael, communicate with sign language
to express their feelings, ask for food and certain teachers and
inquire about other animals.
   Colossus' sperm may be used because captive gorillas sometimes
develop incest taboos against cage mates, so Michael would be
unsuitable, Ms. Patterson said.Another advantage is that Colossus
was captured in the wild as an infant and isn't inbred with zoo
gorillas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
