<1ST_LINE>u i PM-NIreland-Gibraltar 1stLd-Writethru a0488 03-12 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NIreland-Gibraltar, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0488,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three IRA Dead To Be Flown Home</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: INSERTS 2 grafs after 6th, `As a ...' to ADD Spanish Customs
comment. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `The bodies...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bodies of three IRA
guerrillas killed by British troops in Gibraltar will be flown to
Dublin Monday on a chartered plane, the IRA's political wing Sinn
Fein said today.
   Police said Friday night they will move in to stop any IRA
paramilitary display at the funerals and asked the families for a
public promise that there would be no such display. There was no
immediate reaction from the families.
   Last Sunday's killing of the three unarmed Irish Republican Army
guerrillas sparked nighttime rioting in Belfast much of the week.
Authorities have said the guerrillas were plotting a huge car bomb
explosion in the British colony of Gibraltar, on Spain's southern
tip.
   The Irish government had complained that there was no attempt to
arrest the guerrillas before they were shot.
   A Sinn Fein statement said Spanish customs had refused ``to
accommodate the return'' of the bodies of Mairead Farrell, 31,
Daniel McCann, 30, and Sean Savage, 24, on the first available
scheduled flight to Dublin.
   As a result, it said, the bodies will be put aboard a chartered
plane which will fly directly from Gibraltar to Dublin, from where
they will be taken to Belfast, in the British province.
   Spanish Customs spokesman Julio Verdu in La Linea de la
Concepcion, which borders Gibraltar, said today ``it is absolutely
false'' that the Spanish government had refused entry into Spain of
the three bodies.
   Verdu said Health Ministry officials had stayed on the job
overtime Friday night in case the families decided to transport the
bodies to Malaga.
   The bodies have been kept at the Gibraltar Royal Naval Hospital
while attempts have been made to find a way to return them to
Ireland.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA has been fighting to unite the
predominantly Protestant Northern Ireland with the overwhelmingly
Catholic Irish Republic under socialist rule.
   No date has been set for the funerals, but Sinn Fein sources in
Belfast have been hinting they may be held next Thursday, St.
Patrick's Day.
   IRA funerals in Northern Ireland have seen repeated violence as
angry crowds clashed with police trying to stop paramilitary IRA
members from firing over the coffin.
   Police say the ceremonial gunfire represents an illegal show of
arms. But despite their presence in force, paramilitaries shielded
by crowds of thousands often have managed to fire the traditional
salute.
</TEXT>
