<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Hermit'sFarewell     03-12 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hermit's Farewell,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family, Friends Bid Goodbye To `Hermit Of Chestnut Hill'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bill Britt, the ``hermit of Chestnut Hill''
whose refusal to leave his makeshift home in the woods cost him his
life, was remembered at his funeral as a colorful, articulate
``free spirit.''
   Fifty relatives and friends packed the funeral home Friday to
pay tribute to the garrulous, 52-year-old eccentric whose body was
found Monday in his lean-to at the Chestnut Hill cemetery.
Authorities said he had frozen to death about two weeks before.
   The funeral also attracted the media, and the room was lit up
with television lights, a touch which Britt's son said his father
would have enjoyed.
   ``My father would have loved this. He's got all the cameras
here,'' Britton Steven Boughner, 30, said.
   But if his father loved attention, he also cherished
independence. Said his son: ``He was a free spirit and he (taught)
me not to be afraid of anything or any individual.''
   Britt's daughter, Ingrid Boughner, 28, wept talking about the
father who was reunited with two of his three children only a year
ago.
   ``My father never really was a hermit,'' she said. ``He was a
naturalist. ... He was the most colorful and articulate human
being.''
   Britt's friend of two decades, birth control activist Bill
Baird, recalled Britt's ``passion for freedom, independence and the
beauty of the woods.''
   Also at the service were Britt's mother, Marion, 86, his two
brothers, and close friends like Sophie ``Bubbles'' Haggett. Ms.
Haggett spoke to Britt daily by telephone from her home in Malden
and would bring him soup and clothing. Britt died while the
70-year-old woman was laid up in the hospital.
   Britt's body was cremated. His ashes were to be scattered today
in the woods where he had lived.
   Britt was once an ordinary married man with three children and a
job in an office. All that changed after a painful divorce in 1969.
   Soon he cast off his three-piece suits and his three-piece name,
Britton William Boughner. He began to retreat to the woods at the
state-owned Chestnut Hill reservoir, near the affluent suburb of
the same name where he was born.
   But the ``hermit of Chestnut Hill'' was hardly a recluse. He was
shrewd, witty and stubborn, given freely to tears. He would ride
the trolleys and hunt for pay phones to call reporters, clad in
cast-off clothing and dragging an armful of plastic buckets.
   Bear-shaped and nearly toothless, Britt had blind eyes swollen
with infection. He refused welfare and lived on the nickels he got
for empty bottles and cans.
   Two years ago, officials began trying to force Britt to leave
the state land.
   Britt fought back. He showed the world a misunderstood hermit
who wanted only to be left among the trees. It landed him on ``Late
Night with David Letterman.'' Actor Mickey Rooney suggested a TV
movie about his life.
   A sympathetic judge respected Britt's wish for a suburban Eden
and ordered the state to find a suitable alternative site.
   Britt refused them all. But last July, he was finally ejected
from state land and moved to the adjacent cemetery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880312-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 0857EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p TheChicagoSun-TimesEndorsesBushAndDukakis     03-12 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>The Chicago Sun-Times Endorses Bush And Dukakis</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Sun-Times editorial board says the
newspaper will endorse Vice President George Bush for the
Republican presidential nomination and Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis as the best choice for Democrats.
   The board, in a statement released before formal editorial
endorsements are published Sunday, praised Bush's ``variety and
texture of public experience'' and said Dukakis would give his
party the best chance of regaining the White House.
   The rival Chicago Tribune on Friday endorsed Sen. Robert Dole
for the GOP nomination but has taken no stand on the Democratic
race in Tuesday's primary. The Tribune said Dole has at times been
``the lone Republican voice of reason and good sense on matters of
budget and foreign affairs.''
   ``We urge Illinois Republicans to give enthusiastic validation
to the Bush candidacy,'' the Sun-Times editorial board said in a
statement issued Friday.
   The editors cited Bush's past experience as a congressman, CIA
director, United Nations ambassador, national party chairman as
well as his current position as vice president.
   ``Rarely has a presidential candidate offered the variety and
texture of public experience that Mr. Bush represents,'' the
editorial board said.
   ``Mr. Bush has more inside knowledge of the workings of more
aspects of government than all but a few candidates in two
centuries,'' the newspaper's editors said.
   ``We have supreme confidence in Mr. Bush's understanding of
international affairs and his capability for stewardship in guiding
the United States through the mine fields of world politics,'' the
editors said.
   In their Democratic endorsement, the editors said, ``On balance,
we consider Governor Dukakis the best Democratic choice to grapple
with and attempt to master the awesome powers of the presidency.''
   ``There is no question _ no question at all _ of Mr. Dukakis'
skills, talent, fiscal prudence and sound instincts administering a
large bureaucracy,'' the newspaper's editorial board said.
   ``We also believe he represents the party's strongest contender
to regain the White House.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
