<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ChicagoEndorsements     03-12 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chicago Endorsements,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Retransmits to restore slug</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Chicago Sun-Times Endorses Bush And Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago Sun-Times editorial board says the
newspaper will endorse Vice President George Bush for the
Republican presidential nomination and Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis as the best choice for Democrats.
   The board, in a statement released before formal editorial
endorsements are published Sunday, praised Bush's ``variety and
texture of public experience'' and said Dukakis would give his
party the best chance of regaining the White House.
   The rival Chicago Tribune on Friday endorsed Sen. Robert Dole
for the GOP nomination but has taken no stand on the Democratic
race in Tuesday's primary. The Tribune said Dole has at times been
``the lone Republican voice of reason and good sense on matters of
budget and foreign affairs.''
   ``We urge Illinois Republicans to give enthusiastic validation
to the Bush candidacy,'' the Sun-Times editorial board said in a
statement issued Friday.
   The editors cited Bush's past experience as a congressman, CIA
director, United Nations ambassador, national party chairman as
well as his current position as vice president.
   ``Rarely has a presidential candidate offered the variety and
texture of public experience that Mr. Bush represents,'' the
editorial board said.
   ``Mr. Bush has more inside knowledge of the workings of more
aspects of government than all but a few candidates in two
centuries,'' the newspaper's editors said.
   ``We have supreme confidence in Mr. Bush's understanding of
international affairs and his capability for stewardship in guiding
the United States through the mine fields of world politics,'' the
editors said.
   In their Democratic endorsement, the editors said, ``On balance,
we consider Governor Dukakis the best Democratic choice to grapple
with and attempt to master the awesome powers of the presidency.''
   ``There is no question _ no question at all _ of Mr. Dukakis'
skills, talent, fiscal prudence and sound instincts administering a
large bureaucracy,'' the newspaper's editorial board said.
   ``We also believe he represents the party's strongest contender
to regain the White House.''
</TEXT>
