<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ClubFire 1stLd-Writethru a0462 03-12 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Club Fire, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0462,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Patrons Refuse To Leave Burning Disco</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `Thirteen firefighters ...,' with 1 graf to
add detail; SUBS last two grafs with 2 grafs to update cause of
fire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Firefighters had to force about 100 patrons at a
midtown Manhattan nightspot to leave the building after a fire
broke out in the back of the Club Oasis early today, a spokesman
said.
   ``They didn't want to leave the disco,'' said Fire Lt. Frank
Martinez.
   The fire, reported at 12:12 a.m. by residents in apartments
above the basement club, was declared under control around 3 a.m.,
Martinez said.
   Thirteen firefighters reported minor injuries, including a fire
captain who went to Lenox Hill Hospital with a cut head after he
fell in the basement of a nearby shop while battling the blaze,
Martinez said.
   Two people believed to be apartment residents were also sent to
hospitals, an elderly woman complaining of chest pains and another
woman suffering smoke inhalation, he said.
   About 100 firefighters were at the scene. The club runs under
three five-story buildings with about eight businesses and 30
apartments overhead, Martinez said.
   Some of the residents may not be allowed back into their
apartments until the units can be checked for possible structural
damage, Martinez said, adding that the Red Cross had relocated the
75 people.
   The department said after a preliminary investigation that the
fire had started in some rubbish in an alleyway behind the disco.
</TEXT>
