<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PLOShut 3rdLd-Writethru a0511 03-12 0642</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PLO Shut, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0511,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Says Order Gives PLO ``Legitimacy''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: RESTORES changes from previous leads; NOTE a0511 should have
been slugged 2nd Ld-Writethru.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The administration has reluctantly ordered the
closing of the PLO observer mission at the United Nations because
of a law Secretary of State George P. Shultz called ``one of the
dumber things that Congress has done lately.''
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III gave the Palestine Liberation
Organization mission in New York until March 21 to close, saying
the department would then go to federal court to enforce the
Anti-Terrorism Act of 1987.
   The 1947 treaty under which New York became U.N. headquarters
obliges the United States to let all accredited missions operate,
U.N. officials and the State Department have said.
   Despite the headquarters treaty, Congress passed the law
ordering the mission closed and President Reagan signed it into law
last Dec. 22 as part of a State Department spending bill. Rep. Jack
Kemp, R-N.Y., who played a leading role in the congressional
debate, called the PLO ``the world's most vicious terrorist
organization.''
   The State Department earlier had closed the PLO's information
office in Washington but opposed the law that would close its UN
office.
   ``For more than a century ... the Supreme Court has held that
Congress has the authority to abrogate treaties and international
law for the purpose of domestic law,'' Assistant Attorney General
Charles Cooper, head of the Justice Department's Office of Legal
Counsel, said Friday at a news conference. He said the Justice
Department is obliged to follow the congressional decision.
   Calling the law ``one of the dumber things that the Congress has
done lately,'' Shultz added:
   ``The administration opposed that law. And my opinion remains
that it is a very bad piece of legislation ... and the net result
of it is, from the standpoint of those who don't like the PLO _ and
I don't like the PLO _ but from the standpoint of those don't like
the PLO, what have they done?
   ``They've glorified the PLO and they've given legitimacy to the
PLO.''
   United Nations Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
``strongly protested this violation of the headquarters agreement''
during a Friday morning meeting he had with Herbert Okun, deputy
U.S. ambassador to the United Nations, said U.N. spokesman Francois
Giuliani.
   The secretary-general's legal staff is ``studying options,'' but
Giuliani refused to describe them or say if the United Nations
would join litigation on behalf of the PLO.
   Okun, in a letter to Perez de Cuellar, said the United States
refuses binding arbitration of the dispute over the mission in the
worst confrontation ever between the United Nations and its host
country.
   Cooper said the statute ``has superseded the requirements of the
U.N. headquarters agreement'' and that participation in an
international tribunal ``would be to no useful end.''
   The 159-nation General Assembly, in a special meeting last
month, asked the World Court in the Hague to rule on whether the
United States must agree to arbitration. Oral arguments are
scheduled for April 11.
   The Arab League's permanent observer at the United Nations,
Clovis Maksoud, said that if the United States presses to close the
mission, ``naturally one of the options would be ... that the 43rd
session of the (U.N.) general assembly would have to meet
elsewhere.''
   Several Arab diplomats have suggested that the General Assembly
move to Geneva if the mission in New York is closed.
   ``The call by all members of the U.N., Israel being the only
obvious exception, for the U.S. to abide by its treaty obligations,
was not heeded, and with the attorney general's decision the
international consensus was brushed aside,'' Maksoud said.
   The United States and Israel consider the PLO a terrorist
organization. But the United Nations recognizes it as the only
legitimate spokesman for Palestinians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
