<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StormRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0471 03-12 0643</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Storm Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0471,0658</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blizzard Blankets Plains, Closing Interstates, Stranding Travelers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf with 1 graf to UPDATE with I-94 in North
Dakota reopened.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BART ZIEGLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A major blizzard continued its slow march east across the
northern Plains today, stranding travelers and schoolchildren,
forcing authorities to close interstate highways and causing scores
of minor accidents.
   Snow combined with winds of 30 to 50 mph produced limited
visibility and drifts up to 10 feet deep from northeast Colorado
and southeast Wyoming into northern and western Minnesota.
   ``There's zero visibility. We're just advising people not to
travel right now,'' said Polk County, Minn., sheriff's dispatcher
Bob Janorschke.
   Conditions were so bad by 9 p.m. Friday that even snow plows
were pulled off roads in parts of Minnesota, the state
Transportation Department said.
   Wyoming state offices were closed Friday, although the
Legislature met. North Dakota Capitol workers were sent home about
an hour after they arrived.
   Blizzard warnings remained in effect today for much of the
eastern Dakotas and western Minnesota, and winter storm warnings or
winter storm watches were issued for sections of Minnesota,
Wisconsin, Iowa and Michigan.
   In Chadron, Neb., 31 inches of snow fell, with snow drifts 5
feet deep. Up to 40 inches of snow fell in two days in the
mountains of Utah at the Alta ski resort, with 37 inches at
Snowbird. Three to 4 feet fell around Lead and Deadwood on the
edges of South Dakota's Black Hills. Visibility in many areas was
down to zero.
   In western Nebraska, school bus driver Linda Barret and her 13
riders took refuge Thursday at a farm some 20 miles from Harrisburg
when the storm cut visibility, and bus driver Sharon Grubbs and her
eight riders, ages 7 to 13, wound up at a farm 17 miles from the
town.
   ``It looks as if the children will be snowed in at least until
this morning,'' Mrs. Barrett said Friday night.
   Power has been out at the second farm, owned by Jack and Karen
Holt, since late Thursday, cutting off the heat.
   ``You can see your breath in the house,'' said one of the
stranded youngsters, 14-year-old Jeff Rundell.
   Ms. Grubbs said the house was holding the heat to about 40
degrees.
   In the Nebraska Panhandle, Kimball Civil Defense Director Dan
Jenson estimated 600 stranded travelers spent Friday night in the
town of 3,800 residents. Many stayed with townspeople, Jenson said.
   Outside Scottsbluff, Neb., Jim and Elizabeth Davis of Hot
Springs, Wyo., spent about 15 hours stuck in their car before being
rescued Friday. Davis, 68, said he and his 67-year-old wife had
apples and candy, plenty of blankets and a full gas tank.
   Winds gusting to 69 mph were reported Friday at Akron, Colo.,
and to 67 mph at Fort Morgan, Colo., while gusts over 50 mph were
clocked at Rapid City, S.D.; Scottsbluff, Neb.; and Duluth, Minn.
   The wind blew off a 20-by-30 foot section of roof at a Rapid
City hotel, and it landed on three cars. No one was hurt.
   The weather threatened thousands of newborn calves, and ranchers
in the Nebraska Sandhills region worked around the clock to get
animals to shelter.
   ``We had 300 calves born yesterday. We're dragging them in,
separating them from their mothers,'' said Marianne Beel.
   The storm could cause severe losses to South Dakota's cattle
industry. Dick Kjerstad, chairman of the state Beef Checkoff
Campaign Committee said Friday.
   Interstate 80 was closed for more than 300 miles, from Walcott,
Wyo., to Big Springs, Neb., because of snowdrifts and low
visibility. Almost 140 miles of Interstate 25 were closed in
Wyoming, more than 200 miles of Interstate 90 in South Dakota, and
parts of Interstates 25 and 70 in Colorado. A 200-mile section of
I-94 in North Dakota, closed Friday afternoon, was reopened this
morning.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
