<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CadillacGetaway     03-12 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cadillac Getaway,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Limo Service Owner Charged With Using Cadillac As Getaway Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It was an unforgettable getaway car,
unfortunately for a man accused of using the white Cadillac
limousine in two holdups and one attempted robbery.
   A man dressed in a black leather jacket entered a doughnut shop
early Friday and demanded money, police said. He got $20 and sped
off in the white limousine, victims told officers. Soon afterward,
a man tried to hold up a convenience store but fled without any
money, again in a white Cadillac.
   At another convenience store, the man escaped with $6, and
witnesses remembered the limousine and black leather jacket, too.
   Officer Gerald Young cruised the neighborhood looking for the
car, and spotted one in front of a house two blocks from one of the
stores.
   Alexander J. Fulton Jr., 36, came out of his house while police
were checking the car and asked what was going on, police said.
   Police found a black leather jacket, and witnesses identified
both Fulton and the car, they said. Fulton was booked on two counts
of armed robbery and one of attempted armed robbery.
   Fulton, police said, is the owner of Fulton Limousine Service.
It has one car _ a white Cadillac limousine.
