<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 1051EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Tibet-Reporting     03-12 0692</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tibet-Reporting,0715</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chinese News Blockade on Tibet Highly Effective</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHENGDU, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Finding out what is happening in Tibet has
become almost as difficult in this age of high-tech
telecommunications as it was for 19th-century adventurers who had
to scale snow-swept mountains to reach the fabled land.
   Chinese authorities, hypersensitive to criticism of their
Tibetan policies, have shut out all foreign reporters since
pro-independence Tibetans on March 5 staged their fourth protest in
five months.
   They also have halted plane ticket sales to foreigners in
Chengdu, the main gateway to Tibet.
   In the 19th century, Westerners faced possible death from frigid
temperatures and bandits when they set out to discover the
mysteries of Tibetan Buddhist worship and the location of their
gold and silver fields.
   Foreign reporters in 1988 have no clear picture of what would
happen if they somehow managed to evade the barriers and enter
Lhasa. Expulsion from China is one possibility. No news agency has
attempted it.
   Concern remains high that authorities are using Lhasa's
isolation to crack down heavily on youthful militants among the
city's fewer than 1,400 Tibetan Buddhist monks.
   One of the few official reports on the March 5 protest concluded
ominously: ``Local religious leaders ... demand justice against the
rioters (and) are of the opinion that the people's government has
exercised too much restraint and shown enough tolerance and
patience towards these people.''
   Closing off Lhasa was easy this time because most travel there
already had been halted following three independence protests in
September and October in which at least 14 people were killed and
dozens others arrested.
   Fourteen foreign journalists who went to Lhasa to cover those
protests were given 48 hours to leave Tibet.
   An official report said one policeman was killed in daylong
clashes March 5 between police and protesters, but unconfirmed
reports put casualties at 21 Tibetans and three police killed.
   A U.S. State Department official told The Associated Press that
at least 6,000 people took part in the riots and pro-independence
rallies.
   Only one reporter, from Agence-France Presse, was in Lhasa on
March 5 and he was ordered to leave the next day.
   The fewer than one dozen foreign travelers left in Tibet's
mile-high capital of Lhasa have become the only link, albeit a weak
one, to the outside world.
   Backpackers staying in Lhasa's grubby cold-water guesthouses
have been interviewed several times each day by reporters
telephoning from Chengdu and Beijing.
   Most have acknowledged the limits of their information _ some
don't speak Tibetan or Chinese, and those who do fear bringing
police attention to their Tibetan friends and so stay away from the
protests.
   Many sympathize with the Tibetan cause and all are anxious to
keep a low profile aware that Chinese authorities have blamed
foreigners for past protests.
   Chengdu, a city of 2.6 million people in western China's lush
Sichuan province, about 760 miles east of Lhasa, became a listening
post last week for several Western reporters.
   They met Lhasa's only outgoing flight each morning and
intercepted the few dozen passengers in hopes of obtaining updates
on conditions in the city.
   The interviews produced unconfirmed reports of hundreds, perhaps
as many as 1,000 arrests since March 5, several beating deaths of
arrested protesters and shows of force by convoys of more than 100
trucks filled with armed police.
   Authorities have refused to comment on the reports. Officials in
the Tibetan Autonomous Region's Foreign Affairs Office brusquely
told reporters who telephoned to put their questions in writing.
   The result is that reporters are hard put to screen fact from
fiction.
   Most foreigners in Lhasa or arriving in Chengdu from Tibet were
amazingly patient in answering reporters' questions.
   A Japanese traveler who spoke barely any English nonetheless
spent an hour trying to convey what he saw to non-Japanese-speaking
reporters, by using gestures and imitating the sound of automatic
rifle fire.
   Reporters wondered whether their calls to Lhasa might get the
recipients in trouble. One Tibetan woman who answered the telephone
at a hotel willingly answered a few questions and then asserted,
``I'm not afraid because ...'' when the line suddenly went dead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880312-0081 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 1051EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Philippines     03-12 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Philippines,0686</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Tells Cadets To Fight Communism, Not Make Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGUIO CITY, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino told
military cadets Saturday to leave policy-making to civilians and
concentrate on defeating communist rebels on the battlefield.
   Meanwhile, a classified military intelligence report said the
rebels were losing support among the Filipino people and predicted
that the New People's Army would lose about half its fighters by
the end of Mrs. Aquino's term in 1992.
   The report appeared to contradict public statements by the armed
forces leadership that the rebellion is growing and poses a major
threat to Philippine democracy.
   Mrs. Aquino made her remarks during graduation exercises at the
Philippine Military Academy, on a mountaintop 130 miles north of
the capital of Manila.
   ``The insurgency war cannot be won by programs and speeches, nor
by commissions and committees,'' Mrs. Aquino told the crowd of
3,000. ``It will be fought, and it will be won, only by you and the
men you lead.''
   Mrs. Aquino reminded the 135 graduating cadets that ``policy is
the business of the civilian authorities.''
   She urged the graduates to place allegiance to the constitution
``above your deference to superiors or friendship for your peers.''
   Last year, cadets staged a brief sit-down strike in sympathy
with leaders of the August coup attempt in which at least 53 people
were killed and hundreds wounded, including Mrs. Aquino's only son,
Benigno Aquino III.
   Former Col. Gregorio ``Gringo'' Honasan, leader of the August
coup attempt and a graduate of the academy, was arrested last
December in Manila.
   Mrs. Aquino said the academy curriculum would be revised to
emphasize small unit leadership and combat skills. She also
promised that officers who display skill in combat will be favored
for promotion.
   Honasan complained that corruption and favoritism had sapped the
fighting spirit of the 160,000-member Armed Forces of the
Philippines.
   About 2,000 troops stood guard during the commencement ceremony.
Soldiers armed with M-16 rifles and grenade launchers searched
vehicles entering the grounds and helicopter gunships hovered
overhead during Mrs. Aquino's speech.
   On March 18, 1987, four people were killed when a bomb exploded
during rehearsals for the annual graduation exercise. Officials
blamed right-wing extremists but no one was ever charged in the
blast.
   The academy, modeled after the U.S. Military Academy at West
Point, was established in 1904 to train officers for the Philippine
Constabulary while the country was an American colony. It now
trains all branches of the military.
   A classified military intelligence report on the communist
insurgency, made in a National Intelligence Estimate at the end of
1987, predicted the Communist Party will ``suffer increasing
political isolation by 1992.''
   The report, distributed to Defense Secretary Fidel Ramos in
January, says the party will have to step up military operations to
recover political support.
   The report predicted the rebels would escalate their campaign of
assassinations of police and soldiers ``to continuously project a
position of strength.'' The rebels claimed responsibility for
killing scores of police, soldiers and officials in Manila last
year.
   But the report estimated that the New People's Army, the party's
armed wing, had already decreased from 24,430 fighters in 1986 to
21,520 by the end of last year. It predicted the rebel army would
decline in strength to 12,170 by 1992, when Mrs. Aquino's term ends.
   Rebel supporters, or ``mass base,'' had declined from 3.6
million people to 3.1 million people since Mrs. Aquino took office
and was expected to decline to about 1 million by 1992, the report
added.
   The Associated Press obtained excerpts of the report from
sources who insisted on anonymity.
   The report attributed the decline in rebel strength to
improvements in the combat capability of the armed forces and Mrs.
Aquino's economic and political reforms.
   The forecast contradicts the military's public assessment of the
rebel threat. Last week, the army said the New People's Army
numbered 25,000 fighters and that the guerrillas had drawn up plans
to take power by 1992.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
