<HEAD>Protest Against Governmental Appointment Of Governor, Mayors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 150 people rode a convoy of 47
trucks and vans through Taipei on Saturday to demand direct
elections for Taiwan's provincial governor and the mayors of the
island's two largest cities.
   Leaders of the opposition Democratic Progressive Party, standing
on top of the vans, chanted slogans during the two-hour
demonstration. Banners hung from the cars, including one that read:
``Governmental appointment is a symbol of authoritarian rule.''
   Under existing law, the provincial governor and the mayors of
Taipei and Kaohsiung, a southern port, are appointed by the
Nationalist government.
   Opposition lawmaker Kang Ning-hsiang, who organized the
demonstration, said the appointed officials ``lack support of the
people.''
   The demonstration was approved by the police and ended without
any violence.
