<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 1103EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Panama Bjt   03-12 0665</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama, Bjt,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sanctions May Hurt Panamanian Civil Servants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan's decision to withhold a $6.5
million payment owed to Panama next Tuesday was aimed at impairing
military strongman Manuel Noriega's ability to pay government
workers this coming week, according to U.S. officials.
   ``The timing was no coincidence,'' one official said, expressing
hope that the departure of Noriega could be hastened if government
workers, faced with economic hardship, join the ranks of the
opposition.
   The remaining sanctions Reagan imposed on Friday will not have
an immediate consequence, and the officials believe Noriega could
be out of office by the time they have an impact.
   The sanctions were the latest in a series of steps the United
States has taken over the past eight months to undercut Noriega,
who is under U.S. indictment on drug smuggling charges.
   According to reports from Panama, the government is so strapped
for cash that it has been considering several austerity measures to
deal with payroll budget shortfalls.
   They included delaying paychecks to the nation's 150,000
government workers, reducing their pay temporarily or giving them
partial payment in food instead of cash, the reports said.
   Outside the 15,000-member Defense Force, the regime's main
source of support has been government workers. If civil servants
begin turning against Noriega, that would narrow his already small
base of support even further, said the U.S. officials, insisting on
anonymity.
   The soldiers were paid last Thursday but Monday is payday for
the nation's 20,000 school teachers, and thousands of other
government workers are due their paychecks on Tuesday.
   Ambassador Juan B. Sosa, who opposes Noriega, said the cash
shortage forced Panama to default on a $39 million loan repayment
due last week to the government of Japan.
   Sosa has remained loyal to ousted President Eric Arturo Delvalle
and has refused to relinquish his post to a successor named by
Noriega. Sosa shares the Reagan administration view that Delvalle's
ouster by Noriega two weeks ago was unconstitutional.
   Before last Friday, the administration had suspended all
economic and military aid to Panama and ordered U.S.
representatives in international lending institutions to oppose
loan requests from Panama.
   Beyond that, it has lent its support to legal efforts by
Delvalle's representatives here to freeze Panamanian assets in the
United States.
   As a result, Panama does not have access to the revenues it
normally receives from American use of a trans-isthmian pipeline
that sends Alaskan oil on its way to East Coast U.S. ports. Those
revenues have been variously estimated at between $80 and $120
million a year.
   In addition, Panamanian assets in U.S. banks, estimated at $50
million, also have been frozen.
   Noriega has been attempting to rally support from his countrymen
by blaming the United States for Panama's financial problems. But
Secretary of State George P. Shultz said Noriega's campaign has not
worked and that the United States and the Panamanian people are
``on the same side.''
   Reagan tightened the screws on Friday when he ordered the $6.5
million fee due to Panama for canal-related services placed in
escrow. It will be released once civilian government is restored,
he said.
   Reagan also acted to strip Panama of the right to sell its
products in U.S. markets either duty-free or at the lowest tariffs
rates possible. These benefits are given to Panama under a system
of tariff preferences accorded to Third World countries and under
the Caribbean Basin Initiative, designed to help 21 countries in
that region.
   But most of Panama's income from U.S. exports would not be
affected by the sanction because they carry no duties to begin
with. Examples are bananas, shellfish, fish and coffee, which
account for well over half of Panama's annual U.S. exports.
   Two items which will be affected by Reagan's action are
sweaters, a $23.5 million business for Panama last year, and
petroleum products, $14.6 million. U.S. government estimates of
Panama's total exports to the United States range between $342
million and $388 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
