<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Frank     03-12 0142</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Frank,0147</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inquest Ordered Into Death of Nuremberg Interpreter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MERE, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hugh Wolfe Frank, chief interpreter at the
Nuremberg war crimes trials, has died. He was 75.
   Frank's body was found Thursday in a fume-filled car on a farm
track near the Wiltshire village of Mere in southwest England on
Thursday.
   Frank had been suffering from Parkinson's disease and was known
to be depressed about his worsening health.
   Wiltshire police said Saturday they did not suspect any crime in
connection with his death and had reported the facts to assistant
Wiltshire coroner Peter Stoddart.
   Frank, who was separated from his fifth wife, was a skillful
linguist who led the team of interpreters at the trials in
Nuremberg, West Germany, of top Nazis, including Hermann Goering
and Rudolf Hess.
   The Wiltshire coroner's office has ordered an inquest into his
death.
</TEXT>
