<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Spill,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>23 Tank Cars Spill Fuel After Derailment in Lithuania</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A speeding freight train derailed near the Baltic
port of Klaipeda in Lithuania, breaking open 23 tank cars that
spilled fuel over a 1,300-foot stretch of railway, the Tass news
agency reported Saturday.
   Tass said workers had blocked the flow of oil into the nearby
Baltic Sea, but did not make clear whether the spill was contained
before some of the oil reached the water.
   There was no indication whether there was any permanent
environmental damage or whether the accident caused casualties.
   The accident occurred near Klaipeda, but Tass did not say how
far away from the Soviet's major fuel-shipping port on the Baltic.
   ``Twenty three tanks, which were deformed and derailed, leaked
oil products to both sides of the railway embankment,'' Tass said.
   ``According to tentative information, the accident occurred
because safe speed at the turn of the railway was exceeded,'' the
news agency said, quoting a Baltic railway official identified as
Dmitri Blyaskin.
   Rail traffic resumed midday Saturday after a halt of several
hours, Tass said.
</TEXT>
