<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MultipleSlayings     03-12 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Multiple Slayings,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Men Cleared Of Murder Spree, Released</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOPE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities released two men they had
described as prime suspects in a two-state killing spree after the
men passed lie detector tests, their prints didn't match those on a
weapon and a witness failed to identify them.
   Authorities had planned to hold a hearing Friday night to
determine if they had probable cause to hold the men in connection
with four brutal slayings on Monday in Gainesville, Texas;
Farmersville, Texas; and in Saratoga, Ark. But when the two passed
lie detector tests, authorities canceled the hearing and agreed
unanimously to let the men go.
   The men were given tickets for a bus bound for Terre Haute,
Ind., hometown of one of the men, officials said.
   ``It was a misidentification is what it was,'' one of the men
said. ``We fit the description, so what else can you say? It's not
my fault somebody else out there looks like me.''
   The other man told The Dallas Morning News he was terrified to
learn ``I was facing death row.''
   ``I thought I was going to die for something I didn't do,'' he
said.
   Prosecuting attorney Jim Hudson Jr. said a man who reported
having a run-in with the apparent killers the night of the Arkansas
murder was unable Friday to identify the two men in custody.
   Their release leaves officials without a suspect in the slaying
of Deana Andrews Woodard, 23, who was found in her Gainesville,
Texas, mobile home Monday with her throat slashed, police said.
   Authorities believe Ms. Woodard's slaying is connected to the
fatal shootings of Cecil Floyd Morrison, 85, and Cecil Leonard
Morrison, 62. The two were killed in their Farmersville, Texas,
home. The men's pickup truck was found later in southwestern
Arkansas, and officers said a prescription of Ms. Woodard's was
found in the vehicle.
   A description of two men who hitched a ride Monday night with
Kenneth Olden, 34, of Saratoga, whose body was found Tuesday, led
authorities to the men who were arrested and released. Olden's body
was dumped along a road after he had been shot three times.
   ``They fit the description. But when all the evidence came back
in, the fingerprints didn't match (those lifted from a murder
weapon) and they passed a polygraph,'' said Hempstead County
Sheriff Don Worthey said.
</TEXT>
