<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-SouthAfrica     03-12 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-South Africa,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department Official to Hold South Africa Talks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assistant Secretary of State Chester A.
Crocker will hold his first talks in two years with South Africa's
foreign minister in an effort to advance a U.S. peace initiative
for southern Africa, the State Department said Saturday.
   Crocker's meeting with Roelof ``Pik'' Botha next week at an
unspecified European location also will give the United States an
opportunity to ``register concern'' about recent developments in
South Africa, spokeswoman Anita Stockman said. The United States
has complained about anti-dissent measures proposed in South Africa
in the past few weeks.
   A State Department working group arrived in Angola on Wednesday
to explore the possibility of further talks on getting the
estimated 40,000 Cuban troops out of the country as part of an
overall settlement, Stockman said.
   Since he took office in 1981, Crocker has been seeking to
negotiate a withdrawal of Cuban troops from Angola in return for
South African withdrawal from neighboring Namibia.
   The Cuban troops have been battling a powerful guerrilla force,
UNITA, which is backed by South African and U.S. assistance.
   In what appeared to be a major breakthrough when Crocker was in
Angola in January, Cuba declared its willingness in principle to
pull the troops out of the country, but the overall settlement that
would bring that about is still to be arranged.
   Angola has said South African willingness to participate in the
negotiations _ and abide by a United Nations resolution giving
independence to Namibia _ is a necessary ingredient of a settlement.
   Stockman said Crocker's meeting with Botha will ``afford an
opportunity to reassess South Africa's willingness to proceed
toward a settlement involving total Cuban troop withdrawal from
Angola and Namibian independence based on U.N. Security Council
resolution 435.''
   Crocker also is expected to restate U.S. demands for a cessation
of cross border forays by South African troops and concern about a
new crackdown on groups seeking more rights for the country's black
majority.
   Last month, the government outlawed the political activities of
17 anti-apartheid organizations. The government has also introduced
legislation to bar a wide range of organizations from receiving
foreign funds.
   Foreign governments and private agencies send millions of
dollars in assistance to these groups as a way of aiding South
Africans without sending funds to their government.
</TEXT>
