<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CulturalExchange     03-12 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cultural Exchange,0351</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan, Gorbachev Hail Mammoth U.S.-Soviet Cultural Fest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A three-week festival featuring Soviet music
opened with envoys for President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev praising the organizers of the cultural exchange for
bringing the two countries closer together.
   ``Making Music Together,'' with its 285 Soviet musicians,
dancers, composers and other artists, is the first part of an
exchange that will bring a celebration focusing on American
contemporary music to Moscow in the fall of 1989.
   Reagan's praise came in a letter to Sarah Caldwell, a key
organizer of the exchange and artistic director of the Opera
Company of Boston. It was read Friday night by Greg Guroff of the
government-run U.S. Information Agency.
   The letter described the event as ``one of the most ambitious
cultural projects ever undertaken between the United States and the
Soviet Union ... a testament to the potential of U.S.-Soviet
cooperation in artistic and cultural endeavors.''
   Soviet Ambassador Yuri Dubinin, who flew from Washington to
attend opening ceremonies, read Gorbachev's ``best wishes for
success for the benefit of peace, friendship and cooperation
between our two nations.''
   Also present at the ornate, turn-of-the century Boston Opera
House was Yuri Melentiev, the minister of culture of Russia, the
Soviet Union's largest republic.
   Melentiev told reporters the festival stood as a symbol of
improved superpower relationships in the wake of the meeting
between Reagan and Gorbachev in Washington late last year.
   The festival is in the red because of unexpected costs that
drove the price tag above the estimated budget of $2.4 million to
$3.3 million, and organizers last month seriously considered the
idea of declaring bankruptcy and canceling the event.
   But organizers said they decided not to call if off after being
told by the State Department that cancellation could mar relations
with the Soviet Union.
   Harold Hestes, president of the Greater Boston Chamber of
Commerce and a key fund-raiser, said shortly before the opening
ceremonies that the original shortfall of $900,000 had been reduced
to about $200,000.
</TEXT>
