<1ST_LINE>r p AM-DemocraticSuperdelegates 1stLd-Writethru a0546 03-12
0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democratic Superdelegates, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0546,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Urge For Brokered Convention Cools Among Democrats</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Corrects date Michigan caucuses to March 26 in graf 17 bgng
`Richard Gephardt ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ESPO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush's apparent lock on
the Republican presidential nomination is beginning to cool
Democratic excitement over the prospect of a brokered national
convention.
   Barring a collapse of unimaginable proportions, Bush will spend
the final months of the primary season seeking support for the fall
campaign from independent voters and potential Democratic converts.
   The longer the Democratic nominating war goes on, the better
Bush likes it. A Democratic National Convention this summer
featuring bloodletting on prime-time TV would suit him just fine.
   Democrats know this well, and that may give them an impetus to
rally around a candidate sooner rather than later, particularly
given Bush's evident vulnerability on the Iran-Contra affair.
   No one understands this better than Jimmy Carter. The former
president told an audience in Connecticut last week that he emerged
from the 1976 and 1980 conventions ``weaker than I went in.''
   He said the Democrats should find a ``winning ticket'' and unite
behind it in Atlanta.
   ``Why is 51 percent the magic number?'' asks New York Gov. Mario
Cuomo. ``Let's pick the guy who's ahead after California,'' the
last state to vote in the primary season.)
   ``If Mike Dukakis has 41 percent (of the delegates), get
everybody together in a room and say, `Jesse (Jackson) Gore,
Gephardt, you came close, but Mike's the candidate.''
   That would avoid what Carter calls the ``circus'' type of
convention that twice nominated him.
   Carter's lead over Republican Gerald Ford declined steadily
during the 1976 fall campaign, although he won a close call. In
1980, weakened politically, he triumped over Sen. Edward M. Kennedy
in an emotional convention struggle before losing a landslide to
Ronald Reagan.
   Carter says that this time, he and the 645 so-called Democatic
superdelegates, ``will have a burning desire to put together a
winning ticket'' when they convene in Atlanta.
   That makes the Senate Democratic caucus, which picks 43
delegates on April 19, and the House Democratic caucus, which picks
210 delegates a day later, as critical as any Democratic primary
waged with television advertising, phone banks and direct mail.
   The same is true for the 362 members of the Democratic National
Committee who are superdelegates, and the 25 governors.
   ``The key now to this thing ending early is superdelegates,''
says Robert Beckel, a Democratic campaign consultant not aligned
with any of this year's contenders. ``They're also the key to not
ending it early.''
   Any candidate who succeeds in picking up a large amount of
support from the people selected in those two congressional
meetings will be able to send a clear signal to the party that he
is the presumptive nominee, even before the primary season ends.
   To earn that support, a contender would presumably have to score
well in the industrial state contests leading up to the
congressional caucuses _ Illinois, Michigan, Connecticut, Wisconsin
and New York.
   Richard Gephardt, the Missouri congressman, already has the
support of several dozen House members. He probably could
consolidate his strength if he mounted a comeback after his poor
Super Tuesday showing. But he if fails to win in Michigan's
caucuses March 26, he is a likely dropout, and his supporters are
free to go elsewhere.
   Sen. Albert Gore of Tennessee must show quickly that he can win
in the industrial states or he will have littel claim on the
allegience of Congress members.
   Jesse Jackson is in the process of obtaining a large bloc of
perhaps 800 delegates, and figures prominently in the brokered
convention scenarios that occupy Democratic political insiders. He
will get his share of support in Congress, as elsewhere, but most
House and Senate members aren't likely to go over to his side.
   The Democrat who now looks in the strongest position in the
race, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, would have to run well in
the industrial states, and probably signal his willingness to name
a southerner as his running mate in the fall.
   Carter said he and the party leaders want a winning ticket, and
Dukakis, for all the boasting over his primary wins in Texas and
Florida, ran poorly among disaffected Democrats that the party
needs to win the presidency.
   Gore whipped him among Democrats who voted for President Reagan
in 1984, 39 percent to 23 percent, according to ABC interviews on
Super Tuesday with primary voters in 12 southern states.
   Dukakis defeated Gore among liberals and the two split the
moderate vote. But Gore won among self-described conservatives, 38
percent to 21 percent, according to the ABC polls.
</TEXT>
