<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DardenExecution     03-12 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Darden Execution,0692</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Darden Has Dodged Death Penalty More Than Once</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A condemned man who insists he's
innocent and whose case has become a rallying cry for death penalty
opponents is seeking his seventh reprieve from the electric chair,
with just two days left before his scheduled execution.
   Willie Jasper Darden faces execution early Tuesday at Florida
State Prison near Starke for the September 1973 killing of
furniture store owner Carl Turman during a $15 robbery.
   ``Let me tell you something. Willie Darden is not a murderer!''
Darden, 54, told The Associated Press in a 1985 interview, a claim
that he has made to dozens of reporters who have interviewed him.
   Darden has received six stays of execution, more than any other
Florida inmate, and his case has attracted international attention,
with supporters saying he was a victim of racial prejudice at his
trial because he is black.
   Two witnesses say they have information to back up his story,
but their accounts were dismissed as mistaken and not new by the
lawyer who prosecuted Darden.
   ``There is no question he is guilty,'' Ray McDaniel, now a
Bartow attorney, said Friday in a telephone interview.
   McDaniel said he believed Darden will die Tuesday. ``I don't
think you will find a judge with the guts to issue a stay,'' he
said.
   ``I think it's time. I think it's about 12 years too late,''
McDaniel said, who added that Darden was linked, but never charged,
with other murders.
   Attorneys for the Office of Capital Collateral Review filed an
appeal Friday with the Florida Supreme Court.
   Darden's is one of the most-litigated cases involving a death
row inmate, with nearly 100 judges involved in decisions. It has
been before the U.S. Supreme Court four times already.
   McDaniel discounted the assertions of two people who repeated
claims Friday at an Amnesty International news conference in
Tallahassee that they believe Darden is innocent.
   The Rev. Sam Sparks, a Baptist minister, and Christine Bass, a
Lakeland secretary, said they had information they say might clear
Darden of the crime.
   ``I know Willie Darden is innocent. It is not a belief, it is a
knowledge,'' said Ms. Bass.
   Sparks said Turman's wife had told him that all blacks looked
alike to her and that her identification of Darden was unimportant
because lawyers had told her that Darden committed the crime. Helen
Baum, formerly Helen Turman, recently denied having made that
statement to Sparks and reaffirmed her identification of Darden as
the man who shot her husband.
   Ms. Bass said Darden's car was broken down near her home until a
tow truck arrived about 25 minutes before the robbery, eight miles
away.
   McDaniel said the two are mistaken about the times and that the
defense knew their claims at the time of the trial.
   Amnesty International officials have claimed Gov. Bob Martinez
is rushing to execute Darden for political reasons.
   The governor signed a seventh death warrant for Darden on March
8, just a day after the U.S. Supreme Court refused to intervene,
and set his execution for Tuesday, giving Darden's attorneys less
than a week to prepare his case.
   ``I think what the governor is looking for some kind of
ritualistic sacrifice that he can go through to prove he's tough on
crime,'' said Magdaleno Rose-Avila, national director of Amnesty
International's campaign to abolish the death penalty. He noted
that the governor's popularity rating has been low in recent polls.
   When Martinez signed the sixth death warrant in Darden's case
earlier this year, Soviet dissident Andrei Sakharov, American
actress Margot Kidder and British rock star Peter Gabriel urged
clemency for Darden. Sakharov won the 1975 Nobel Peace prize for
his defense of human rights in the Soviet Union.
   The governor's spokesman said politics had nothing to do with
the decision.
   ``International attention has no real bearing on whether a
legally imposed sentence that has been upheld by the courts should
be carried out,'' said press secretary Jon Peck.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
