<1ST_LINE>r i AM-StadiumCollapse     03-12 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Stadium Collapse,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maltese Player Recalls Horror Of Tripoli Stadium Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A soccer player who witnessed a deadly stadium
collapse in the Libyan capital last week said he thought Tripoli
had been hit by an earthquake.
   ``Suddenly there was a rumble ... and then the bodies fell
down,'' Maltese player John Buttigieg told the Rome daily Il
Messaggero in an interview published Saturday.
   Part of the grandstand collapsed Thursday after some of the
60,000 spectators at the 75,000-seat June 11 Stadium panicked
because of a knife fight, according to reports.
   News reports from Malta and Yugoslavia said 20 people were
killed and that scores of people were injured. Radio Malta in a
report from Tripoli said at least 17 people died and that two
people were arrested.
   The reports conflicted with those from the Libyan news agency
JANA, which said two people were killed and 16 others were
hospitalized.
   Buttigieg said at first he ``screamed like a madman'' at his
team captain that it was an earthquake.
   ``The grandstand in front of me was coming down like a sand
castle and the fans ... fell by the tens, by the hundreds,''
Buttigieg was quoted as saying.
   ``Three years ago I saw on television the scene at Heysel, but
in Tripoli it was worse, much worse,'' he added, referring to the
May 1985 riot by English fans at Brussels' Heysel Stadium that
killed 39 people.
   ``After a part of the third tier of seats, the highest, fell on
the second tier, it was hell. There was a continuous scream ... I
saw people run toward the dead,'' he said.
   ``The referee told us to go into the dressing rooms. But we
couldn't. The entrance was blocked by bodies and pieces of
cement,'' he said.
   The Belgrade daily Politika Ekspres said the incident began when
several fans pulled out knives during a quarrel.
   Seeking shelter nearby, spectators toppled an iron fence. At the
same time, a 6-foot-thick, 15-foot-high wall crashed down, the
newspaper said.
   The paper said many people were injured when fans stampeded
toward the exits.
   ``People began to enter the field,'' said Buttigieg. ``They ran
toward the collapsed grandstand. Perhaps they wanted to help the
injured, but no, they wanted to fight. With whom, I do not know.''
   Politika Exspres said about 5,000 fans chased those who had
brandished weapons. One of them was caught, but police managed to
drag him free from the enraged crowd, it said.
   The Maltese paper L'Orizzont reported that Libyan leader Col.
Moammar Gadhafi had planned to attend the match, which opened a
sports festival in Tripoli. However, at the last moment he changed
his mind and was represented at the match by a city official.
   The exhibition game was stopped in the 43rd minute and did not
resume.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
