<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AirPanama     03-12 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Panama,0296</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Grounds Air Panama in U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has grounded Air Panama's U.S.
operations, freezing the company's assets while he decides which
leader of Panama should control the government-owned airline.
   ``Basically the airline is out of service,'' said Mark Cohen,
the Miami attorney who sued to seize Air Panama's assets on behalf
of Eric Delvalle, Panama's president-in-hiding.
   U.S. District Judge William Hoeveler on Friday issued a 10-day
restraining order freezing the airline's assets while he considers
which Panamanian government should control the company _ Delvalle
or ruling military stongman Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   Noriega was indicted last month on drug trafficking charges by
federal grand juries in Tampa and Miami. Soon afterward, Delvalle
ordered Noriega to resign, but the Panamanian assembly backed
Noriega and ousted Delvalle.
   Each man contends he is Panama's legitimate ruler; the United
States recognizes only Delvalle's claim.
   Attorneys for Air Panama did not attend the hearing but
responded to Hoeveler's questions by telephone.
   An Air Panama reservations clerk in Miami said Saturday that no
Air Panama officials would be available until Monday.
   Air Panama's assets in the United States include two Boeing 727
jets, ground equipment and facilities, tickets that can be
exchanged for cash and an undetermined amount of money in U.S.
banks, Cohen said.
   Peter Reaveley, head of the Aviation Development Department at
Miami International Airport, said curtailment of Air Panama service
should not have much of an impact on travel to the Central American
nation.
   ``Business and tourist travel to Panama has already been drying
up,'' he said.
   Air Panama has been flying once daily from Miami to Panama City.
Eastern Airlines and Pan American Airways also have daily service
there.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
