<DOCNO> AP880312-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 1439EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     03-12 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florence Ann Felton doesn't monkey
around when there is a baby beast in need at her husband's zoo _
she takes the critters home.
   Felton, whose husband George Felton is the director of the
Greater Baton Rouge Zoo, can't bear it when the animals become
orphaned or rejected by their natural mothers. ``I love them,'' she
said of her furry patients.
   ``The babies, though, are exotic _ wild. They do not make good
pets,'' Mrs. Felton said.
   ``I've raised them on bottles, but I know they have to go
back,'' she said.
   ``The main problem is getting them on a bottle,'' she added.
``Once they're on a bottle, it's no problem.''
   The Feltons live near the zoo in a home that has been modified
for easy care of baby animals.
   They have raised chimps, bears, cougars, otters, leopards,
jaguars, small deer, antelope and other hoofed stock, baboons,
monkeys, lions, and tigers.
   Baby beasts must be fed every two hours, with feedings spread
out gradually. Mrs. Felton said animal babies got her up more often
during the night than did her own children, all of whom are now on
their own.
   Do the animals ever remember her?
   Some do, she said. Two young cougars she once helped raise would
stand up at the zoo with their paws on the wire, trying to get her
to scratch their noses.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ASHLAND, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ashland women deny they are ladies of
leisure, despite a recent report saying there are fewer of them in
work force than anywhere else in the country.
   The 1988 Congressional District Fact Book said only 31.6 percent
of the northeastern Kentucky women are employed, while the national
average for working women was 54.7 percent in 1986.
   But some members of the American Business Women's Association in
Ashland dispute the finding.
   ``I've got three daughters and two daughters-in-law and they all
work,'' said Margaret Moore. ``I've worked all my life. All the
women I know work.''
   Helen Hunt, vice president of the association, said she doesn't
think Ashland is much different than any other area.
   ``Usually women can find work here quicker than men,'' she said.
   On the other hand, Prince Georges County, Md. topped the list of
working women with 62.6 percent; Arlington, Va., was second with
62.2 percent, and Bloomington, Minn., ranked third at 62.2 percent,
the book said.
   Ranking slightly above Ashland are Huntington, W.Va., 31.9
percent; Washington, Pa., 36.2 percent, and the economically
depressed South Bronx section of New York City, 36.5 percent, the
book said.
   The book was published by the Joint Center for Political
Studies, a Washington, D.C., think tank, which used U.S. Census
data to determine its rankings.
   One explanation for the small percentage of working women in
Ashland might be that males traditionally have held the high-paying
jobs at large local employers such as Ashland Oil and Armco Inc.
   ``Perhaps it wasn't necessary for women to work in some
situations,'' said Mike Sturm, employment and training program
supervisor with the Kentucky Department of Employment Services in
Ashland.
</TEXT>
