<1ST_LINE>r p AM-SouthCarolinaAt-A-Glance     03-12 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Carolina At-A-Glance,270</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are the methods for picking
delegates from South Carolina to attend the 1988 Democratic and
Republican national conventions this summer.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Method: Caucus
   Date: Saturday, March 12
   Candidates filed: Bruce Babbitt, Michael Dukakis, Richard
Gephardt, Albert Gore, Gary Hart, Jesse Jackson, Paul Simon.
   Pledged delegates: 44 Super elegates: 4 TOTAL: 48
   Delegates allocated: Saturday, March 12
   Selection of delegates: Saturday, April 16
   
   South Carolina uses a three-step process of caucuses and
conventions for picking its delegates to the Democratic National
Convention.
   Precinct caucuses on March 12 pick delegates to the county
conventions later in the month, which name delegates to the state
convention on April 16. Partricipants at each step of the process
will be divided according to presidential preferences and are
pledged from one level to the next.
   Twenty-nine pledged national convention delegates from
congressional districts will be chosen and allocated in
congressional district caucuses at the state convention. The rest
of the state's 15 pledged national convention delegates will be
chosen at the state convention and will be allocated among
presidential candidates in proportion to presidential preference
expressed by state convention delegates.

</TEXT>
<HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Method: Primary
   Date: Saturday, March 5
   Delegates: 37
   Delegates allocated: Saturday, March 5
   Selection of delegates: Saturday, April 9
   
   South Carolina Republicans awarded all of their national
convention delegates to Vice President George Bush in a
winner-take-all primary on March 5.
   The delegates from congressional districts will be picked at
district conventions in the next few weeks.
   The at-large delegates will named at the state convention in
April.
</TEXT>
