<HEAD>Tibetans Rap China In London, New Delhi, Zurich</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to include Zurich protest; picks up
3rd graf pvs: About 150...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tibetan women set fire to a Chinese flag
and demanded freedom for their homeland on Saturday, vowing to
return to the region they fled nearly three decades ago.
   In London, about 50 Tibetan demonstrators protested outside the
Chinese Embassy. There was no response from the embassy and police
maintained a discreet watch on the demonstrators, who ended their
vigil without incident.
   In Switzerland, about 400 Tibetans carried banners that said
``China Out of Tibet,'' and ``Long Live the Dalai Lama'' on a
peaceful march through Zurich's inner city.
   About 150 Tibetan refugees participated in the New Delhi
demonstration, one of the latest last week to mark the 29th
anniversary of an unsuccessful uprising against Chinese rule in the
Tibetan capital of Lhasa.
   ``The pride and might of Communist China will not crush the
spirit of Tibetan nationalism,'' the Tibetan Women's Organization,
which organized the New Delhi protest, said in statement.
   Indian policewomen stood by and watched the Tibetan women burn
the red flag of China near Parliament.
   Tsewang Topgyal, a spokesman for the demonstrators, fled his
country at the age of 5 in the wake of the violent revolt in 1959.
He said ``this anniversary is like Christmas for Tibetans. It is a
time when we remember family and friends at home.
   ``There are few Tibetans who have not lost members of their
immediate family due to the Chinese presence there,'' he said.
   On March 10, 1959, Tibetans revolted against their Chinese
rulers, who responded with a brutal crackdown. India is the home of
at least 100,000 Tibetan refugees who fled Tibet along with their
leader, the Dalai Lama.
   The anniversary of the Tibetan revolt coincides with an upsurge
in anti-Chinese rioting in Lhasa.
   An official report said one policeman was killed in daylong
clashes March 5 between police and protesters in Lhasa, but
unconfirmed reports put casualties at 21 Tibetans and three police
killed.
   During three independence protests in September and October, at
least 14 people were killed and dozens arrested.
</TEXT>
