<2ND_LINE>AM-Syria-US, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0595,0450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Syria Rejects U.S. Proposal For Mideast Peace</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: SUBS 14th graf to CORRECT to last week, sted this week. Pick
up 15th pvs, `Sharaa said...'</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syria on Saturday rejected an American
proposal for an Arab-Israeli peace settlement, submitted last week
to Arab and Israeli leaders by Secretary of State George P. Shultz.
   Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa also said he did not
believe any other Arab leader would support the plan.
   ``We have studied the American proposal and we think the plan,
as presented to us, is not acceptable. We also believe that it is
not acceptable to any other Arab side,'' Sharaa told reporters.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization and Israeli Prime Minister
Yitzhak Shamir also have rejected the plan. Shamir's rival in the
coalition government, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres, supports the
plan.
   Sharaa spoke at Damascus Airport after seeing off his Swedish
counterpart, Sten Andersson. Andersson left for home after a
24-hour visit and talks with President Hafez Assad and Sharaa on
the Arab-Israeli conflict.
   Sharaa's statement was the first outright Syrian rejection of
the plan, which Shultz submitted to Assad during a visit to
Damascus March 4.
   Shultz handed copies of the proposal to King Hussein of Jordan,
Shamir, Peres and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak.
   The proposal, aimed primarily at halting violence that has raged
in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip since Dec. 8, called for
limited self-rule for 1.5 million Palestinians living under Israeli
occupation.
   It also called for the formation of a joint
Jordanian-Palestinian delegation to negotiate a permanent
settlement in the West Bank and Gaza under an international peace
conference to convene by May 1.
   At a later parley, other Arab-Israeli conflicts, including the
future of the Syrian Golan Heights, occcupied by Israel in the 1967
war, would be discussed.
   Shultz had asked that the leaders concerned respond to his
proposal within 10 days.
   The Syrian president, speaking at a rally on Tuesday, had
indicated he rejected the plan, saying Israel did not want peace
and that the Arabs have no alternative but to keep up the fight
against the Jewish state.
   But he did not openly reject the plan.
   Earlier last week, Assad discussed the proposal with Hussein,
the Jordanian monarch, during a meeting in Damascus.
   Sharaa said ``we hope the American adminstration would come up
with a much clearer proposal,'' leaving the door open for
additional U.S.-Syrian consultations.
   Sharaa said Syria would not accept any settlement that is not
based on ``the termination of Israel's occupation and recognition
of Palestinian rights'' to self-determination and the establishment
of a state.
</TEXT>
