<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Contra 1stLd-Writethru a0556 03-12 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0556,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McFarlane Plea A Major Breakthrough for Iran-Contra Prosecutor</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: FIXES spelling of Salvador in penultimate graf bgng, `The
charges'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By allowing Robert C. McFarlane to plead
guilty to four misdemeanor counts, Independent Counsel Lawrence E.
Walsh virtually secured a major prosecution witness if other
players in the Iran-Contra affair go to trial.
   McFarlane's promise of full cooperation as part of the plea
agreement is a prize for Walsh. The former national security
adviser was among the inner circle of Reagan administration aides
who masterminded the Iran-Contra scheme.
   Walsh said McFarlane's cooperation would solve the technical
problem of ``joinder.'' Legal experts said this means Walsh could
have live testimony from a crucial player instead of having to
build his case around documents.
   McFarlane, who was national security adviser from October 1983
through November 1985, initiated the review of U.S. arms policy
toward Iran. After leaving the White House he remained a key
policymaker, leading an unsuccessful arms-for-hostages mission to
Tehran in May 1986.
   His guilty plea focused on his role in secret U.S. assistance to
the Nicaraguan Contras at a time Congress had banned such aid.
   He admitted that he withheld information about the activities of
Lt. Col. Oliver L. North and other members of the National Security
Council staff in three 1985 letters to House committees.
   He also admitted withholding information from the House Foreign
Affairs Committee when he told the panel on Dec. 8, 1986, that he
was unaware of any efforts to solicit donations for the Contras
from a third country.
   Although Walsh and McFarlane agreed that the cooperation was
voluntary, the independent counsel acknowledged McFarlane could
have faced much more serious perjury charges if he was
uncooperative.
   Each of the misdemeanor counts of withholding information
carries a maximum one year prison term. By contrast, felony perjury
charges carry a maximum of five years in prison, and larger fines
also could be levied.
   Walsh said McFarlane's cooperation wasn't the only reason he
went the misdemeanor route.
   He cited McFarlane's ``undisguised demonstration of remorse
after the false testimony was given in which he tried to correct
his testimony; and actually imposed injury upon himself in a fit of
depression,'' a reference to McFarlane's attempted suicide via an
overdose of Valium last year.
   While admitting his guilt, McFarlane told reporters he acted at
a time that relations between Congress and the White House ``broke
down so tragically.''
   ``My actions were motivated by what I believed to be in the
foreign policy interest of the United States,'' he said.
   McFarlane's comments were reminiscent of remarks by former CIA
Director Richard Helms on Oct. 31, 1977, when he pleaded no contest
to two misdemeanor charges under the same law used by Walsh.
   The charges against Helms arose from his testimony to the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee that the CIA had made no attempt to
prevent the election of Marxist Salvador Allende as president of
Chile in 1970.
   ``I found myself in a position of conflict,'' said Helms. ``I
had sworn by my oath to preserve certain secrets ... I didn't want
to lie. I didn't want to mislead the Senate. I was simply trying to
find my way through a very difficult situation in which I found
myself.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880312-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 1610EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Stalin     03-12 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Stalin,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Magazine Publishes Late Writer's Memoir on Stalinism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A monthly magazine has published the first half of
an unfinished memoir by late poet Konstantin M. Simonov in which he
explores the shame felt by Soviets like himself who aided the
repressions of dictator Josef V. Stalin.
   Simonov began the memoir in 1979 but died in 1980 before he
could finish it.
   He wrote the book ``for the archives'' and told his secretary
that he did not expect to see the memoir published in his lifetime,
explained an accompanying publisher's note in the March issue of
Znamya, a literary journal.
   Articles and books re-examining the legacy of Stalin have been
appearing regularly over the past year as Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's campaign for glasnost, or openness, encourages broader
discussion of social and historical problems.
   The memoir, ``Through the Eyes of a Person of My Generation,''
attempts to explain, without excusing, the behavior of those who
grew to regard Stalin's excesses as a normal state of affairs.
   Referring to his acceptance of the arrest and exile of three
aunts in the 1930s, Simonov wrote four decades later that such
events ``which seem monstrous and impossible today, were then a
norm and gradually became habitual.''
   He wrote that the rationale he adopted at the time was ``you
can't make an omelette without breaking eggs.''
   Simonov, who was twice honored with the Stalin Prize for
literature and earned numerous other accolades during his writing
career, was one of the many literary figures who followed the
government's lead in denouncing poet Anna Akhmatova, writer Mikhail
Zoshchenko and others in a 1946 purge of the intelligentsia.
   He referred to the role he played in ruining the careers of
contemporaries only as ``the events of 1946,'' acknowledging that
his readers would know what he meant.
   Simonov had confessed to sinning against his conscience in
denouncing respected writers and artists. In the way of atonement,
he championed the suppressed works of writer Mikhail Bulgakov and
eventually succeeded in getting published his masterpiece, ``The
Master and Margarita.''
   The weekly newspaper Moscow News published a commentary on the
Simonov memoir, observing that Simonov was trying to explain why it
is possible for many Russians to feel both awe for Stalin's
accomplishments and revulsion over his purges.
   The second half of the unfinished memoir is to be published in
April edition of Znamya, the journal said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880312-0131 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 1613EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-UAW-Chrysler     03-12 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UAW-Chrysler,0656</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Early Talks Only Way To Mend Damaged Relationship with Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chrysler Corp.'s failed attempt to quietly sell
off a fifth of the company before its United Auto Workers contract
expired has created a fracture in labor relations that the two
sides hope can be healed at the bargaining table.
   The No. 3 automaker once planned to use the months before its
three-year UAW contract expires Sept. 14 to rid itself of most
parts operations by selling its 28,000-worker Acustar Inc.
subsidiary.
   Under that plan, Chrysler could have evaded restrictions on
closing plants or shifting inside work to outside suppliers that
already are in place at Ford Motor Co. and General Motors Corp.
under the established UAW pattern contracts for the auto industry.
   Instead, Chrysler found itself with a work force whose anger
exploded over the possible sale and remains largely unappeased by
Chrysler's retreat in the face of a threat of crippling
plant-by-plant strikes.
   ``There's still a lot of hard feelings and the central issue is
still not settled,'' said UAW Local 412 President Jim Jensen, whose
local represents engineers and other salaried Chrysler workers in
the Detroit area.
   Rather than allow the anger to simmer and build during the three
or four crucial months before contract talks open, hurting chances
of a settlement and continued quality production, Chrysler asked
for early negotiations.
   ``It's always important to resolve issues that are
outstanding,'' said Chrysler's chief negotiator, human resources
Vice President Anthony St. John. ``We've had some convergence of
issues that have been very difficult for the union and for
Chrysler.''
   The UAW agreed last week, marking the third time in the last 10
years that the two will bargain early. Once before, in 1982, the
early talks failed. But this time, neither side can easily afford a
failure at the table.
   Chrysler and the union are betting that in the talks, which
could begin as early as next month and will cover 59,500 workers,
they'll be able to fix the problem rather than make it worse.
   But difficult issues remain, beginning with Acustar. In
announcing its retreat from the sale, Chrysler said it would
instead close four Acustar plants, affecting 2,000 workers, if it
can't sell them in 18 months.
   ``We as a union are not prepared to just give up and say there
goes 2,000 jobs,'' said Jensen, who will be one of 10 elected
members of the union's bargaining team.
   St. John, however, said last week that the fate of the plants is
not up for negotiation.
   Jensen and other workers also say they expect Chrysler to seek a
two-tier wage system _ paying parts workers lower wages and
benefits than assembly workers _ because it has shown it considers
the parts operation too expensive.
   The UAW sidelined similar attempts by Ford and General Motors
last fall when it negotiated new three-year contracts with
Chrysler's larger rivals.
   ``Given the enormous reaction to Acustar, Chrysler's ability to
institute two-tier wages in this round of negotiations would be
very low,'' said Harley Shaiken, labor and technology expert at the
University of California at San Diego.
   UAW President Owen Bieber said the union will demand a two-year
contract so that in 1990, the GM, Ford and Chrysler contracts will
expire together for the first time since 1979.
   Bargaining with the Big Three together makes it easier for the
union to impose one contract on all and gives it a third choice
when it is choosing a strike target, the company whose contract
serves as the pattern for the others.
   St. John said Chrysler finds advantages in remaining out of
synch with GM and Ford. Chrysler sought a separate relationship
with the union beginning in 1979, when workers made the first of
many concessions to help the automaker survive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
