<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vatican-Cuba     03-12 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vatican-Cuba,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vatican Offical Says Relations Improving With Cuba</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vatican official said Saturday that permission
from Cuba's communist government to send 20 foreign priests to Cuba
was a sign of improving relations between the Roman Catholic church
and that Caribbean nation.
   However, Monsignor Carlos Manuel de Cespedes, director of the
Vaticans' Secretariat of the Episcopal Conference, told Vatican
Radio that the church hopes for still more improvement in the area
of individual rights.
   He said the church would like to see more religious freedom in
Cuba and the construction of new churches.
   He said there has not been ``sensational changes in the rapport
between the church and state, between Catholics and Marxists. But,
nevertheless, things are moving and I would like to say they are
moving in the right way.''
   De Cespedes said examples of change were the government allowing
the Cuban church to import 30,000 Bibles last year and permission
last week for the church to send 20 foreign priests to Cuba.
   Vatican Radio said there are 406 Cuban priests to serve the
predominantly Catholic population of about 10 million.
   It said most of the 20 foreign priests that will go to Cuba are
Spanish or Italian, but there also will be one Mexican and one
Canadian.
   Rebels led by Fidel Castro ousted the Fulgencio Batista
dictatorsyip in 1959 and in December 1961 Castro declared Cuba
would be a Marxist-Leninist state.
</TEXT>
