<DOCNO> AP880312-0136 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 1700EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Ariane     03-12 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ariane,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Satellites Prepare Move To Permanent Orbit After Flawless Launch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KOUROU, French Guiana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American and French
telecommunications satellites sent into space by Europe's Ariane 3
rocket were prepared Saturday to move into permanent orbits on
their own power.
   The European Space Agency also announced plans for two more
launches in May.
   Technicians said France's Telecom 1C and the American Spacenet
IIIR-Geostar, which includes facilities for The Associated Press,
were thrust into a geographically stationary orbit Friday night
about 20 minutes after liftoff from this South American jungle base.
   Officials called the launch perfect.
   Arianespace, the space agency's commercial arm, said Saturday
two more launches were planned for May, one a demonstration flight
of the more powerful Ariane 4 rocket. Arianespace is now the West's
only active commercial satellite launcher with America's
space-shuttle program grounded.
   The Ariane 3 rocket ignited normally four minutes after
blastoff, officials said. Ignition was the cause of failed Ariane
launches in September 1982, September 1985 and May 1986.
   The last failure, the 18th launch, left the rocket grounded for
more than a year.
   Technicians said Friday's satellites obtained an altitute of
22,554 miles.
   The French satellite is to begin moving into its definitive
geostationary orbit Sunday, 37 hours after the launch, after
igniting its own engine, Arianespace said.
   Spacenet IIIR-Geostar is to start moving into a permanent orbit
about 90 hours after the liftoff, the company said.
   GTE Spacenet, the European firm's first American client, has
used the Ariane to launch five satellites, losing one in a
September 1985 failure.
   Jerry Waylan, GTE Spacenet chief, said this was the first
American telecommunications satellite to be launched in two years.
   The satellite, with an expected lifetime of 10 years, weighed
2,674 pounds before liftoff and 1,562 pounds in orbit.
   Two transponders on Spacenet III purchased by AP are to provide
the New York-based news cooperative with domestic satellite
delivery services.
   The French Telecom IC, replacing one that broke down Jan. 15, is
to be used for telephones, radio and television transmissions and
military communications.
   Arianespace said it has orders for 41 more satellite launchings,
valued at $2.29 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880312-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 1713EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LaRoucheTrial     03-12 0685</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LaRouche Trial,0702</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LaRouche Trial Suddenly Takes a Spy Novel Twist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two months into the trial of Lyndon LaRouche comes
evidence supporting the political extremist's claim that he was the
target of plots by the FBI, the CIA and even Lt. Col. Oliver North.
   Now, even some defense lawyers who had dismissed LaRouche's
allegations of a conspiracy theory as one of his many bizarre
claims are taking notice. LaRouche has also said Britain's Queen
Elizabeth condones drug trafficking and that one way to help the
U.S. economy is to populate Mars.
   The trial of LaRouche, six aides, and five of his political
organizations on fraud and conspiracy charges was halted Friday so
that defense attorneys could search government files, including
those of the White House and Vice President George Bush, for any
evidence suggesting infiltration of LaRouche groups.
   Prosecutors have insisted that talk of FBI, CIA and other
government infiltration in recently declassified documents is just
that _ talk _ and that the subject is irrelevant to charges that
LaRouche and followers conspired to stymie a grand jury
investigation into alleged fraud by fund-raisers during his 1984
presidential campaign.
   But, at least for now, LaRouche has turned the tables on the
government, which has been ordered to search thousands of files
belonging to the FBI, CIA, the National Security Council and Bush.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney John Markham on Monday is to update U.S.
District Judge Robert E. Keeton on the status of the search. The
judge will decide whether to resume testimony Tuesday or wait until
the search is completed.
   LaRouche lawyers last week received a copy of a memo from
retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard Secord to North, two principals
in the Iran-Contra affair, in which Secord says retired Army Sgt.
Major Fred Lewis had met with the FBI and ``other agency reps'' and
has ``collected info against LaRouche.''
   The defense then demanded FBI files mentioning Lewis. After
first refusing to do so, the FBI declassified parts of a document
in which Lewis and two Texas lawmen who had worked as government
informants say the FBI and CIA asked them to infiltrate LaRouche
groups.
   Lewis and the lawmen were involved in two Texas companies
reportedly used by the Pentagon and CIA for covert activities.
Markham insists they are lying about infiltrating LaRouche groups.
   But the mere existence of the FBI document and the Secord-North
memo, discovered months after Markham had said searches of
government records were complete, was enough to persuade the judge
to halt testimony and order new searches.
   It also was enough to convert Michael Reilly, attorney for
LaRouche's central political organization, the National Caucus of
Labor Committees. Reilly had told the jury in his opening statement
that LaRouche's infiltration claim was misguided paranoia.
   ``This is a fundamental change in my defense strategy,'' Reilly
said. ``I should have had this 18 months ago and I have a right to
have it before I pursue this case.''
   Another defense attorney, William Moffitt, says his legal
strategy may be affected by the document searches.
   In his opening statement, Markham referred to an entry in a
notebook seized from Moffitt's client, LaRouche aide Jeffrey
Steinberg, as evidence LaRouche and aides conspired to obstruct the
grand jury investigation.
   The Aug. 23, 1986, entry is attributed to Ryan Quade Emerson,
who at the time had recently returned to the LaRouche organization.
Five days earlier, according to documents recently surrendered to
defense lawyers, an FBI agent interviewed Emerson and asked him to
rejoin the LaRouche organization.
   The prosecutor's task will be to convince Keeton that references
to FBI and CIA infiltration of LaRouche groups are unsubstantiated
and irrelevant to the case.
   The defense lawyers, who concede the material may not be
directly relevant, say it nevertheless supports their argument that
LaRouche and his followers are longtime government targets and
victims of entrapment.
   Ironically, LaRouche missed the week of his trial he would have
enjoyed the most. With court permission, he went to West Germany
for cataract surgery last week and is not expected back for several
weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
