<1ST_LINE>u w AM-PLO-Congress 1stLd-Writethru a0615 03-12 0858</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PLO-Congress, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0615,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressional Aides Hold Secret Meeting with Arafat</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Recasts top 15 grafs to raise material about meeting; picks
up 16th graf pvs, People with</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several lawmakers have criticized a group of
congressional aides for meeting secretly with Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat in January, only weeks after Congress voted to close
Palestine Liberation Organization offices in the United States.
   The secret, two-hour meeting, which took place in Baghdad, Iraq,
became publicly known last week. It was arranged by the National
Council on U.S.-Arab Relations, the group that paid for the
congressional aides' eight-day trip to Iraq on Jan. 11-19.
   The meeting, described as an open exchange between Arafat and
the aides, was held shortly after Congress passed controversial
legislation shutting down two PLO offices in the United States on
the grounds they represent a terrorist organization. Arafat is head
of the PLO.
   ``It was very foolish, very wrong,'' Rep. Larry Smith, D-Fla.,
said of the aides' meeting. ``He (Arafat) is not going to change
his positions because a Capitol Hill staffer meets with him.''
   Rep. Robert G. Torricelli, D-N.J., said he was upset when he
learned an aide attended the Baghdad meeting with Arafat.
   ``She acted independently, and I had no knowledge of this
meeting nor would I have approved it, and I remain very disturbed
about it.'' The staffer no longer works for Torricelli, but left
for personal reasons unrelated to the meeting.
   But another lawmaker was unfazed by his aide's attendance at the
meeting.
   Rep. Edward Feighan, D-Ohio, said his assistant ``was not on any
official trip and he was traveling in a personal capacity.''
   Michael Van Dusen, staff director of the House Foreign Affairs
subcommittee on Europe and the Middle East, said seeing Arafat was
``extremely unwise when as a matter of law American officials are
not supposed to negotiate with the PLO. ... I wouldn't do it.''
   U.S. policy _ set by Congress _ prohibits officials in the
executive branch from negotiating with Arafat or members of the PLO
until the group recognizes Israel's right to exist.
   The policy does not apply to Congress, and a few lawmakers as
well as members of their staff have met openly with Arafat in the
past.
   While the congressional group did not violate the law, members
of Congress and key staff people on Capitol Hill said that, in view
of U.S. policy, it was unwise to hold discussions with Arafat,
particularly if a lawmaker had not authorized the talks.
   Ronald W. Cathell, the executive director of U.S.-Arab council,
said he would not release the names of the staffers who attended
the Arafat meeting or traveled to Iraq for fear they would be
subjected to reprisals for going to the meeting.
   The council, which seeks to promote understanding between
Americans and Arabs, receives its money from grants and private and
corporate contributions.
   Several staffers contacted about the meeting refused to talk
about it and would not provide the names of their companions.
   People with knowledge of the free trip confirmed that those who
went to Iraq worked for Sens. Mark Hatfield, R-Ore.; John Heinz,
R-Pa.; J. Bennett Johnston, D-La., David Karnes, R-Neb; and Reps.
Feighan; Torricelli; Helen Bentley, R-Md.; Douglas Bereuter,
R-Neb.; William Clay, D-Mo.; James Inhofe, R-Okla., and Robert
Lagomarsino, R-Calif.
   Bereuter's spokeswoman, Carol Lawrence, said the congressman's
aide resigned before the trip, but now works at the Pentagon.
   A State Department official, speaking on condition on anonymity,
said all but one of the staffers on the Iraq trip went to the
meeting with Arafat.
   Cathell said the original agenda did not include seeing Arafat.
Once the group arrived in Baghdad, the council learned the PLO
leader was in town and broached the possibility of a meeting with
the congressional aides.
   The staffers were never pressured to attend the meeting, which
Cathell said was designed to give them ``information they could
relate to their bosses.'' The staffers were told, ``It's totally up
to you,'' he said.
   One aide, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the group was
given less than an hour's notice that a face-to-face meeting with
Arafat had been fixed.
   Torricelli complained the U.S. Embassy in Baghdad failed to
advise his aide about U.S. policy prohibiting official negotiations
with the PLO. Cathell said the embassy simply told the group its
own people couldn't attend the meeting because of U.S. policy.
   But a State Department official, refusing to be identified by
name, said the U.S. ambassador had tried to dissuade the Americans
from meeting with Arafat.
   Cathell said the meeting was constructive, and gave the staffers
``a unique chance to find out firsthand where the Palestinian
stood.'' The aides, he said, were ``candid and forthright'' with
Arafat.
   The Baghdad meeting came a few months after Congress voted to
close both the PLO's office at the United Nations in New York, and
a Palestine Information Office in Washington.
   Lawmakers took the action, which has provoked widespread
criticism from civil libertarians and U.N. members, on the grounds
that the PLO supports terrorism.
   Rep. George W. Crockett Jr., D-Mich., has introduced legislation
to repeal the closings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
