<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     03-12 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow Storm Moves Toward Great Lakes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Storm Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The snowstorm that battered the Plains spread snow across
central Minnesota into northern Wisconsin and Upper Michigan on
Saturday, but it was weakening with wind not blowing as strongly as
the day before.
   Snowfall amounts across central and northeastern Minnesota
ranged from 6 to 12 inches and northern Wisconsin got from 3 to 8
inches.
   Up to 6 inches of snow was expected over Michigan's Upper
Peninsula while freezing rain and sleet moved across northern Lower
Michigan.
   During the morning, wind in Minnesota gusted from 25 to more
than 50 mph but by afternoon the peak gusts were down to about 40
mph.
   Wind gusts in Wisconsin were clocked at from 20 to 30 mph at
times.
   Gusty wind also blew around the west side of the storm system,
with gusts of 55 mph at Mitchell, S.D., during the morning. Gusts
to 35 to 45 mph were reported across the eastern Dakotas into
eastern and central Nebraska, western and northern Kansas into
northwestern Missouri and western Iowa.
   Temperatures were in the single digits across the northern
Plains, combining with the wind to produce wind chill factors as
low as 30 below zero during the afternoon.
   Showers and a few thunderstorms were scattered ahead of a cold
front that extended from southeastern Wisconsin into the lower
Mississippi Valley, accompanied by brief heavy rain, small hail and
gusty wind across northeastern Louisiana into west-central
Mississippi.
   The heaviest rainfall reported during the six hours up to 1 p.m.
EST was 0.53 of an inch at Texarkana, Ark.
   The heaviest snow during the same period was 6 inches at
Marquette, Mich.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 6
degrees at Yellowstone National Park in Wyoming to 85 at McAllen,
Texas. The low for the day was 20 degres below zero at West
Yellowstone, Mont.
   For Sunday, snow showers were forecast across the Great Lakes
region with rain changing to snow over the eastern Great Lakes and
northern New England. Showers were forecast from the upper Ohio
Valley into central and southern New England. Scattered showers
also were forecast over the middle and southern Atlantic Coast
region.
   Highs in the teens and 20s were predicted across the northern
Plains, the upper Mississippi Valley and upper Great Lakes region;
in the 60s from the central Pacific Coast over western and central
Texas and the central Gulf Coast to the middle Atlantic Coast; in
the 70s over the southern California coast, desert Southwest, the
southern tip of Texas and northern Florida and the southern
Atlantic Coast; in the low 80s over the southern half of Florida;
and in the 30s, 40s or 50s across most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
