<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FernaldReport     03-12 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fernald Report,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Report Critical of Uranium Plant Operator</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The company that operates the federally owned
Fernald uranium-processing plant violates its own regulations and
puts its workers' health at risk, a new government report concludes.
   The report says the U.S. Department of Energy, which owns the
plant, and Westinghouse Materials Co. of Ohio, the private
contractor that runs it, should work harder to eliminate potential
worker health hazards at the facility's Feed Materials Production
Center.
   The 37-year-old plant, 18 miles northwest of Cincinnati,
processes uranium for use in the government's nuclear weapons.
   The National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health, part
of the U.S. Department of Health and Human Services, issued the
preliminary report last week on the basis of a December inspection
conducted at the request of labor unions at the plant.
   Its final report is not due out for three more months, but
Westinghouse says it has already responded to the institute's
findings by making some rule changes at the plant.
   The report said plant employees sometimes leave portable
air-breathing equipment lying out in areas containing loose and
radioactively contaminated dust, which could get into the
respirators and ultimately into workers' lungs.
   ``Given the fact that many surfaces in the plants where we made
measurements are radiologically contaminated, it is imperative that
workers store their respirators in a clean location when not in
use. This practice should prevent inadvertent ingestion of
radiation-contaminated materials,'' wrote the industrial hygienists
who prepared the report.
   Many surfaces in the plant are contaminated with radioactive
substances from the plant's years of service and require cleanup,
the federal hygienists said.
   They said they found Westinghouse technicians who violated
company regulations and created a potential health hazard by
smoking, eating and drinking while handling and counting
radiological samples.
   ``Surely, such a practice needs to stop immediately,'' the
investigators wrote.
   They also urged improving workplace ventilation in some areas of
the plant. And they recommended that the Department of Energy
improve its supervision of worker health and safety by assigning a
health physicist to the plant.
   The investigators lauded Westinghouse, however, for improving
worker health and safety since taking over operation of the plant
in January 1986 from the previous contractor, National Lead of Ohio.
   Westinghouse spokesman Pete Kelley said the report made no major
criticisms of his company.
   Westinghouse has responded to the federal report by banning
smoking, eating and drinking in the radiological sampling area,
Kelley said. Leaving respirators in potentially contaminated areas
is a violation of Westinghouse policies, he added.
   The spokesman also noted that Westinghouse has increased the
staff of health physicists since it took over the plant's operation.
</TEXT>
