<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush     03-12 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Increasingly Confident Bush Looks Beyond Illinois</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED WHITE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ARLINGTON HEIGHTS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A confident George Bush predicted
Saturday that victory in the Illinois primary election Tuesday
would ``cinch the Republican nomination'' for him.
   Campaigning in the heavily Republican northwest Chicago suburbs,
the vice president preached GOP unity and all but ignored his rival
candidates, Kansas Sen. Bob Dole and former TV evangelist Pat
Robertson.
   ``I want to be your president,'' Bush said to a cheering crowd
at St. Viator High School. ``I do not want to do it by tearing some
other Republican, by weakening the party that needs to be
together.''
   Bush so far has won 705 of the 1,139 delegates needed to win the
GOP nomination.
   Dole and Robertson also campaigned in Illinois Saturday, with
Dole conceding, ``We're hanging by our fingernails.''
   Bush, appearing with his wife, Barbara, Illinois Gov. James R.
Thompson and pilot Chuck Yeager, began his day with a breakfast
appearance before the Barrington Area Chamber of Commerce, before
speaking to a partisan audience of about 600 at McHenry County
College.
   ``You give me this vote on Tuesday and it seems to me I will
cinch the Republican nomination,'' Bush said.
   The vice president was buoyed by results of a Chicago Tribune
poll published its Sunday editions. The poll of 504 Republicans
showed Bush ahead of Dole 62 percent to 28 percent among those
likely to vote Tuesday.
   Robertson was a distant third with 6 percent.
   The survey, conducted in the past week, had a margin of error of
plus or minus five percentage points.
   Bush has rejected Dole's bid for a face-to-face debate in
Illinois.
   On Saturday, he talked mostly about what he would do if he
captures the White House.
   ``On the deficit, we've got to whip it,'' he said, promising not
to raise taxes to do it.
   ``It is public enemy No. 1. The answer to the deficit is simple,
hold the line on taxes. You're not paying too little in taxes,
we're spending too much in Congress,'' he said.
</TEXT>
