<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Libya-Gadhafi     03-12 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Libya-Gadhafi,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gadhafi Returns Passports To Libyans On Travel-Ban List</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi stood before a
cheering crowd Saturday and tore up a list of names of Libyans
banned from travel abroad and ordered their passports returned, the
Libyan news agency JANA reported.
   Gadhafi was quoted as telling a mass gathering in front of the
passport office in the capital, Tripoli, that ``there must be no
citizen jailed or banned from traveling abroad ... in the society
of freedom.''
   The JANA report, monitored in Rome, did not say how many names
were on the list Gadhafi destoyred. It said destruction of the list
and the return of the passports were another step in the ``festival
of freedom'' that began when Gadhafi ``stormed the prison,
demolishing it and liberating the prisoners.''
   Earlier this month, Gadhafi used a bulldozer to knock down the
wall at a prison in Tripoli to release prisoners as part of an
amnesty he declared. JANA said 400 prisoners were freed.
   It also said 130 foreigners of various nationalities were
released from prison last Monday.
   In London, the Foreign Office said James Abra, a 59-year-old
British engineer employed by the British electronics firm Plessey
Company, would be freed Sunday. Abra has been serving a life
sentence for alleged spying.
   He was arrested June 20, 1985, at the Tripoli Airport.
</TEXT>
