<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF-RadioactiveMaterial     03-12 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF-Radioactive Material,0196</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thieves Take Car Containing Radioactive Material</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car with a device stored in the trunk
containing mildly radioactive material was stolen, and the thieves
could be harmed if they tampered with the devide, federal officials
said Saturday.
   The car, which was stolen Thursday night, had a measuring device
containing cesium-137 and americium-241, said Karl Abraham, a
spokesman for the Nuclear Regulatory Commission in Philadelphia.
   Abraham said the material was inside a 30-inch-high yellow
plastic case bearing a ``radioactive'' label and a federal
Department of Transportation sticker.
   ``It's perfectly safe to pick up and carry the case around,''
Abraham said. ``The radioactive sources are not all that powerful.''
   The substances were part of a moisture density gauge that
measures the compaction and moisture content of materials used in
constructing roads, Abraham said. The car is owned by an employee
of Soils Engineering Services Co. in Whippany.
   A person ``would have to tamper with it and take the radioactive
sources out of a safe container and carry them in one's hands for
several hours before there would be the possibility of radioactive
injuries,'' said Abraham.
</TEXT>
