<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 1902EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Austria-Habsburg     03-12 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Austria-Habsburg,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Pretender To Throne Has Triumphant Return To Hofburg Palace</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Waldheim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Otto von Habsburg, ex-pretender to the
Austrian throne, made a triumphant return Saturday to the former
imperial Hofburg palace, from which his ancestors ruled a vast
empire for centuries.
   The son of the last Austrian emperor, Karl I, von Habsburg was
greeted with cheers and a standing ovation by about 1,600 people
crowded into a main hall.
   Uniformed students threw their caps into the air and a brass
band played as von Habsburg entered the hall.
   Von Habsburg, 75, made the appearance to mark the 50th
anniversary of the annexation of Austria by Nazi Germany and
addressed the crowd as president of the International Pan-European
Union.
   The Habsburg family ruled much of central Europe for more than
600 years. The monarchy was abolished in 1918 at the end of World
War I. Otto von Habsburg was barred from Austria until 1961 when he
renounced his claim to the non-existent throne.
   Most members of the Pan-European Union in Austria and parts of
West Germany are elderly monarchists. One of their declared goals
is the unification of western and eastern Europe without the Soviet
Union.
   Von Habsburg's eldest son, Karl, is head of the union's Austrian
branch and welcomed guests to the palace gathering.
   Speakers condemned the Nazi rule of Austria and referred to van
Habsburg as ``royal highness.''
   None of the speakers mentioned President Kurt Waldheim, who has
come under increasing pressure to resign because of allegations
about his past while serving in the German army in the Balkans
during World War II.
   In his speech, von Habsburg said, ``The past shows that
diversity can only be preserved in unity. A good example for that
was the old Austria, that community of Danube peoples, in which
many nations were united economically and politically.''
   Von Habsburg holds a West German passport. He is still a subject
of controversy between Austrian conservatives and socialistts.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
