<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-MIAs     03-12 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-MIAs,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Military Team Flies To Hanoi For MIA Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. military team flew to Vietnam
Saturday to discuss the Southeast Asian nation's accounting of
Americans listed as missing in action from the Vietnam War, a U.S.
official said.
   The regularly scheduled talks in Hanoi follow Vietnam's
repatriation on March 2 of what it believed were the remains of 17
American MIAs.
   It was the largest turnover in two years and the fourth largest
since the war ended in April 1975 with a communist victory over
U.S.-backed South Vietnam. The United States lists nearly 1,800
Americans as missing in Vietnam during the war.
   Ross Petzing, a spokesman at the U.S. Embassy in Bangkok, said
the team is composed of six experts from the Joint Casualty
Resolution Center and the Army Central Identification Laboratory,
both based in Hawaii.
   ``The team is presenting cases on Americans missing from the war
in Indochina for Vietnamese investigation,'' Petzing said.
   He said the talks with Foreign Ministry officials, scheduled to
extend through Tuesday, would be the fourth round of technical
discussions since Vietnam agreed last August to resume cooperation
on the issue.
   As part of the agreement, a U.S. medical team visited Vietnam
earlier this month to study how private American assistance could
help war-disabled Vietnamese.
</TEXT>
