<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Kidnap     03-12 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kidnap,0373</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Survives Kidnap Ordeal in Car Trunk</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Town of Otego and county of Otsego are cq.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEWBURGH, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 73-year-old woman was found alive and
apparently unharmed Saturday after spending as many as four nights
locked in her car trunk by an alleged kidnapper, state police said.
   Martha Bushnell of Arkville was rescued from the trunk of her
compact car shortly before 9:30 a.m., about three hours after a
33-year-old woman was arrested on a charge of kidnapping her.
   Police believe Bushnell had been in the trunk since Tuesday
night, with no food or water and with overnight temperatures
dipping below freezing, said state police Sgt. Al Dorer in
Middletown.
   She was lucid and coherent when she was found and did not appear
to be injured, but she was admitted to St. Luke's Hospital in
Newburgh, police said. ``She was in pretty good condition,
considering her ordeal,'' said Dorer. The hospital would not
release details on her status Saturday evening.
   Investigators were questioning her to determine what had
happened, according to state police Sgt. Bob Parlett in Ithaca.
Details of the incident were still sketchy Saturday, and police
would not speculate on a motive.
   Police had initiated a statewide search for Bushnell after her
car was seen parked on a Newburgh street Wednesday morning, said
Dorer. Two girls had heard cries for help from the car and had
flagged down a taxi driver to help. The driver called police, but
when they arrived the car was gone, Dorer said.
   Parlett said Bushnell, who lives alone, had last been seen
around noon Tuesday at the Valkyrian Motel in Fleischmanns, where
she works part-time.
   At 6:30 a.m. Saturday, authorities arrested Jamesetta Marie
Strong, 33, of Otego, after acquaintances reported seeing her
driving the Bushnell car in the Newburgh area, Parlett said.
   Police found the car later Saturday morning in the parking lot
of a knitting mill, Dorer said.
   ``When they popped the trunk, there she was,'' Dorer said. ``The
first words out of her mouth were `Thank you.'''
   Strong was sent to Otsego County Jail without bail after being
arraigned on a charge of first-degree kidnapping, Parlett said.
</TEXT>
