<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chief Of Rebel Alliance Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Yunis Khalis, the chief of the
seven-party Afghan opposition alliance, resigned Saturday for
health reasons, an alliance statement said.
   It gave no further details and did not announce a replacement.
   The statment said the Hezbi Islami party, which Khalis heads,
will remain in the alliance and did not say if Khalis also resigned
as party leader.
   His resignation came less than a week after another rebel leader
quit the alliance over plans to form an interim Afghan government
when Soviet troops withdraw from the country.
   But Sibghatullah Mojaddedi, head of the National Liberation
Front, rejoined the alliance three days after resigning.
   Khalis, a Moslem clergyman, was born in 1919 in the village of
Gandumak in the Afghan province of Nangarhar. He was elected to
head the alliance in October 1987. Most of the alliance members
have headquarters in Pakistan.
   Recent developments within the alliance coincide with United
Nations-sponsored talks in Geneva between Pakistan and
Afghanistan's Marxist government to end the Afghan war and and pave
the way for the withdrawal of an estimated 115,000 Soviet military
personnel.
   The Soviets intervened in December 1979 to help the government
battle the anti-communist guerrillas.
   The rebels are suported by the United States, China and Pakistan.
</TEXT>
