<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Italy-Arson     03-12 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Italy-Arson,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Buses Burned At Nuclear Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONTALTO DI CASTRO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five buses used to transport
workers at a nuclear power plant were set afire Saturday night, two
days after the government said construction could resume there, the
ANSA news agency said.
   The Italian agency said the buses were burned inside the
compound of the Montalto Di Castro nuclear plant and were owned by
the Central Nuclear Consortium, which is building the facility 50
miles north of Rome.
   Strong Socialist Party opposition to resuming construction at
the plant was one factor that led to the resignation of Christian
Democrat Premier Giovanni Goria Friday night.
   Goria, leader of the coalition government since August, resigned
twice before, the last time in February, but agreed to stay on to
help pass the national budget. The budget was passed Thursday and
Goria had been expected to resign next week. Politicial leaders
said he decided to quit immediately because of the controversy over
construction at the plant here.
   The government announced a moratorium on construction at the
plant last November after voters in a non-binding referendum
expressed their disapproval of nuclear power facilities.
   On Thursday the government said construction could resume at the
plant, which already has cost Italy $5 billion.
</TEXT>
