<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChemicalFire     03-12 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chemical Fire,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Destroys Huge Chemical Warehouse; 500 Persons Evacuated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKDALE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A huge chemical fire emitting potentially
dangerous fumes forced the evacuation of about 500 residents for a
time Saturday as it destroyed a huge warehouse and set fire to two
homes.
   Ten people including seven firefighters were injured in the fire
at the Werco chemical warehouse complex, authorities said.
   The evacuees were allowed to return home later in the day but
were instructed to boil drinking water into Sunday, said Lynn
Behringer, spokeswoman for the Will County Emergency Services and
Disaster Agency.
   Strong winds blew smoke and sparks directly into the downtown
area of Rockdale, a town of about 2,000 residents southwest of
Chicago, and exploding chemicals punctuated the flames.
   ``It looked like the Fourth of July,'' said Mrs. Behringer.
``Considering the magnitude of this fire and the number of homes so
close, we are very lucky.'' Of the two homes set ablaze, one was
heavily damaged.
   The warehouse complex, which covered several square blocks,
stored some 60 kinds of chemicals for various businesses.
   Village President Donald B. Gould said police began evacuating
residents about 5 a.m. because of the potential danger from the
fumes, although the identity of the full range of chemicals was not
known. The evacuation area eventually covered two square miles,
officials said.
   After the evacuation order was lifted, residents were told to
boil drinking water because of low water pressure from the
firefighting.
   The cause of the fire and the dollar loss were not immediately
determined.
   Seven firefighters and three other people were treated and
released at hospitals in Joliet and Morris, spokesmen said.
</TEXT>
