<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 2016EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-Peace     03-12 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Peace,0608</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinistas Agree to New Peace Talks With Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Sandinista government announced
Saturday it has formally agreed to hold the first cease-fire talks
inside Nicaragua with rebel leaders.
   It said the talks will be held March 21-23 in the southern
frontier post of Sapoa, 90 miles south of Managua.
   President Daniel Ortega ordered local civilian and military
authorities in the area ``to lend all facilities to the delegation
of the counterrevolution'' to enter and leave the country freely at
the Pena Blanca border crossing, according to a statement issued by
his office.
   The statement said the government would assume all
responsibility for the security of the rebel delegation during the
negotiations and cross-border traffic would not be affected.
   Adolfo Calero, the top political leader of the Nicaraguan
Resistance, is expected to head the delegation from the rebels,
known as Contras. Nicaraguan Resistance is an umbrella organization
of rebel group.
   Ortega previously announced that his brother, Defense Minister
Humberto Ortega, would lead the government delegation.
   The Sapoa meeting also will be the first between the two sides
without a mediator.
   Calero told The Associated Press recently that the Sapoa talks
would take place with ``an open agenda.'' He said Joao Baena
Soares, secretary general of the Organization of American States,
and Roman Catholic Cardinal Miguel Obando y Bravo would attend as
witnesses.
   Obando y Bravo, the archbishop of Managua, mediated previous
talks held in the Dominican Republic and Guatemala.
   Calero said a representative of Nicaragua's internal opposition
also would be invited to attend. A Contra representative in Miami,
who spoke with the condition he not be identified, told AP Saturday
the Nicaraguan Resistance still was insisting that a domestic
opponent of the Sandinistas be present at the talks as an observer.
   Ortega's statement did not mention that demand.
   Both sides had tentatively agreed to meet in Sapoa for three
days of direct negotiations beginning March 9. Ortega canceled that
schedule after the rebels said they would not attend without
preliminary discussions.
   Ortega dismissed Obando y Bravo as mediator on March 2 after the
cardinal proposed an agenda that included discussion of internal
politics.
   The Contras previously had insisted on the presence of Obando Y
Bravo, a frequent critic of the left-wing government.
   Contra spokesmen also insisted Ortega's government agree to
discuss the political points outlined by Obando y Bravo during the
last cease-fire talks held Feb. 18 in Guatemala.
   The cardinal's plan would have required the Sandinistas to grant
amnesty to political prisoners, restore full press freedom, open
talks with internal opposition political parties and review the
military draft law.
   The Sandinistas have refused to discuss internal political
issues with the Contras, saying the only purpose of the talks is to
work out a cease-fire in accordance with the regional peace plan
signed Aug. 7 by the presidents of the five Central American
countries.
   Roger Guevara, secretary of the Nicaraguan Democratic
Coordinate, a coalition of opposition political parties and
business and labor groups, said his organization would send a
representative to the talks but as a participant, not as an
observer.
   In a broadcast over the Rebels' Radio Liberacion, Guevara said
``in spite of the fact there does not exist an official invitation,
the Coordinate is ready to assist in this reunion.''
   Obando y Bravo told local reporters Saturday he was willing to
attend as a witness. ``I would like these talks to advance so that
they redound to the benefit of the Nicaraguan people,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
