<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dole 4thLd-Writethru a0658 03-12 0884</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dole, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0658,840</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Stakes Illinois Effort on Half-Hour TV Show</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 3 grafs after 9th graf pvs bgng, `Ladies and,' to
UPDATE with 2-3 minute glitch on TV program; PICKS UP 10th graf pvs
bgng, `A poll'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GALESBURG, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kansas Sen. Bob Dole, saying ``the issues
are more important than the odds,'' went on television for 30
minutes Saturday in an effort to reverse the decline in his
presidential prospects.
   Standing in front of a portrait of Abraham Lincoln, Dole said,
``I know I'm the underdog in this race. The issues are more
important than the odds. ... I didn't expect this job to be handed
to me in the first place.''
   Dole spoke from Alumni Hall at Knox College which was the site
of the fifth of the seven debates in 1858 between Lincoln and
Stephen Douglas during their campaign for the Senate. Dole's
address was televised in Illinois.
   Vice President George Bush, who has refused to respond to a Dole
challenge for a one-on-one debate before the Illinois primary on
Tuesday, was the featured speaker at a dinner on the campus shortly
after the Dole program aired.
   Dole spoke as a new survey said Bush was the choice of 62
percent of likely Republican primary voters. Only 28 percent named
Dole as their choice.
   ``It just seems to me we should have had a debate,'' said Dole.
``My opponent is less than 100 yards away as I speak.''
   Actually, Bush was not scheduled to arrive until after Dole left.
   ``Nothing has ever come easy for Bob,'' said his wife,
Elizabeth. ``His only inheritance was the love of his parents.''
   ``Ladies and gentlemen, you're going to be voting Tuesday and we
want you to know more about Bob Dole's life,'' she said,
introducing a 14-minute segment from a biographical sketch filmed
for showing to Dole campaign meetings.
   But her remarks were never seen by WGN viewers because of a
technical problem that cut off the live picture for about two to
three minutes, said Raymond Kirk, the master controller for the TV
station.
   The station froze the last live shot of Dole and kept it on the
screen while viewers also heard his voice.
   Then the station switched to the biographical sketch, bypassing
Mrs. Dole's introduction. The program concluded without further
problems.
   A poll published in the Sunday edition of the Chicago Tribune
said the vice president was the choice of 62 percent of Republicans
likely to vote in Tuesday's primary. Dole was named by 28 percent
and Pat Robertson by 6 percent.
   The survey of 504 likely GOP voters was conducted Wednesday and
Thursday.
   During campaign appearances on Friday, Dole conceded he was
``hanging by our fingernails.''
   The senator, who took a drubbing on Super Tuesday this past
week, losing 16 of 16 primaries to Bush, needed a victory in
Illinois to maintain any faint hope that he can stage a comeback in
the presidential race.
   Bush, campaigning in northwest Chicago suburbs, predicted
Saturday that victory in the Illinois primary election Tuesday
would ``cinch the Republican nomination'' for him.
   The vice president preached GOP unity and all but ignored Dole
and Robertson.
   ``I want to be your president,'' Bush said to a cheering crowd
at St. Viator High School. ``I do not want to do it by tearing some
other Republican, by weakening the party that needs to be
together.''
   The latest Associated Press delegate count gave Bush 705 and
Dole 163. A total of 1,139 delegate votes would be needed at the
GOP convention in New Orleans next August to win the presidential
nomination.
   Larry McCarthy, communications director for the Dole campaign,
said $100,000 was spent to purchase one half-hour on Chicago
television station WGN and additional time slots Sunday and Monday
on other stations around the state. He said the amount also covered
the production costs.
   Campaign manager William E. Brock said the broadcast would be
repeated Sunday on other stations around the state.
   Brock also said that contrary to earlier statements from
campaign officials, other Dole commercials were running in Illinois.
   Earlier in the week, the campaign had said that all commercials
in a total buy of $500,000 had been pulled off the air.
   Brock said some were pulled off, but others _ biographical spots
portraying Dole as a strong leader _ were continuing to run. He
said some commercials were dropped when it was decided to use part
of the media budget for the half hour program.
   ``We need to somehow capture the attention of the Illinois
voters,'' said Dole, who has repeatedly challenged Bush to a
one-on-one debate. The vice president brushed off the challenge,
saying he already has participated in seven debates and called them
``cruel and unusual punishment.''
   The only encouragement Dole could get from the Tribune poll was
the response when Republicans were asked if they agreed with the
statement that it was ``important for the Republicans that Bob Dole
does well in Illinois so that the Republican presidential campaign
continues.'' A total of 56 percent said they agreed, while 30
percent said they disagreed.
   Other findings strongly favored Bush.
   When people were asked which candidate they considered ``tough,
a strong leader,'' 45 percent named Bush and 32 percent Dole.
</TEXT>
