<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Colombia-Elections     03-12 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Elections,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Armed Forces On Alert As Colombians Prepare To Elect Mayors,
Councils</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government placed Colombia's
150,000-member armed forces on alert as voters prepare to vote
Sunday to elect mayors for the first time since independence from
Spain 169 years ago.
   The campaign to elect mayors in 1,008 municipalities has drawn
violence from leftist guerrillas, drug traffickers and right-wing
death squads. The election is the first real challenge to
upper-class control of local government.
   Until now Colombia's mayors, with the exception of Bogota, have
been named by governors, who are appointed by the president. The
president chose the mayor of Bogota.
   In the election, Colombians also will choose 10,543 councilmen,
421 state assembly representatives and 89 assemblymen from remote
territories.
   National police were included in the military alert. All leaves
and days off were canceled.
   Broadcast reports said soldiers were patrolling cities and towns
from the Amazon jungle area in the south to the Guajira desert
region in the north.
   In the capital of Bogota, a city of 6 million people, jeeps
mounted with machine guns cruised streets and police stopped cars
and searched them for guns and explosives.
   Leftist guerrillas and right-wing death squads have killed
scores of political activists in the last year.
   Two months ago drug traffickers kidnapped Bogota's leading
mayoral candidate, Andres Pastrana, because he had spoken out for
stronger action against the traffickers. Police later freed
Pastrana, the son of former president Misael Pastrana.
   Polls have indicated that Pastrana, the only Conservative Party
candidate, will win.
   The Liberal party mayoral candidates in Bogota are Bernardo
Ossa, who was president Virgilio Barco's emissary for talks with
leftist guerrillas; Juan Caicedo, former president of Colombia's
Federation of Businessmen, and Jorge Eastman, a former Cabinet
minister.
   Newspaper polls indicate that the leading contenders among
lower-class voters are two women.
   One, Maria Eugenia Rojas, running as an independent, is the
daughter of a 1950s military dictator, Gustavo Rojas Pinilla.
   The other woman is Clara Lopez, an independent supported by the
Patriotic Union party, which was formed three years ago by leftist
guerrillas.
   The Patriotic Union's president, Bernardo Jaramillo Ossa,
predicted his party will win 25 mayoral posts.
   In a broadcast interview Saturday with the Colombian radio chain
RCN, he called upon his leftist coalition party ``to overcome fear
and threats'' and go to the polls.
   Right-wing death squads have killed 520 members of the party
since it was formed in 1985 with the help of Colombia's estimated
10,000 leftist guerrillas.
   The government of former president Belisario Betancur, in an
effort to negotiate peace, allowed the rebels to form the party.
Betancur's government also agreed to election of mayors, a goal of
Colombia's leftists.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
