<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Salvador-Bombs     03-12 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Bombs,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Claim Responsibility for Car Bombings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas claimed
responsibility Saturday for detonating two car bombs in a trendy
shopping and restaurant area.
   ``The peace of the rich has ended, the war of the poor has
begun,'' said a communique issued by the Farabundo Marti National
Liberation Front, an alliance of five leftist guerrilla groups that
has been fighting to overthrow El Salvador's U.S.-backed government
for the past eight years.
   Two car bombs went off Friday night in the Pink Zone, a
fashionable neighborhood of sidewalk cafes and restaurants. Two
people were injured.
   The statement said the blasts targeted ``those who daily plan
the repressive campaign against campesinos, those who fly the
helicopters and planes, the diplomats, Marines of the U.S. Embassy,
and the demagogues who design electoral campaigns.''
   The campaigns mentioned referred to legislative and municipal
elections scheduled for March 20.
   ``These individuals have never felt the consequences of misery
and exploitation and, being parasites, much less have felt the
ravages of the dirty war they impose on the humble people. With
this action we intend to make them feel, if only a little, this war
they direct comfortably from afar,'' said the communique.
   An anonymous caller told the radio station YSU where to find the
communique, and a reporter for the station picked it up.
   One of the bombs exploded just a few feet from where leftist
guerrillas killed 13 people, among them six Americans, in a machine
gun attack in June 1985.
   A 12-year-old boy and a middle-aged man were slightly wounded in
the first explosion Friday. The other bomb exploded about five
minutes later in a parking lot behind a Pizza Hut restaurant,
causing no injuries.
   An armed forces spokesman consulted by The Associated Press said
explosives experts were studying the vehicles' remains.
   The conservative daily La Prensa Grafica on Saturday had
attributed the blasts to the Farabundo Marti National Liberation
Front.
   ``The object of these actions ... is to demonstrate that the
terrorists continue attacking the citizenry in an effort to disrupt
the elections,'' said the paper.
   One blast destroyed three vehicles and shattered windows.
   It occurred in front of a restaurant that adjoined the cafe
where four off-duty U.S. Marines and two American businessmen were
killed along with seven Salvadorans in 1985. Leftist guerrillas
claimed responsibility for that attack.
</TEXT>
