<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Gallaudet-President     03-12 0362</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gallaudet-President,340</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deaf College's Trustees To Discuss Selection of New President</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Barriers Broken Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gallaudet University's embattled board of
trustees planned to meet Sunday to discuss picking a new president
for the school for the deaf just days after massive student
protests prompted the hearing person chosen for that post to resign.
   Students at the nation's only liberal arts school for the deaf
said Saturday they hoped the meeting will bring about their demand
for the nation's first deaf university president.
   The university was shut down for five days last week by student
protests after Elisabeth A. Zinser _ who can hear and does not know
sign language _ was appointed by the board last Sunday over two
deaf candidates.
   Faced with student outrage, Zinser stepped down early Friday.
``My decision to resign was reached with great difficulty as I came
to understand how deeply some see the social stature of deaf
persons reflected in the presidency of this university,'' she said
in a statement.
   The two deaf candidates who were bypassed last week are being
reconsidered for the position. They are Harvey J. Corson, 44,
superintendent of the Louisiana School for the Deaf in Baton Rouge
and a Gallaudet board member; and I. King Jordan, 45, dean of
Gallaudet's College of Arts and Sciences. Both are Gallaudet
graduates.
   Students in the Deaf President Now Committee last night asked
for mediation with the board to resolve the students demands:
   ``That a deaf president be appointed from the two finalists;
that board Chairwoman Jane Bassett Spilman resign from the board of
trustees effective immediately; that the bylaws of the board of
trustees be amended to reflect a majority of deaf voting members,
to be achieved within a specific period of time; and that no
reprisals be taken at any time against any student, faculty or
staff member of Gallaudet University.''
   Gallaudet has never had a deaf president in its 124-year
history. The college was founded by Congress in 1864, and became a
university by an act of Congress in 1986.
   The federally supported institution receives 75 percent of its
budget from Congress.
</TEXT>
