<2ND_LINE>AM-Stranded Kids, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0654,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plows Free Children Who Took Refuge at Farms During Blizzard</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf, `All but...' to UPDATE that last child left
Holt farm, driver expected to leave. Picks up 7th graf, `Power
at...'.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Storm Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two busloads of children who had been
snowbound at farms for two nights finally made it home Saturday
when snowplows cleared the roads.
   The 21 children and two bus drivers had taken refuge at the two
homes during a raging snowstorm Thursday afternoon, and had passed
the time playing games and listening to a battery-operated radio.
At one farm, electrical power was off for more than a day and meals
were cooked on a campstove.
   Drivers Linda Barrett and Sharon Grubbs were taking children
home from the Banner County school in Harrisburg when the heavy
snow and winds gusting to 55 mph enveloped their buses, reducing
visibility to zero.
   ``The storm hit a little faster than we thought,'' said Ms.
Grubbs, who was in radio contact with Mrs. Barrett when they
decided to find shelter rather than continue.
   Ms. Grubbs and her eight children wound up at the farm of Jack
and Karen Holt, about 17 miles west of Harrisburg. One of the
maintenance workers who cleared the roads Saturday was the father
of two of the stranded children, Mrs. Holt said.
   All the children left Saturday, including one who had to wait
until her parents, stranded elsewhere by the storm, made it home.
Ms. Grubbs said she would probably drive the school bus home
Saturday night.
   Power at the Holt farm was out from Thursday night until about
7:30 a.m. Saturday. It was about 38 degrees in the house before the
heat came back on.
   ``We're all so thankful for the heat,'' said Mrs. Holt. ``We're
fed and warm and wonderful.'' Power was lost again about 2 p.m.,
but the house was staying warm, she said.
   The two women used a camping stove to cook meals as the
children, ages 7 to 13, huddled under blankets. The three boys and
five girls played games and listened to a battery-operated radio,
Mrs. Holt said.
   ``They've been super for us,'' said Ms. Grubbs, a 10-year
veteran bus driver. ``They've cooperated so well.''
   Mrs. Barrett and her 13 passengers waited out the storm at Agnes
Wynne's farm, about 20 miles from Harrisburg. A snowplow cleared
the road about 3 p.m. Saturday, Mrs. Wynne said.
   Mrs. Wynne, who lives alone, said having so many children on
hand ``was a little trying. But they were a good bunch of kids.''
Worries that she wouldn't have enough food were eased when a a
neighbor brought over buffalo meat, eggs and bread on his
snowmobile.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
