<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BrushFires 4thLd-Writethru a0651 03-12 1002</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brush Fires, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0651,1025</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blaze Appears Under Control, Officials Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf pvs, `The fire...', with 4 grafs to UPDATE with
fire chief quote, detail on mop-up, fire breaks being built. Picks
up 8th graf pvs, `About 265,000. SUBS last 3 grafs, bgng,
`Elsewhere, a...', with 3 grafs to UPDATE with Val Verde County
fire also brought under control. No pickup.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto DN7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVAN RAMSTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major brush fire that destroyed tens of
thousands of acres of West Texas prairie land appeared under
control late Saturday afternoon, officials said.
   For parts of Friday and Saturday, the fire seriously threatened
the towns of Albany and Moran in Shackelford County and Baird in
northern Callahan County, but three tanker airplanes helped contain
it by dropping fire-retardant chemicals.
   At least 265,000 acres were burned, and officials said the dry,
windy weather continued to pose a danger that the fire could
rekindle.
   Sam Logan, public information officer for the Texas Forest
Service, said the grass fires that ravaged much of Shackelford
County and parts of Callahan and Throckmorton counties since
Thursday were under control and the Forest Service was beginning
its mop-up operation.
   ``That'll take about two days,'' Logan said. But he added,
``We'll continue to keep an eye on it, because with the strong
winds and low humidity, just a spark could start it up all over
again.''
   Most of the fires appeared to be interior ones that appear
likely to burn themselves out where they were, officials said.
   ``We've pretty well got fire guards around the complete fire.
Tonight, we're going to just more or less be running a patrol and
mop-up operation,'' said Baird Fire Chief Pat McKennon. ``We will
have Forest Service crews out and some local fire units out, just
more or less patrolling.''
   National Guardsmen and other military personnel used heavy
equipment such as bulldozer and scrapers to build fire breaks.
   ``The idea is to get the grass down real short so that if a fire
jumps a street it doesn't ignite,'' said Airman 1st Class William
Cross from Dyess Air Force Base in Abilene.
   The fire killed livestock, burned trailer homes and oilfield
equipment and closed roads across parts of an area 60 miles long
and 25 miles wide, officials said.
   About 265,000 acres of rangeland had burned in Shackelford
County alone, or roughly half the county, said Joe Fox of the Texas
Forest Service. Albany, a town of about 2,500, is the county seat.
Smaller acreages were burned in the other two affected counties,
officials said.
   At a 3,000-acre ranch south of Albany, workers moved about 100
head of cattle away from the blaze while a U.S. Forest Service
crew, with three bulldozers, fought flames earlier Saturday that
had rekindled in a pasture.
   ``It looks worse at night because that's when you can see the
flames. During the day, the smoke covers everything,'' said Wanda
Sims, a part-owner of the Dyer-Sims Ranch. ``The night before last,
it looked like hot lava moving down the hills.''
   Volunteer firefighter Phillip Rodriguez said he and hundreds of
other workers stopped the flames just inside the city limits of
Baird, a town of about 1,700 people, about 7 a.m. Saturday.
   ``When it was dark, all you could see was orange rolling down
the hills,'' said Rodriguez.
   ``Smoke is drifting across Baird. It is like we are having a big
wienie roast out here,'' said Callahan County Sheriff's Officer Jan
Davis.
   Some homes were evacuated Friday night in the Hannersville
section of Baird and authorities set up a command post, but no
dwellings were lost in the community 21 miles east of Abilene, said
Ms. Davis. Residents returned to their homes Saturday.
   But in Albany, 25 miles north, the fire consumed trailers and
oilfield equipment, and its relentless march eastward earlier in
the day Saturday, fanned by strong winds, had worried authorities.
   ``There's plenty of damage to rangeland, oilfield equipment _
including storage tanks _ and some trailer houses,'' said Albany
Mayor Wayne Hogan. ``We are still trying to get it under wraps
after three days. But it seems to be under better control than this
time yesterday.
   ``But if the wind changes, which it can do real sudden, we're in
trouble again,'' he said.
   In Moran, a town of about 340 people 16 miles southeast of
Albany, Morris Snyder Jr. gazed with neighbors through a smoky haze
at a long bluff a few miles away, pointing toward a line of flames.
   ``This is the worst anyone living here has seen,'' he had said,
before the situation was reported under control. ``It's the worst
anyone can remember.''
   Federal officials, at the request of Texas emergency management
officials, approved aid to help reimburse the state for expenses in
fighting the blaze, which began Thursday from a trash fire.
   Murry Fly, a spokesman for the Texas Forest Service in Lufkin,
said crews arriving from around the state gave tired Forest Service
crews, volunteers and National Guardsmen the chance to rest.
   Numerous firefighters, among hundreds battling the blaze, have
suffered injuries from smoke inhalation and minor burns, said Tom
Millwee of the Division of Emergncy Management.
   An aircraft tanker containing 2,000 gallons of fire retardant
chemical arrived Saturday from the U.S. Forest Service in Fort
Smith, Ark., said Millwee.
   `We are trying to survey the burned area from the air because
you still can't drive through most of it,'' said Hogan, the Albany
mayor. ``We lit backfires last night to protect rural houses just
west of the city limits to stop the flames, advancing from the west
and northwest.''
   Elsewhere, another range fire in Val Verde County, about 300
miles to the southwest, consumed about 60,000 acres before it was
brought under control.
   Mike Scott, a spokesman with the governor's office of emergency
management, said Saturday night that National Guard troops sent to
the area had been released.
   ``There is still apparently some fires down there, but it's
minor,'' Scott said.
</TEXT>
