<DOCNO> AP880312-0174 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 2315EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Burma-Rebels     03-12 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burma-Rebels,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burmese Rebels Call for Federal Union, Deny Drug Involvement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>THREE PAGODA PASS, Burma (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burma's top rebel leaders called
Saturday for a political settlement of the 40-year-old insurgency
and greater autonomy for the country's ethnic minorities.
   Although the rebel's National Democratic Front operates in a
region awash in opium and heroin production, the leaders denied
involvement in drug trafficking. They have been accused of dealing
in drugs to finance their war.
   Democratic Front leaders, in a meeting with journalists in this
Thai-Burmese border town, called on the United States and other
countries to cut support for the regime of President Ne Win.
   Chiefs of the coalition of 10 guerrilla organizations claimed
aircraft provided to Ne Win by the United States to fight the
narcotics trade were being used in military operations against the
insurgents.
   Coalition chairman Saw Mah Reh said the group wanted to
``present its case to the outside world'' and counter government
claims that the insurgency would be crushed within two years.
   He called for peace negotiations to be conducted on neutral
ground with an impartial mediator. Three countries have expressed
interest in the mediation role, he said, but he did not identify
them or elaborate.
   ``The NDP does not want war and desires to end the civil
conflict as soon as feasible,'' he said, calling for a democratic,
multi-party system to replace Ne Win who has presided over
one-party rule since 1962.
   The insurgency began shortly after Burma became independent from
Britain in 1948. Ethnic minorities said the original British
concept of a federal union was changed by central government
leaders.
   Ethnic minority groups represented Saturday were the Mon,
Kachin, Wa, Palaung, Pa-O, Karenni, Arakanese, Lahu and Shan.
   The leaders claimed a rigorous anti-narcotics policy had been
laid down and opium eradication is being pursued.
   They said U.S.-provided helicopters were being used to ferry
troops and ammunition to the battlefield and for medical
evacuation. They also said chemical herbicides provided by the
United States were causing illness among humans and killing
livestock.
   Washington has provided aircraft and herbicides to allow the
Burmese government to spray border areas where opium is grown.
   Knowledgeable Western narcotics sources say that some of the
rebel groups probably are not involved in narcotics trafficking,
but others are instrumental in the flow of opium that is used to
produce heroin.
   The Burmese Communist Party, which also is battling the
government, is regarded by Western diplomats as a major drug
trafficker. The Democratic Front leaders said their ooperations
with the communists were limited to ``military matters.''
   The front claims it has 35,000 guerrillas and they control about
half of the country. Western military analysts say Burma has more
than 250,000 personnel in its military services, police forces and
militias.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880312-0175 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 2349EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-RatPack     03-12 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Rat Pack,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Rat Pack' Rolls Again As Sinatra, Pals Arrive on Eve of National
Tour</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hollywood's fabled ``rat pack,'' Frank
Sinatra, Dean Martin and Sammy Davis Jr., arrived here by private
jetliner Saturday night on the eve of a nostalgic North American
tour.
   Their sold-out show Sunday at the Oakland Coliseum Arena is the
first of 40 performances that the stars will perform through Oct.
1. Promoters are billing it perhaps the last chance to see them
together in concert.
   ``It's all about music, three good friends genuinely enjoying
themselves on stage together,'' said Mort Viner, Martin's manager
and coproducer of the tour, last week. ``They'll probably be having
more fun than the audience.''
   Sinatra, 72, Martin, 70, and Davis, 62, first performed together
in Las Vegas in 1960. They went on to make three movies: ``Ocean's
11,'' ``Sergeants Three,'' and ``Robin and the Seven Hoods.''
   Among the other cities slated to be visited during the tour are
Chicago, Minneapolis, Pittsburgh, Cleveland, Washington, New York,
Los Angeles, Houston, Atlanta, Miami, Philadelphia and Boston.
</TEXT>
