<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Meese-Wallach     03-12 0427</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Wallach,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese and Wallach Briefed Peres on Pipeline in 1985</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III and his
friend, E. Bob Wallach, jointly briefed then-Israeli Prime Minister
Shimon Peres in October 1985 about the status of plans for a $1
billion Iraqi pipeline project, The Washington Post said in
Sunday's editions.
   The newspaper said memos written by Wallach and reviewed by the
Post described Peres as enthusiastic and ``intensely'' interested
in the project when briefed on it at an Israeli Embassy reception.
   Wallach, in the memos, said he had given up hope of getting
enough time to brief Peres, when Meese walked up to them and came
to his rescue, according to the Post.
   Wallach said he had been expecting to meet with Peres on the
afternoon of his Oct. 16, 1985 arrival here to discuss the pipeline
project. Peres' plane, however, arrived 90 minutes late and Peres
went directly to the reception.
   Almost 1,000 guests were waiting, ``a mob scene,'' wrote
Wallach, but he waited for a break and managed to get to Peres and
introduce himself, the Post said.
   ``He (Peres) literally dragged me off into a corner at that
moment and began discussing the project intensely,'' Wallach said.
But then a crush of people built up, led by then-Israeli Ambassador
Meir Rosenne, who wanted Peres to meet various members of Congress.
At that point, Wallach said he gave up and Peres asked him to wait
around until after the reception.
   ``Fortunately, as that time approached, my friend (Wallach's
usual phrase for Meese) arrived and there was a three-way
discussion which took approximately 10 minutes,'' the Post quoted
Wallach as saying. ``He (Peres) is very quick and we went right to
the point and he was agreeable in all respects. It wasn't the kind
of briefing I would have preferred, but it seemed to have been
effective.''
   Wallach said Peres later invited him to meet again in New York a
few days later, and Wallach said he did so, accompanied by a
staffer from the National Security Council who had been assigned to
expedite the pipeline plans and its construction by the Bechtel
Group of San Francisco.
   According to a memo composed by Wallach on Oct. 20, 1985, the
meeting at the Israeli Embassy here was more of a ``briefing'' than
a chat.
   Independent counsel James C. McKay is investigating Meese's role
in the pipeline maneuvering to determine whether Meese might have
violated any laws in concert with Wallach, Swiss financier Bruce
Rappaport, or anyone else.
   The pipeline was never built.
</TEXT>
