<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ShuttleBoosters     03-12 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shuttle Boosters,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Plans to Recommend Building of Government Plant to Build
Boosters</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA plans to recommend to Congress that a
$1.2 billion, government-owned plant be built to make new booster
rockets for the space shuttle, an idea blasted by a senator from
Utah where the boosters are now constructed by Morton Thiokol Inc.,
according to a published report Sunday.
   ``I suspect that this is one of those crazy ideas that was
dreamed up by some empire-building bureaucrat,'' Sen. Jake Garn,
R-Utah, was quoted by The Washington Post as saying. ``In this
current budgetary climate, we shouldn't even be considering this
kind of nonsense.''
   The plan, which calls for a contractor to operate the
booster-building plant, would end Morton Thiokol's monopoly on the
booster manufacturing. The boosters are now built at a plant in
Wasatch, Utah.
   The newspaper cited an unidentified industry source as saying
that Garn has been threatening to hold up space station funding if
the plan isn't blocked.
   Thiokol has dominated the solid rocket industry since 1973, when
it first won the shuttle rocket contract, but the plan by the
National Aeronautics and Space Administration would give other
firms an opportunity to get into the business.
   ``After the space station, this is the biggest initiative we've
got going,'' said Russ Bardos, director of NASA solid propulsion
systems. ``Whoever wins this will be the biggest (rocket)
propellant producer in the country.''
   The proposal already has aroused the interest of four rival
companies, the Post said, identifying them as United Technologies
Corp., Aerojet General Corp.; Atlantic Research Corp. and Hercules
Inc.
</TEXT>
