<HEAD>National Guard Plane Crashes, But Pilot Escapes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Florida Air National Guard F-16
fighter crashed Friday in woods, causing its cannon shells to
explode, but the pilot parachuted 2,000 feet to safety, officials
said.
   Lt. Col. Levis DeWeese of Jacksonville told officials the engine
of the $14 million Fighting Falcon stopped. When he couldn't
restart it, DeWeese said, he steered the plane to an unpopulated
area and bailed out.
   DeWeese, 50, suffered minor injuries.
   The crash occurred about 10 a.m. two miles south of Callahan,
said Lt. Col. Durham Searcy, with the Air National Guard at
Jacksonville International Airport.
   The crash touched off a small brush fire. The plane, with the
125th Fighter Group, was armed with 20mm cannon rounds, and the
fire and crash caused them to explode, said Lt. Col. Reubin Owens,
on-scene commander.
   DeWeese was returning from a training mission over the Atlantic
Ocean.
