<HEAD>Moss Declares Candidacy Against Hatch in Utah</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Brian Moss on Friday declared his
candidacy for the U.S. Senate against incumbent Sen. Orrin Hatch _
the man who defeated Moss' father for the seat in 1976.
   The 43-year-old son of former three-term Sen. Frank Moss made
his announcement during a spirited student assembly at Granite High
School, where his grandfather was the first principal.
   Moss, who holds a degree in economics, is a travel agent and
part-owner and manager of several sandwich shops. Although his
Republican opponent is leading 2-1 in recent polls on his bid for a
third term, Moss said Utah senatorial races are sometimes
unpredictable, citing his father's surprise defeat 12 years ago by
Hatch.
   Moss said if elected he would use the office of senator to
attract more industry to the state and to eliminate foreign trade
barriers now preventing local farmers and industries from selling
products abroad. He also would like foreign economic competitors to
pay for more of their own military defense.
   Moss denounced President Reagan's ``trickle-down economics,''
saying, ``You do not start building from the roof, you start from
the foundation.''
