<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FlagDispute 1stLd-Writethru a0713 03-12 0650</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Flag Dispute, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0713,0664</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Attorneys Seek Dismissal Of Charges In Confederate Flag Case</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUB last graf with three grafs comment from school officials.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAY REEVES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the Alabama NAACP and
13 other black lawmakers asked a judge Friday to dismiss
trespassing charges stemming from their bid to remove the
Confederate battle flag from the Capitol dome.
   Defense attorneys invoked claims of legislative immunity from
such misdemeanor charges and said state historians, not Republican
Gov. Guy Hunt, had jurisdiction to order any arrests while the
Capitol is being renovated.
   Prosecutors did not comment on the defense claims at the brief
hearing before District Judge Craig Miller, who withheld a ruling
pending the filing of further briefs.
   Thomas Reed, a lawmaker and state president of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, vowed for weeks
to remove the flag on Feb. 2 after the legislature opened. The feat
would require climbing an 8-foot chain-link fence, entering the
locked building, climbing an inner stairwell to the white dome and
taking the banner off a staff.
   Hunt had said anyone who made such an attempt would be arrested.
   Minutes after the Legislature's opening gavel, state police
pulled down Reed and others as they made at least symbolic efforts
to scale the fence. They nevergot near the building and the flag
still flies atop the Capitol dome.
   Each lawmaker was charged with second-degree criminal
trespassing and released from the county jail on $300 bond.
Conviction on the misdemeanor count carries a maximum penalty of
three months in jail and a $500 fine.
   Defense attorney Fred Gray said the legislators cannot be
prosecuted for their attempt to climb the fence because the Alabama
Constitution provides immunity from arrest to lawmakers while the
Legislature is in session.
   The trespassing charges should be dropped because no entry was
made and the Capitol is public property, he said.
   Gray also told Miller that Hunt did not have the power to order
the arrests because the Capitol is under the control of the Alabama
Historical Commission while it is being renovated.
   The NAACP says the flag is a racist symbol of oppression and
slavery. Hunt, who has said the Legislature must decide whether to
remove the flag, has said many view the banner as a historical
symbol of the Old South.
   Despite Gray's arguments, Hunt is standing by his decision to
have the lawmakers arrested, said his press secretary, Terry Abbott.
   ``Our legal research showed that the governor is actually in
charge of very distinct parts of the Capitol,'' Abbott said. ``Most
parts of the Capitol, excluding the floor controlled by the
Legislature ... did fall to the governor.''
   In another case Friday involving the Confederate flag, three bus
drivers in Durham, N.C., said they were fired and at least a dozen
students were sent home after they arrived at school wearing the
flags.
   When some of the Chewing Juniuor High School students and
drivers later gathered at a store near the school, police set up a
roadblock, but they would not say why.
   Alesia Keith, 22, who has driven a school bus for the Durham
County schools for three years, said she had the Confederate flag
tucked into her back pocket Friday as a show of pride, not of
racism. One of the drivers fired was black.
   ``This is Southern Pride Day,'' Ms. Keith said. ``They can take
my job and my money, but they can't take my pride.''
   Schools spokeswoman Alisa Terry said the students were dismissed
for the day because their clothing was considered disruptive.
   ``Administrators are meeting and will discuss with parents what
kind of long-term action will be taken,'' she said.
   She also said no final decision had been made on the status of
the three bus drivers, although they, too, were sent home for the
day.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
