<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-School     03-12 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-School,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissidents Announce Formation of Independent University</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of dissidents announced Friday the
formation of a small, independent ``university'' with Western
teaching methods to give students an alternative to state-supported
Soviet higher education.
   Lev Timofeyev, a former political prisoner who heads the
unofficial group Press Club Glasnost, said establishment of the
school has not been approved by officials, but he said formal
permission was unnecessary.
   The enrollment will be limited to 70 students. They will begin
English-language training April 1, and an academic year that will
begin in October, Timofeyev said.
   The organizers plan to hold classes in apartments and will not
charge tuition, Timofeyev said. Organizers hope to compensate the
faculty with donations from the West.
   He said the roughly 50 students registered in Moscow and 19 in
Leningrad will be taught by dissidents who have advanced degrees in
physics, mathematics, language, literature and theology.
   But the school, called Moscow Independent University, also hopes
to use Western books and have instruction by Western professors,
either on videotape or in person, he said.
   A member of the group, Valery Soifer, said it already had
agreements for assistance from Long Island University in New York,
Hebrew University in Jerusalem and several French universities.
   Timofeyev is to act as the school's president.
   Glasnost is Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of
greater openness on selected subjects.
</TEXT>
