<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 0550EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-Quebec     03-12 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Quebec,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Cabinet Minister's Diary Questions Response To 1970 Crisis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Prime Minister Pierre Elliott Trudeau may
not have had grounds for imposing the War Measures Act in October
1970 to deal with Quebec separatists, according to the diary of a
late Cabinet minister.
   The sweeping powers given police by the act led to the arrests
and detention of more than 460 civilians in Quebec. Only 62 were
ever charged and 18 were convicted.
   Trudeau justified his action by saying an insurrection was
taking place in Quebec, a predominantly French-speaking province,
and police lacked the power to suppress it.
   A diary left by former Transport Minister Don Jamieson, who died
in 1986, said two days after Trudeau acted, the Cabinet was told
police had no evidence of an insurrection _ no firearms, ammunition
or explosives.
   Portions of the diary were published Friday by the Toronto
magazine Saturday Night.
   Jamieson's notations marked the first time in 18 years the
official version of events was questioned by a person who was in
the government at the time.
   Trudeau, stopped on a street by a reporter and asked about
Jamieson's conclusions, said, ``Look, I don't want to talk to the
media for God's sake. Read your history.''
   The October crisis began when guerrillas of the Quebec
Liberation Front kidnapped British Trade Commissioner James Cross
and Quebec Labor Minister Pierre Laporte. Cross was freed after two
months but Laporte was killed.
   Jamieson wrote that in his view, Trudeau used the War Measures
Act to assert federal power, not halt an insurrection.
   ``I am satisfied that from the very moment when Cross was
abducted the prime minister saw the incident as an issue on which
we (the Liberal Party government) would stand or fall and through
which he might very well be able to assert the federal position in
a dramatic manner,'' Jamieson wrote.
   Truedeau retired in 1984 and an election returned the
Conservative Party to take over the federal government.
   The separatist movement subsided in Quebec after voters rejected
a 1980 referendum on the issue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880312-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 0550EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Bolivia-Cocaine     03-12 0357</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bolivia-Cocaine,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Fund to Help Miners Who Crossed the Andes to Grow Coca</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER MCFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least half of the 600 jobless miners
who crossed the Andes on foot last week to grow coca will be
relocated by the Save the Children organization, it was announced
Friday.
   The miners, many with their families, arrived in the tropical
town of Chulumani 50 miles east of La Paz over the weekend and said
they would grow coca leaves unless the government provided them
with jobs.
   Bruce Harris, director in Bolivia of the Westport, Conn.-based
Save the Children aid program, said arrangements have been made for
at least 300 of the miners and their families to relocate in the
town of Circuata, 30 miles east of Chulumani, where they will be
encouraged to cultivate coffee, citrus plants and bananas.
   He said Circuata residents have agreed to make land available,
the government will assist with building houses and Save the
Children will provide seeds, technical assistence and credits.
   The humid area around Chululmani has been an important coca-leaf
producing zone for generations. A paste is made from the leaves and
then refined into cocaine.
   Since 1985, more than 21,000 employees in the mining work force
of 27,000 have lost their jobs as the government closed 14 of 21
government-owned mines because of the collapse of the tin market
and deficits by the state mining company.
   The government has provided temporary jobs for 6,000 unemployed
miners with funds provided by the United Nations and some European
governments.
   Other jobless miners are living in tent cities on the outskirts
of La Paz or have gone to tropical zones to farm. Coca leaves are a
major cash product in this impoverished country with a population
of 6.4 million.
   ``The reason for our presence in Chulumani is very simple: We
are demanding from the government a solution to our problem,''
Augusto Leon, the leader of a group of miners, said last week.
``All options for finding jobs are closed to us. We have nowhere to
live ... so we have adopted this political decision.''
</TEXT>
