<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BurkinaFaso     03-12 0401</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burkina Faso,0412</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Burkina Faso President Welcomes Foreign Interests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCO WERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Blaise Compaore of Burkina
Faso outlined his government's new program Friday and made it clear
that he will give business and foreign interests a warmer welcome
than his predecessor did.
   In a radio broadcast monitored in Abidjan, Compaore said that
with Burkina Faso's ``limited resources, the state alone cannot
pretend to do anything.''
   Compaore led the Oct. 15 coup in which President Thomas Sankara
was killed. It was the fifth coup in the poor West African nation
of 7.5 million since Burkina Faso _ formerly Upper Volta _ won
independence from France in 1960. Both men were army captains and
Compaore was a close aide of Sankara's.
   Sankara had antagonized business people and Western governments
and creditors with his policies and statements attacking Western
imperialism.
   Compaore said Friday his government will work with national,
foreign and private sectors, an apparent reference to his efforts
to improve government relations with national trade unions,
commercial interests and foreign neigbors.
   The new program, published later Friday in the official daily
Sidwaya newspaper, pledged to continue some economic reforms begun
under Sankara.
   The program called for a ``reinforcement of industrial
production and the rehabilitation of factories that are underused
or currently dormant.''
   The plan pledged to ``enlarge and reinforce democracy.'' Its
most striking change was abolition of Sankara's feared
Revolutionary Defense Committees in favor of smaller organizations
with a social and cultural focus. The organizations would be
separate groups of rural peasants, blue collar workers, youth,
civil servants, women and the elderly.
   Compaore avoided offending elements sympathetic to Sankara.
Without directly naming Sankara, he noted his speech borrowed ideas
from the political program Sankara laid out in a 1983 speech made
shortly after taking power.
   Compaore's foreign relations program was more moderate than the
radical policies of Sankara, which criticized France's Africa
policy and its involvement in Chad. The Sankara program troubled
many of Burkina Faso's neighbors, whose relations with Libyan
leader Moammar Gadhafi have been strained.
   Compaore said his program was drawn up after a review of the
four years of Sankara's government. He offered no direct criticism
of Sankara and only briefly referred to his seizure of power as a
``rectification process.''
   Compaore also pledged to continue the government crackdown on
corruption and laziness begun when Sankara took power in 1983.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880312-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 0552EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-France-Syringe     03-12 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-France-Syringe,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Testing Single-Use Syringes To Help Stop AIDS</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLOIRES, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States has begun testing two
types of single-use syringes to help stop the spread of AIDS and
hepatitis transmitted by contaminated needles, an American official
said Friday.
   Alan Woods, administrator of the U.S. Agency for International
Development, announced the disposible syringe tests at an
international conference of doctors and health experts.
   Woods declined to say how much money the United States was
spending on developing the syringes, but he said they could be on
the market by the end of the year.
   Unlike other disposible syringes already in use, neither of the
two new types can be reused, Woods said.
   He said they are being tested by the Program for Appropriate
Technology in Health, a Seattle-based company, under contract to
the government. Woods did not provide details on the tests at the
conference on immunization and children's health.
   Woods said several other countries also are testing pre-filled,
single-use syringes, including France and Switzerland.
   ``When they are ready, we will have to flood the market with
these devices,'' said Dr. William Foege, director of the Task Force
for Child Survival, the conference sponsor.
   ``We will have to find some way of subsidizing the cost to get
them to developing countries because they'll be too expensive at
first. And we'll have to find some way to get the old syringes off
the market,'' said Foege, former director of the Centers for
Disease Control in Atlanta, Ga.
   Contaminated needles are responsible for the spread of a number
of diseases in developing countries and are a particular threat to
young children receiving vaccine injections.
   Needles contaminated with the HIV virus are believed to be a
major method of transmitting AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency
syndrome, the fatal disease that attacks the body's immune system
leaving it vulnerable to cancers and other diseases.
   AIDS can be transmitted by sex, intravenous drug use, blood
transfusion and from infected pregnant mothers to fetuses.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
