<HEAD>Dead Stowaway Found On Banana Boat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An apparent stowaway was found dead Friday in the
cargo hold of a banana boat on which seven other men had hidden in
hopes of getting into the country, authorities said.
   Four of the stowaways were caught Thursday, and three more came
out of hiding and were caught trying to run away Friday when a
workman unloading Colombian bananas from the freighter discovered
the body, authorities said.
   A carton of bananas, apparently fallen from a stack, lay across
the body.
   James Wright, a spokesman for the Metro-Dade police, would not
speculate on the cause of death and said an autopsy scheduled for
Saturday.
   Joe Livingston, who found the body, said it appeared the man had
been hiding in a small floor space cleared by moving cartons aside.
   The seven stowaways were in Immigration and Naturalization
Service custody. George Waldroup, an INS spokesman, said seven are
believed to be Colombian. The nationality of the dead man was not
immediately known.
   The British-registered Castaneda calls at the Port of Miami
every 11 days, officials said. It arrived after a five-day voyage
from Santa Maria, Colombia.
</TEXT>
