<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Editor     03-12 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Editor,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Editor In Court Over ``Secret Document''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Andreas Whittam Smith, editor of The Independent
newspaper, appeared at a hearing in the Old Bailey Central Criminal
Court on Friday over alleged possession of a secret document on the
fight against terrorism.
   The hearing before Judge Aron Owen was closed but Whittam Smith
told reporters his newspaper was accused of having a document
obtained in violation of the Official Secrets Act.
   ``We shall argue against that most strongly,'' he said after the
case was adjourned to next week.
   A story in his paper Thursday described proposals in a ``draft
confidential report'' on how information would be built up by the
12 European governments in a data base to keep track of extremists
across frontiers.
   It said the British were unenthusiastic about the idea because
of reluctance to endanger informants and surveillance methods.
   The interior ministers of the 12 governments involved are known
as the Trevi group, after the Italian town where their first
meeting was held in 1976.
   The story did not say how the document was obtained. A police
order served on The Independent to surrender the document said it
concerned a meeting of the Trevi group in Brussels last January.
   Press and public were excluded from the Old Bailey hearing at
the request of government law officers.
   Whittam Smith said his daily's attorney, Desmond Brown, had
argued that the 1911 Official Secrets Act could not apply to a
document obtained outside Britain and one that was held by all 12
members in the Trevi agreement.
   Under the act, unauthorized release of government information is
illegal.
   The Independent story by its domestic affairs correspondent,
Sarah Helm, said the killing of three Irish Republican Army members
by British security agents in Gibraltar last Monday ``is seen as
firm proof that intercountry cooperation promoted by Trevi is
working.''
</TEXT>
