<HEAD>Report Syrians Arrest Palestinian Official.
^Eds: Name Salah Salah is cq.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salah Salah, a leader of one of the
factions in the Palestine Liberation Organization, was detained by
Syrian troops stationed along the Lebanese-Syrian border, police
sources said Friday.
   The sources, speaking with the condition they not be identified,
said Salah was seized Monday as his chauffeur-driven car arrived at
the Masnaa border post.
   They said Salah's Palestinian driver was released but Salah was
taken away and they had no information about his whereabouts.
   Salah, 48, is a Politburo member of George Habash's Marxist
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine _ PFLP. Neither PFLP
nor PLO officials would comment on the police report.
   Salah had played an active role in gaining the release March 1
of two United Nations relief officials, a Swede and a Norwegian,
who had been kidnapped and held captive by Moslem militants for 25
days.
   The police sources said they did not know if Salah's detention
was linked to his mediation to free the Scandinavians.
   They said Salah was en route to the PFLP headquarters in
Damascus, the Syrian capital, when he was seized by the soldiers.
   Syria has 25,000 military personnel in northern and eastern
Lebanon under a 1976 peacekeeping mandate issued by the Arab League
because of the civil war between Lebanese Moslem and Christian
militias.
   Damascus has supported rebels opposed to PLO chief Yasser Arafat
since 1983. The PFLP has maintained good relations with the Syrian
government even after a reconciliation last year with Arafat.
