<HEAD>Argentina Asks for U.N. Meeting on Britain's Falkland Maneuvers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Argentina asked Friday for a U.N. Security
Council meeting on British military maneuvers under way near the
disputed Falkland Islands, a spokesman for the Argentine mission to
the United Nations said.
   Ambassador Marcelo E.R. Delpech made the request at a meeting
with the president of the council, Yugoslav Ambassador Dragoslav
Pejic, according to the spokesman.
   The Falklands are a British colony, but Argentina maintains its
claim to the islands 500 miles off the Argentine coast based on
settlers dating from the early 1880s.
   In 1982, Argentine forces invaded and captured the islands, but
they were defeated by a British task force in a 74-day war.
   Argentina has denounced the British military exercises as a
provocation and put its armed forces on alert.
   The Organization of American States expressed concern and called
on both countries to resume negotiations over the the islands,
known in Argentina as the Malvinas.
   Ricardo Ernesto Lagorio, a spokesman for Argentina's U.N.
mission, said the Security Council was expected to hold
consultations next week to decide how to approach the issue.
