from power.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Independent counsel Lawrence E. Walsh says the
guilty plea and promise of cooperation from former national
security adviser Robert C. McFarlane will help advance his
investigation of the Iran-Contra affair.
   McFarlane's plea ``furthers the work of the Office of
Independent Counsel because he has agreed to cooperate fully'' in
the investigation, Walsh said Friday following the former national
security adviser's arraignment in U.S. District Court.
   McFarlane pleaded guilty to four misdemeanor charges of
withholding information from Congress by falsely assuring lawmakers
that members of his staff, specifically Lt. Col. Oliver L. North,
were not involved in private efforts to arm the Nicaraguan rebels
during a statutory ban on direct U.S. aid to the Contras.
