   Kansas Sen. Bob Dole, acknowledging that ``we're hanging by our
fingernails,'' announced Friday he has purchased 30 minutes of
television time tonight and he challenged Bush to join him ``to
discuss the issues.''
   The vice president rejected a one-on-one debate with Dole.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The administration has reluctantly ordered the
closing of the PLO observer mission at the United Nations because
of a law Secretary of State George P. Shultz called ``one of the
dumber things that Congress has done lately.''
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III gave the Palestine Liberation
Organization mission in New York until March 21 to close, saying
the department would then go to federal court to enforce the
Anti-Terrorism Act of 1987.
   The 1947 treaty under which New York became U.N. headquarters
obliges the United States to let all accredited missions operate,
U.N. officials and the State Department have said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The woman who resigned as head of Gallaudet
University after angry student protests says officials didn't
foresee that having a deaf president would become ``a national
civil rights matter.''
   Elisabeth Ann Zinser, who can hear and does not know sign
language, said a week of outcry over her appointment at the school
for the deaf made her see that deaf people as a group must ``take
their place in society and this had become the time.''
   ``I have responded to this extraordinary social movement of deaf
people, not to the demands of the students and protesters,'' she
said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army barred worshipers from three mosques
in Gaza City on the Moslem holy day in an attempt to keep order,
but Israeli soldiers wounded nine Arabs in protests after prayer
services in the occupied lands.
   Troops razed four Palestinian homes to punish suspects in the
attempted lynching of a collaborator and the knifing of a Jewish
settler.
   On orders from the Palestine Liberation Organization, 250
Palestinian policemen resigned, half of the police force in the
West Bank.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of protesters vowed to maintain a
three-day vigil outside President Kurt Waldheim's office, demanding
that he resign over his questionable World War II service in the
German army.
   They were among 300 demonstrators outside the imperial Hofburg
Palace on Friday, the 50th anniversary of Austria's annexation by
Nazi Germany. They carried a banner reading, ``Who Will Make
Waldheim Resign?''
   Organizers planned another protest this afternoon against
Waldheim, who had concealed his role as a German army lieutenant in
the Balkans until it was disclosed in the media in March 1986.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former top aide to Gov. Evan Mecham
acknowledged that he told the governor an alleged death threat by a
state official was a ``frivolous matter'' Mecham should forget
about.
   Max Hawkins, former head of the Department of Administration,
testified Friday at the Republican governor's impeachment trial
that he thought the alleged threat was ``a matter that would
probably go away by itself.''
   Mecham is accused of trying to thwart the attorney general's
investigation of the threat, allegedly made against a witness
testifying before a state grand jury that was investigating the
governor's campaign finances.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Rep. Mario Biaggi could have helped Wedtech
Corp. for free, but chose to help plunder millions of dollars from
the Bronx defense contractor, a prosecutor told jurors in the
congressman's racketeering trial.
   ``The crime is not what the congressman did. The crime is that
he was paid for what he did, the extortion and bribes,'' Howard
Wilson, an assistant U.S. attorney, said Friday in U.S. District
Court.
   Wilson's opening statement to jurors hearing the case of Biaggi
and six co-defendants outlined how ``a little company in the
Bronx'' was turned into ``an enterprise that was to be plundered,
to be used by the people on trial here.''
</TEXT>
