<1ST_LINE>a i AM-Lebanon-Election Adv18   03-12 0813</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Election, Adv 18,0838</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, March 18 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Chaotic Lebanon Has Presidential Election Coming Up</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SAMIR F. GHATTAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Even with all its sectarian strife and
economic chaos, Lebanon is preparing for a presidential election in
July and the signs now point to more disruption and division.
   By tradition, the presidency has been set aside for Lebanon's
Christians while the posts of prime minister and Parliament speaker
have gone to Moslems. This year, however, some leading Moslems have
begun laying claim to the presidency as well.
   An array of Christian politicians, ambassadors, exiles, former
security and intelligence chiefs, the army commander and militia
chieftains are possible candidates to succeed President Amin
Gemayel, a 45-year-old Maronite Catholic, when his six-year term
expires Sept. 22.
   No Moslems have yet to step forward as candidates, but some
influential Moslem factions are making it plain they believe the
presidential post should be theirs.
   With Lebanon dismembered by the 13-year-old civil war, Gemayel
has become politically powerless; his authority is confined to a
shrunken Christian enclave. He is constitutionally barred from
running for a second term.
   Finding a successor acceptable to all sides promises to be a
monumental task. To a large extent, that includes being acceptable
to Syria and Israel, the two key outside players in Lebanon.
   Gemayel torpedoed a Syrian-arranged peace treaty between rival
Moslem and Christian militia leaders in December 1985 and Syria now
is expected to want someone more to its liking. Syria, which has
troops in Lebanon, is heavily influential among Sunni and Shiite
Moslems.
   But hardline Christians, such as Samir Geagea, leader of the
Lebanese Forces, the Christians' main militia, are not expected to
go along with anyone Syria wants.
   A Lebanese Forces spokesman, Georges Abdel Massih, told The
Associated Press the militia ``will block the election of a
president imposed by Syria ... with political pressure and even
military pressure.''
   ``We want a president who can liberate Lebanon, then unite it,''
Geagea has said. ``We're tired of intervention that has no limits
and we will not let foreigners play a role in presidential
elections.''
   Gemayel was hastily elected president after his younger brother,
Bashir, was killed in a September 1982 bombing nine days before he
was due to be sworn in as president.
   Under an unwritten convention dating from Lebanon's independence
from France in 1943, the president is traditionally a Maronite
Catholic, the prime minister a Sunni Moslem and the Parliament
speaker a Shiite Moslem.
   When that pact was made, the Christians were deemed to be the
majority sect by a pre-independence census. But now the 1.2 million
Shiites are the biggest single group. Christians, whose ranks have
been depleted by those who have fled the country, now number about
900,000.
   With Syria's backing, the Shiites are now demanding political
equality, and some even want one of their own as president.
   Christians like Geagea refuse to surrender the presidency,
however.
   Pro-Iranian Shiite fundamentalists are even another matter,
since they seek to establish an Iranian-style Islamic republic in
Lebanon.
   So far, only one candidate has announced officially for the
presidential race. He is Dany Chamoun, a former Christian militia
leader, leader of the National Liberal Party and son of the late
Camille Chamoun, a former president.
   Chamoun has said he opposes partition of Lebanon and favors a
secular state, free of all foreign forces, like the 25,000 Syrian
troops in north and east Lebanon and Moslem west Beirut, and the
Israelis who remain in a southern border strip.
   Iran has about 3,000 of Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini's
Revolutionary Guards in east Lebanon and thousands of Palestinian
fighters are in Lebanese refugee camps.
   Unannounced but likely Christian candidates are Raimond Edde, a
veteran politician in self-exile in France since 1976 following two
assassination attempts, and Suleiman Franjieh, a Maronite who was
president when the civil war erupted.
   Still other possible Christian candidates are Lebanon's
ambassador to France, Farouk Abi Lamaa, a former security chief;
and the envoy to Switzerland, Johnny Abdo, a former military
intelligence chief.
   Other Christians mentioned are Gen. Michel Aoun, the army
commander who once was a Gemayel loyalist; the millionaire
businessmen Manuel Younes, and Henri Sfeir.
   Elie Hobeika, the ousted pro-Syrian leader of the Lebanese
Forces, and former Gemayel aide Jean Obeid, who was kidnapped in
Beirut for several days last year, are considered outside
possibilities. Both also are Christians.
   On the Moslem side, the maneuvering is much less in the open.
   Nonetheless, Justice Minister Nabih Berri, leader of the
Syrian-backed Shiite Amal militia, has declared Lebanon should have
a Shiite president, although he has not put himself forward.
   Leaflets distributed in west Beirut call for the installation of
Sheik Mohammed Hussein Fadlallah, spiritual leader of the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God, to head an Islamic
republic.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri AMs, March 18</NOTE>
</DOC>
