<NOTE>$adv 13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions March 12-13</NOTE>
<HEAD>1988 Shaping Up To Be A Better Year For `Munis'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It probably won't go down as the year of the
``muni,'' but experts say 1988 also isn't expected to mirror last
year's disastrous performance for the municipal bond market.
   The volume of issues from state and local governments totaled
$14.4 billion during the first two months of this year, down from
$16.5 billion a year ago, but still one of the best starts on
record, according to Securities Data Co.-Bond Buyer, which tracks
the municipal market.
   Although 1987 started out on a positive note, rising interest
rates put a damper on activity later in the year, sharply
curtailing volume and bringing about a severe decline in the value
of many municipal bond funds.
   Analysts say a drop in interest rates after the stock market
crash in October helped lure some borrowers back to the muni market.
   Neal Attermann, municipal research director of Kidder Peabody,
called the early data on the muni market was both ``helpful and
misleading.''
   ``It's a helpful indicator in that ... bonds are coming to
market despite restrictions'' resulting from the 1986 tax bill, he
said. Tax reform generally reduced the attractiveness of municipal
bond returns and also restricted use of the bonds.
   But he cautioned that ``1988 won't be a large year of issuance.''
   George Friedlander, a municipal bond analyst for Smith Barney,
Upham & Co., agreed. ``The data (for January and February) isn't so
great. On an annualized basis it comes out to $92 bilion a year.
That's a moderate supply.''
   Still, Atterman noted an early drop in the percentage of
refundings, or bond issues sold in order to retire older securities
usually to take advantage of lower rates.
   ``That's a very encouraging sign. That means that rather than
being tied to interest rates we have a lot of volume independent of
interest rates,'' he said.
   While market experts aren't predicting a banner year for the
municipal market, most aren't forecasting a replay of 1987 even
though the outlook for interest rates remains cloudy.
   Atterman notes that many changes could occur in the municipal
market following the presidential election, especially as demand
for a reduction in the budget deficit persists.
   ``That could result in a further restriction in tax-exempt
bonds,'' he said, adding that bond prices could rise on that
anticipation.
   So far this year, most of the munis sold were general purpose,
followed by education, utilities, health, transportation, water,
sewer and gas, housing, airports, student loans and solid waste
recovery, according to Securities Data.
   The largest issue in January, it said, came from the Municipal
Electric Authority of Georgia, which sold $488.7 million of special
obligation refunding bonds. In February, the largest was $450
million of New York City general obligation bonds; and in March,
$404.75 million of power system revenue refunding bonds, Securities
data said.
   An overwhelming number of the bonds were tax exempt, it said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions March 12-13</NOTE>
