<1ST_LINE>d f PM-EconomyRdp     03-12 0347</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prices Down; Retail Sales Mixed; Markets Rally</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A government report showing lower inflation has soothed anxiety
in the bond market and helped ease interest rates, but some
economists say other figures suggesting weak retail sales raise the
possibility of a recession.
   The Labor Department said Friday its index that measures
wholesale prices fell 0.2 percent in February, reflecting a decline
in food and energy costs. This partly erased a 0.4 percent rise in
January and provided evidence that inflation remains under control.
   For the first two months of 1988, wholesale prices have been
increasing at an annual rate of 1.1 percent _ half of last year's
2.2 percent rise.
   The news cheered the bond market, which is highly sensitive to
evidence of inflation because rising prices erode the value of
fixed-income investments.
   The Treasury's key 30-year issue rose about $6.50 per $1,000 in
face amount. Its yield, which moves inversely to price and is a
signal of interest rate trends, fell to 8.50 percent from 8.55
percent late Thursday.
   Stocks also benefited. On Wall Street, the Dow Jones average of
30 industrials, which took its sharpest drop in nearly two months
Thursday with a 48.24 point loss, closed Friday with a gain of 8.95
at 2,034.98.
   Broader market indices also rose, and the Wilshire 5,000
Equities Index measuring the value of all U.S. stocks rose by
nearly $6 billion.
   A separate report by the Commerce Department showed retail sales
rose 0.6 percent in February, largely because of strong demand for
autos, but economists were more concerned with a sharp downward
revision in January sales.
   Instead of a 0.5 percent rise in January sales reported earlier,
the government said sales fell 0.2 percent, evidence that consumer
buying is much weaker than previously believed.
   This change was considered significant because consumer buying
is a crucial element in economic growth, and a significant slowdown
could slide the country into recession.
   Many economists fear that consumers have been reluctant to spend
money since the October stock market collapse and have been saving
instead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880312-0214 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-12-88 0604EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-OilPrices     03-12 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Continue Rising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices closed out the week on the upswing,
but analysts are not sure how substantial the rally really is.
   After two days of slight gains, oil prices jumped strongly
higher Thursday, as traders anticipated production-cutting moves by
world producers. The advance continued Friday but was hampered by
continuous profit-taking, analysts said.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for April
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark U.S. crude oil,
closed 29 cents higher at $16.29 per 42-gallon barrel. On Thursday,
the contract leaped 51 cents _ topping combined gains Tuesday and
Wednesday of 12 cents.
   Refined products also built on Thursday's strong advance.
Wholesale heating oil settled at 44.69 cents a gallon, up 0.76 cent
after Thursday's 0.90 cent gain. Wholesale unleaded gasoline closed
at 45.59 cents a gallon, up 0.45 cent after leaping 1.14 cents the
day before.
   Bob Baker, an analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc., said
Friday's move reflected ``a growing confidence that, by whatever
means it might take, our oil-exporting friends will contain the
discounting and get prices moving up.''
   At the Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. securities firm, however,
analyst Jayne Ball was less certain.
   ``At this point, it's unclear whether this is just a technical
correction ... or whether it's a serious recovery,'' she said.
   Analysts generally attributed Thursday's advance to market
sentiment that worried OPEC and non-member countries were
attempting to find ways to boost oil prices that had severely
eroded since late last year.
   By early this week, sluggish demand and growing surpluses,
together with discounting by members of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries, had driven prices to levels between
$13 and $14 a barrel in the Persian Gulf _ far short of OPEC's $18
target _ and to $15.37 per barrel on the New York Merc, $2 to $3
cheaper than January levels.
   No hard news moved Friday's market. But Baker said traders were
turning bullish, ``looking for behind-the-scenes action we don't
know about'' on the part of the producers.
   Ms. Ball, however, was less enthusiastic.
   Noting that crude prices continued to gain ground in Friday's
session, she said product prices did not ``put in all that good a
showing.''
   This reflected uncertainty within the market about the strength
of the latest advance, she suggested.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
